<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safeway To Pay Fine for Dumping Milk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Safeway has agreed to pay $200,000 in civil  
penalties for dumping thousands of gallons of spoiled milk into 
Northern California storm drains in 1996, federal authorities said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalty settles a civil suit, filed Thursday by the  
government, accusing the supermarket chain of numerous violations 
of the Clean Water Act, said U.S. Attorney Robert Mueller's office. 
</P>
<P>
	After an error at a milk plant in March 1996 made the milk  
unacceptable for sale, more than 10,500 gallons of milk products 
were dumped by 24 Safeway and Pak'n Save stores into drains that 
led to surface waters, government lawyers said in the suit filed in 
U.S. District Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The waterways included San Francisco Bay, the Petaluma River and  
other bay tributaries, the suit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people reported seeing ``milky'' creeks, and others saw  
store employees pouring milk into storm drains, Mueller's office 
said. It said company headquarters had ordered store managers to 
get rid of the possibly contaminated milk, but didn't tell them how 
to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	Milk can harm the aquatic environment because microorganisms in  
the milk use up oxygen as they degrade, the suit said. It said 
Safeway did not have a permit to discharge pollutants and had not 
treated the products to remove their harmful effects. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed at the request of the Environmental  
Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials could not be reached for comment after business hours  
at Safeway headquarters in Pleasanton. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
