<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Retracts Hewlett-Packard Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency  
has withdrawn a settlement with Hewlett-Packard Co. over inkjet 
printer chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corvallis Gazette-Times reported that the deal was nixed  
partly because the world's second-largest computer maker refused to 
permit an audit of its records. 
</P>
<P>
	Sylvia Lowrance, an EPA enforcement adminstrator, said the order  
had to be revised because of issues raised by an agency board 
reviewing the settlement and new concerns that have come to the 
agency's attention. 
</P>
<P>
	A Hewlett-Packard spokeswoman said the deal was withdrawn  
because the two sides simply failed to agree on details for a 
government audit of the company's chemical records at its U.S. 
manufacturing plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement about audits is a component of that settlement  
agreement,'' Marcy Eastham said. ``Our negotiations with EPA have 
continued to be positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The development is the latest twist in the Palo Alto,  
Calif.,-based company's dispute with federal regulators over 
alleged environmental violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint filed against Hewlett-Packard in September accused  
the company of using a chemical in its inkjet printer inks for 
years without filing the proper documents or providing health 
studies to the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard has said the complaint is a paperwork mix-up and  
maintains it has continued to cooperate with federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The now-retracted settlement reached in April slashed fines  
against company from $2.5 million to $112,000, in part because the 
company admitted problems with chemical records before the 
government completed its investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal investigation of Hewlett-Packard was spurred by  
information supplied by Norman Pawlowski, a former chemist at the 
Corvallis plant who at one time was in charge of making sure the 
company complied with environmental laws around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	He has sued the company, claiming he was fired because he  
complained to managers that Hewlett-Packard was skirting 
environmental laws. 
</P>
<P>
	A Department of Labor administrative judge ordered the company  
to reinstate Pawlowski in April and pay him back salary from his 
firing in December 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard officials said Pawlowski was fired for  
falsifying reports to the Environmental Protection agency. The 
company has appealed the decision to reinstate him. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
