<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Unchanged in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices remained frozen in June for  
the second straight month, the best showing on inflation in 13 
years, as energy costs and airline fares dropped sharply while food 
prices held steady. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that its Consumer Price Index --  
the most closely watched gauge of inflation -- was flat in June, as 
it was in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time prices showed no increase for two straight months  
was in 1986, when for three consecutive months the CPI actually 
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	June's performance was even better than economists had been  
expecting. They had been forecasting a slight rise of 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news on consumer prices, which followed Wednesday's  
report that prices at the wholesale level actually fell 0.1 
percent, was certain to calm fears about inflation that had been 
generated when prices at the retail and wholesale level spiked in 
April. The rise was caused by a sharp runup in prices for gasoline 
and other energy products. 
</P>
<P>
	The big jump in prices in April put the Federal Reserve on alert  
that inflationary pressures could be building and prompted the Fed 
on June 30 to nudge up interest rates for the first time in two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	However, with inflation pressures now moderating, some  
economists believe Fed policy-makers will not increase rates when 
they meet again next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In two other reports, the government said the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose sharply 
to 310,000 last week, and stockpiles held by businesses edged up 
0.3 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the increase of 11,000 in jobless claims, the nation's  
labor market was still exceptionally healthy with unemployment 
remaining near a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as in May, the good showing on prices in June reflected a  
big drop in energy costs. Gasoline prices fell a sharp 3.2 percent 
last month, the most in more than two years. Gasoline prices were 
down 2.7 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The big drop in gasoline prices contributed to an overall  
decline of 1.2 percent in energy costs, which followed a 1.3 
percent drop in May and helped reverse a part of April's huge, 6.1 
percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices, meanwhile, were unchanged in June, after a sharp  
0.4 percent rise the month before. The moderation in food costs 
came even though beef prices shot up 1.5 percent -- the biggest 
increase in more than six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices were held back by big declines in prices of pork and  
fresh vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the volatile food and energy sectors, price pressures  
remained tame as well. This ``core rate'' of inflation was up only 
0.1 percent in June, the same as May. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparel prices, meanwhile, also fell 0.4 percent last month, the  
fifth decline this year. Airline fares were down 4.8 percent, the 
largest drop in more than three years, while new-car prices edged 
down 0.3 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
