<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A former guard has been sentenced  
to 10 years in prison for the death of a 75-year-old woman crushed 
by the electric gates of the National Intelligence School in Buenos 
Aires, reports said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alberto Ricardo Dattoli told a court he slipped over his  
shoelaces the night of Feb. 26, 1998, accidentally triggering the 
button on the gates that killed Sofia Fijman, who used to feed 
several cats living in the school yard. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled the former guard had activated the gate  
intentionally, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The school is part of the government's secret service agency.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico has extradited a U.S. man to face  
charges in the 1996 killing of a Florida woman, the federal 
attorney general's office said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Interpol agents escorted Jose Raul Plasencia aboard a flight  
Wednesday from Mexico's Benito Juarez International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Plasencia is accused of strangling Michaelene Blastic in Ft.  
Myers, Fla. Her bruised body was found in a refrigerator in her 
apartment on March 13, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Two law professors from Mexico's largest  
state-run university filed a criminal complaint Thursday against 
student strike leaders who have occupied university buildings for 
almost three months, Mexican media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignacio Burgoa and Raul Carranca, professors emeritus at the  
National Autonomous University, accused strikers of illegal 
occupation of public property and said they could face 11 years in 
prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the university have been meeting with strike  
leaders for two weeks, but no agreements have been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Students took over buildings in April after yearly tuition was  
increased from a symbolic 2 cents to $145. In June, the university 
agreed to make the tuition increase optional, but students 
continued the strike, saying other demands had not been met. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	OAXACA, Mexico (AP) -- A local bus drove off a steep embankment  
and overturned Thursday in the southern state of Oaxaca, killing 
two people and injuring dozens. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred two miles from Santa Maria Alotepec. The  
bus was heading southwest to the state capital, the city of Oaxaca, 
110 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Arrest warrants were issued Thursday for nine  
Mexican police officers accused of stealing 63 guns from a police 
station in southern Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 29, the officers were found stealing the weapons or  
guarding the station in the borough of Xochimilco during the theft, 
the Mexico City attorney general's office said in a report by the 
government news agency Notimex. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were placed under house arrest July 5 pending an  
investigation. Judge Alberti Rubalcava Ramirez issued the formal 
arrest warrant Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Some 3,000 police and special  
force commandos from the El Salvadoran army began patrolling the 
capital and other areas Thursday in a new five-day campaign to 
crack down on crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation is meant to reduce crime by deploying teams in  
densely populated areas and monitoring vehicular traffic, National 
Civil Police director Mauricio Sandoval told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The forces were patrolling the greater San Salvador area and  
specific rural zones. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teams have been concentrated in areas where criminal bands  
and groups with a high record of crime are known to exist,'' 
Sandoval said. 
  	   	
</P>
