<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Decries N. Ireland Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A disappointed President Clinton likened the  
breakdown in the Northern Ireland peace process Thursday to a 
childish dispute and insisted that eventually a deal would be 
sealed. ``Sooner or later, we'll get this thing back on track,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacemaking efforts were thrown into disarray when Northern  
Ireland's major Protestant party refused to nominate ministers for 
the new provincial administration, derailing hopes for forming a 
government of Protestants and Catholics after a year of deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a difficult day for those of us who have worked for  
years'' for peace, Clinton said. He said it was ``a particularly 
difficult day for British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Prime 
Minister Bertie Ahern, who have performed heroic service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The process broke down when Ulster Unionists refused to support  
the formation of any administration that includes the Irish 
Republican Army-linked Sinn Fein party unless the IRA starts to 
disarm, something the outlawed group has long refused to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the disagreement was one that most Americans would  
find difficult to believe. ``They are having a fight over who goes 
first and acting today as if the whole thing could be abandoned 
over that. That cannot be allowed to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But later, in a written statement, he suggested that too much  
had been invested in the peace process for Northern Ireland's 
leaders to abandon it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cry for a peaceful, inclusive democratic society in  
Northern Ireland has never been stronger,'' he said. ``For the 
future of all the people of Northern Ireland who want an enduring 
peace and a normal life, I call upon all those involved to find the 
way to get the peace process back on track.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
