<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Threatens Force Against Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Vowing to defend every inch of Chinese territory,  
China's military today threatened to use force against Taiwan if 
President Lee Teng-hui declares independence on the island. In a 
sharply worded commentary run in newspapers nationwide, the 
military's newspaper, the Liberation Army Daily, said the armed 
forces stand ready to enforce a long-standing government policy to 
attack Taiwan, if need be, to uphold China's claim to the island. 
The rhetoric is the most aggressive used by China's leaders since 
Lee suggested Saturday that China and Taiwan are separate, equal 
countries. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Launches Mideast Peace Drive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today is launching a new  
U.S. drive for Mideast peacemaking, looking to Israeli Prime 
Minister Ehud Barak for a formula to reopen negotiations with the 
Palestinians and to affirm he will give up West Bank land to them. 
The two leaders are to make a joint statement at the White House 
later today. In Helsinki earlier today, Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat called for the Finnish president to help get the Mideast 
peace process back on track. It was the Finnish leader who 
co-brokered a peace plan for Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Meet Columbine Students  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today will discuss gun  
control efforts with students from Colorado's Columbine High as 
lawmakers try to reconcile a Senate-passed juvenile justice bill 
with a House version that lacks Clinton-backed gun measures. Twelve 
students and a teacher were killed in an April shooting rampage at 
Columbine High. White House-backed gun control legislation cleared 
the Senate earlier in the year. It failed in the House when 
Democrats rejected the legislation as too weak, and Republicans 
opposed it for being too restrictive on guns. 

</P>
<P>
	Rugova Returns to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo Albanian political leader  
Ibrahim Rugova made his long-awaited return from wartime exile 
today, declaring he is still president of the province as crowds of 
supporters chanted his name. Meanwhile in the Yugoslav capital, 
Belgrade, several pro-democracy activists were attacked while they 
organized signing of a petition for the ouster of President 
Slobodan Milosevic, an opposition official said. Dragan Kopcalic, 
of the Democratic Party, said three people were hospitalized and 
one activist was seriously injured. 

</P>
<P>
	Girl Has Unwanted Heart Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	NEWCASTLE UPON TYNE, England (AP) -- A 15-year-old girl in  
Britain has undergone a heart transplant against her wishes at the 
order of a High Court judge. Doctors had gone to the London court 
seeking a ruling to compel the girl, known only as Child M, to have 
the life-saving operation. Child M's case became public today when 
the High Court justice involved, Robert Johnson, explained his 
decision. Johnson said he knew his ruling meant the girl would 
carry ``resentment about what has been done to her.'' But he said 
he had to weigh that against ``not simply the risk, but the 
certainty of death.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Two Warner Studio Chiefs Resign  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The veteran co-leaders of the Warner Bros.  
movie and music studios, Robert Daly and Terry Semel, plan to leave 
their posts by the end of the year, the company announced today. 
Daly and Semel had served with Warner Bros. for 20 years, and said 
they considered their departure for several months. The surprise 
announcement came just a day after Time Warner reported strong 
results for its second quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Unchanged in June  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices remained frozen in June for  
the second straight month, the best showing on inflation in 13 
years as energy costs dropped sharply and food prices held steady. 
The Labor Department said today that its Consumer Price Index -- the 
most closely watched gauge of inflation -- was flat in June, as it 
was in May. June's performance was even better than economists had 
been expecting. ``Inflation remains totally absent,'' said Merrill 
Lynch economist Stan Shipley. 

</P>
