<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Approval of Infant Vaccine Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Drugmakers are working to lessen the pain of  
getting life saving immunizations for infants by combining existing 
vaccines. 
</P>
<P>
	British pharmaceutical firm SmithKline Beecham is seeking U.S.  
approval for a new combination vaccine for five childhood diseases 
-- diphtheria, whooping cough, tetanus, polio and hepatitis B -- 
which would reduce the number of shots babies need in their first 
year of life. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline Beecham asked the federal government Thursday for an  
expedited review for its combination vaccine, which already is 
available in Europe. An expedited review means the government would 
have six months to approve the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Infants now need nine shots during their first 12 months of life  
to gain protection against the five diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Diphtheria, whooping cough and tetanus are already combined in  
one vaccine, while polio and hepatitis B vaccinations are given 
separately. Each of the vaccinations is given three times in the 
first year. 
</P>
<P>
	With SmithKline's new combination vaccine, 1-year-old infants  
would only need a total of three shots to be protected against the 
five diseases. Other shots would still be necessary to protection 
children against measles, mumps and other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything that reduces the number of injections will be welcome  
by medical providers and parents,'' said Dr. Melinda Wharton, chief 
of child vaccines at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Several pharmaceutical companies are working on combination  
infant immunizations, though SmithKline is the only company seeking 
U.S. approval for a vaccine that protects against five diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	The new five-disease vaccine would include the injectable form  
of polio and the acellular form of hepatitis B, which are 
considered the safest versions of the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trauma of the shots (for parents) is one of the reasons  
people do not show up for vaccines,'' said John Jabara, a 
SmithKline Beecham vice president. ``The introduction of this 
vaccine can really have a positive impact on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline and Merck are also working on a vaccine that would  
combine the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine with the shot for 
chicken pox. SmithKline is also developing a single vaccine against 
hepatitis A and hepatitis B. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline had more than $1 billion in vaccine sales last year.  
</P>
<P>
	Other vaccine combinations being developed by companies include  
a Hib (Haemophilus influenzae type b) and Hepatitis B combination 
and a diphtheria, tetanus, whooping cough and polio combination. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
