<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Cites Discovery, Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- As it announced a major oil discovery in the Gulf  
of Mexico, BP Amoco PLC unveiled a sweeping, 3-year reorganization 
program Thursday, including plans to shed $10 billion in poor 
performing petrochemical and refinery operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it would slash expenses by 20 percent by 2001,  
while at the same time boosting capital spending by $26 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco's strategy offers a sign of what may lie ahead for  
other oil companies seeking to boost profits by merging. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like BP Amoco is stealing a bit of a march on their  
competitors,'' said Barney Gray, an analyst at the brokerage 
Williams De Broe. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco said its ``Crazy Horse'' oil prospect is located in  
6,000 feet of water, 125 miles southeast of New Orleans and has 
estimated recoverable reserves of 1 billion barrels -- a level that 
analyst Alan Sinclair of Charterhouse Securities called 
``astonishing.'' BP Amoco has a 75 percent stake in the site, with 
Mobil holding the remaining 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On the news, the U.S. shares of BP Amoco shot up 2.5 percent,  
rising $3 to close at $121.50 Thursday on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	A wave of consolidation is sweeping the oil industry, driven by  
a need to cut costs when oil prices plunged last year to levels 
last seen in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposed merger between Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., which  
would create the world's largest oil company, awaits regulatory 
approval. In France, TotalFina SA launched an unsolicited $43 
billion takeover bid earlier this month for rival Elf Aquitaine SA. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco itself was formed last year when British Petroleum  
acquired Chicago-based Amoco Corp. Since then, it has reached 
agreement to acquire Atlantic Richfield Co., known as Arco. 
</P>
<P>
	BP's integration with Amoco is now effectively complete, chief  
executive John Browne said at a meeting Thursday with investors to 
announce the reorganization. He said the merger is expected to 
produce annual savings of $2 billion by end of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, BP Amoco plans to shift its emphasis increasingly  
toward exploration and production and away from less profitable 
refinery and petrochemicals operations, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco aims to trim its refining operations by about a third,  
due to an increase in global capacity. The first operation it plans 
to sell is the Alliance Refinery near Belle Chasse, La., a facility 
that employs 760 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to sell off $2.5 billion in petrochemical  
operations for similar reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced earlier this year that it planned to cut  
10,000 jobs from its combined work force of 98,000. It has 
eliminated 7,000 jobs already in 1999, most of them in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would dare say the losses will be bigger,'' analyst Gray  
said. ``That's the hardest bit for people to swallow. It's all very 
well talking about efficiency until you start cutting jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco's agreement in April to purchase Arco is expected to  
lead to the loss of 2,000 jobs. It wasn't clear if these cuts are 
to be in addition to the 10,000 already planned for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, analyst Sinclair said BP Amoco is setting a high standard  
of efficiency for the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the others will find it tough to match,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In what was probably an unintended irony, Browne outlined BP  
Amoco's progress in improving efficiency at a time when oil prices 
are surging, due largely to cutbacks in OPEC production. 
</P>
<P>
	Contracts for August delivery of Brent Blend crude oil from the  
North Sea closed at $19.03 a barrel in London. On the New York 
Mercantile Exchange, August contracts of West Texas Intermediate 
crude for August delivery closed at $20.16 a barrel -- almost twice 
the 12-year low of $10.65 reached Dec. 11, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne said BP Amoco aims to reduce its production costs to a  
level where it can still make a robust profit if prices change 
course and fall as low as $11 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair noted that oil markets are fickle and that some blends  
traded at less than $10 a barrel just months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be half that again in six months. We don't know,''  
Sinclair said. 
</P>
<P>
	The current buoyancy in crude prices made Browne's announcement  
of new offshore discoveries all the more welcome for investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Crazy Horse prospect, BP Amoco announced  
three other discoveries, including a major find off the coast of 
Angola. 
</P>
<P>
	``They probably don't need to build another exploration well to  
keep the show on the road for the next 10 years,'' Sinclair said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
