<HEADLINE> Smokers To Testify in Second Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The second phase of a trial involving up to 500,000  
sick Florida smokers and their families will start with testimony 
of two smokers who are terminally ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases of Mary Farnan and Angie DellaVecchia will be tried  
together when phase two begins Sept. 7, Circuit Judge Robert Kaye 
ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In phase one, the jury decided the plaintiffs were entitled to  
punitive damages. The amount will be set, and the cases of the nine 
class representatives heard, in the next phase. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaye also ruled that compensatory damages would be determined  
for the class representatives before the jury decides on punitive 
damages for the class. Plaintiffs' attorneys Susan and Stanley 
Rosenblatt sought punitive damages to be set first. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaye deferred ruling on whether the jury would be instructed to  
award punitive damages as a ratio to the compensatory awards or as 
a dollar amount. He will announce his decision in a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco lawyers argued that punitive damages should be decided  
for each case, not for the class. 
</P>
<P>
	But lead defense attorney Robert Heim said the jury already has  
determined that tobacco is a defective product causing illnesses 
and jurors could not determine the validity of claims of each 
plaintiff. ``It would be a pure exercise in guesswork,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The class-action lawsuit by smokers is the first to reach trial.  
</P>
<P>
	The defendants are the nation's five biggest cigarette makers  
and two industry groups: Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., 
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Liggett 
Group Inc., as well as the Council for Tobacco Research and the 
Tobacco Institute. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
