<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Weather Linked to Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Weather satellite data that detect warming in  
the Indian Ocean and the early signs of an El Nino in the Pacific 
may also give an early warning about an outbreak of Rift Valley 
Fever in Africa, researchers say. 
</P>
<P>
	A study appearing Friday in the journal Science has linked the  
warming of Pacific and Indian Ocean waters with increased rains in 
Africa and the periodic outbreaks of Rift Valley Fever, a 
mosquito-borne disease that can kill humans and animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at the Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt,  
Md., and the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research in Washington 
analyzed 50 years of weather and medical data to establish the 
connection between warm oceans, rains and the fever. 
</P>
<P>
	``We discovered a cycle of Rift Valley Fever outbreaks that  
appeared to depend on rainfall,'' said Kenneth Linthicum of Walter 
Reed. ``There were large outbreaks every seven to 10 years, but the 
virus apparently disappears between outbreaks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assaf Anyamba, a Goddard researcher who uses satellites to study  
the oceans, said that East Africa gets more rain during an El Nino, 
but that this effect, alone, is not enough to prompt a fever 
outbreak. 
</P>
<P>
	A fever outbreak is more likely to occur when the Indian Ocean  
warms at the same time as there is an El Nino, a phenomenon that 
includes the warming of Pacific Ocean waters. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the western equatorial Indian Ocean is similar to the  
East Pacific in sea-surface temperature, there will likely be a 
large-scale outbreak of Rift Valley Fever,'' said Anyamba. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers said their study suggests that satellite data that  
measures sea surface temperature, along with measurements of 
vegetation growth in East Africa, could pinpoint areas where Rift 
Valley Fever outbreaks are most likely to occur. 
</P>
<P>
	The cycle of Rift Valley Fever disease depends on two types of  
mosquitoes. The Aedes mosquito lay eggs in moist soil and the young 
hatch when the ground is flooded. These insects carry the Rift 
Valley Fever virus and infect livestock. 
</P>
<P>
	When there are excessive rains, a second type of mosquito, the  
Culex, becomes prevalent. It takes blood from both livestock and 
humans and spreads the virus to people. As a result, a major human 
outbreak occurs only when there is enough rain for a large hatch of 
Culex mosquitoes. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers said that satellite data could give a  
two-to-five-month warning of a Rift Valley Fever outbreak. This 
would give time to vaccinate livestock and to treat mosquito 
habitats with insecticides that are released upon flooding. This 
would prevent the mosquitoes from hatching and, thus, break the 
cycle of disease. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
