<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: No Hart Probe Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No one pulled any strings to discipline a  
federal investigator who claims he was punished hours after asking 
touchy questions last year about the sex life of former Sen. Gary 
Hart, Pentagon officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigator was doing a routine background check on Hart,  
who had been invited by his friend and former colleague, Defense 
Secretary William Cohen, to serve on a special national security 
study panel and needed a top-secret security clearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart, a Colorado Democrat and former presidential candidate,  
called Cohen's office to complain about what he considered 
inappropriate questions posed by investigator David Kerno, both 
sides say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not dictate any course of action,'' said Robert Tyrer,  
Cohen's chief of staff and a longtime aide. Tyrer took the call 
from Hart, and passed on Hart's complaint to senior officials at 
the Defense Security Service, where Kerno works. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerno was reassigned to a desk job and stripped of his badge and  
credentials shortly after the Sept. 18, 1998, interviews with three 
of Hart's colleagues at a Denver law firm. The agency has since 
recommended he be suspended without pay, his Denver lawyer said. 
The case was first reported in Wednesday's editions of USA Today. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerno declined comment Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``He thought he was doing the right things,'' said Kerno's  
lawyer, Daniel Minahan. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerno had no indication that the three Hart colleagues were  
miffed at his questions, Minahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's our speculation that he (Hart) was,'' upset when told  
about the sessions later, Minahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart's assistant, Pamela Martinson, was one of the three people  
questioned. She said Wednesday neither she nor Hart would comment 
on Kerno's allegations. Two lawyers also questioned by Kerno were 
out of the office Wednesday, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart's 1988 presidential hopes were dashed after he was captured  
on film cavorting with a part-time model, Donna Rice. Hart was 
married at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerno asked Hart's assistant and two other lawyers about the  
1988 incident and related personal questions, both sides said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not so much just about other women, but it was very  
detailed and seemed a bit, I don't want to say prurient, but it was 
inappropriate,'' a defense official familiar with the case said. 
Kerno probed ``well beyond the scope of what you'd look for this 
type of investigation, where a guy's going to chair an unpaid 
(board),'' the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyrer and other defense officials said Hart was concerned that  
intrusive questions could backfire on the Pentagon when it is 
trying to recruit prominent, well-qualified participants for 
positions like the National Security Study Group. 
</P>
<P>
	``His complaint was not so much his own case, but his fear was  
that if this was standard investigative practice that we would 
start to have people opt out of serving,'' Tyrer said. ``I had no 
independent way to evaluate the merit of his complaint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyrer, speaking while flying with Cohen to Ankara, Turkey,  
Wednesday for meetings with top officials on NATO and other 
matters, said the Kerno case was handled no differently from any 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	He said neither he nor Cohen had any plan to interfere with  
Kerno's bosses, nor did he keep abreast of what happened to Kerno 
afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerno remains ``in limbo,'' his lawyer said. The Defense  
Security Service has not yet acted on the recommendation for a 
suspension, and Kerno has tried to clear his name administratively, 
Minahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the agency, Caryl Clubb, said she cannot  
comment on Kerno's case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
