<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BankBoston Earnings Rise 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- BankBoston Corp. reported a 4 percent increase in  
profits for the second quarter of 1999 due to strong performances 
by the corporation's investment and South American operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank on Thursday posted net income of $250 million, or 83  
cents a share, beating Wall Street's expectations by 6 cents. 
During the second quarter last year, BankBoston earned $242 
million, or 80 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues were $1.37 billion, up from $1.10 billion in the  
year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors appeared pleased with the results, and sent  
BankBoston's shares up $1.81 1/4 to $50.81 1/4 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston-based company is in the midst of being taken over by  
Fleet Financial Group Inc. in a merger that would create the 
nation's eighth-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston said its Brazilian and Argentine operations continued  
their strong performances, despite the region's economic troubles. 
Together, they reported an increase of approximately 50 percent in 
net income this year compared with the first half of 1998, the bank 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston's investment banking arm, Robertson Stephens,  
reported an 80 percent growth from first-quarter 1999, when it 
reported pretax income of $30 million. The company was acquired by 
BankBoston in the third quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston ended the quarter with total assets of $77.6 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of 1999, net income totaled $473 million, or  
$1.58 a share, compared with $480 million, or $1.58 a share, in the 
first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the first half were $2.61 billion vs. $2.13  
billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
