<HEADLINE> WNBA Locations To Be Re-Evaluated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- WNBA president Val Ackerman says the league will  
consider moving teams that are not successful at the gate. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance has been low in Los Angeles, Charlotte and Utah, and  
all franchises will be re-evaluated in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will assess team performance after the third year,''  
Ackerman said before the All-Star game Wednesday night. ``There is 
no permanent right to a WNBA team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance at WNBA games has decreased 2.8 percent compared to  
the midpoint of last season. The 12-team league is averaging 9,695 
through 80 games, down slightly from 9,970 of last season. 
</P>
<P>
	When compared to attendance at the end of last season (10,821),  
attendance has decreased 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The emergence of rookie sensation Chamique Holdsclaw in the  
league has not caused a spike in attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think Chamique and players like her will be why the WNBA  
will continue to grow and attract new fans,'' Ackerman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time MVP Cynthia Cooper is not concerned about the dip in  
attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to have up and down seasons, the key is not to  
get nervous about it,'' Cooper said. ``I think the WNBA will do 
what is necessary to pick up attendance in those cities. You have 
to get the right players in the right cities. It may just be a 
question of promotion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four expansion teams will be added in Seattle, Portland, Miami  
and Indianapolis next season. Ackerman said she does not anticipate 
the $14 league-average ticket price to increase. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RIDING SOCCER WAVE:* Mia Hamm, Brandi Chastain, Sara Whalen and  
other members of the World Cup soccer team received a standing 
ovation when they were introduced before the capacity crowd of 
18,645 at Madison Square Garden during the WNBA All-Star game 
Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're all great, especially Ticha Penicheiro and  
Sheryl Swoopes,'' Hamm said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just as exciting as a men's game, with behind the back  
passes,'' Chastain said. ``Tell them we're in awe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honorary All-Star Rebecca Lobo said the way the country has  
embraced the women's soccer team reminds her of the USA basketball 
team's march to the 1996 Olympic gold medal in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's captivated everyone,'' said Lobo, who was voted onto the  
all-star team despite a season-ending knee injury. ``All the media 
attention was focused on it. I hope they can use it to get the 
things they want and use it as a spring board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Lobo's not convinced a professional soccer league can be  
developed quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Major League Soccer is pretty much an infant league like we  
are, trying to grow,'' she said. ``Women's soccer is going to need 
some help from somewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to see a professional league. I also have seen  
everything that the NBA has had to do for us. It takes a lot of 
money, a lot of time, and an incredible infrastructure. I don't 
know if they have that yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *COOPER MISSES MILLION:* Cynthia Cooper's half-court shot to  
make Jason Walters a millionaire was three feet short during 
halftime festivities of the inaugural WNBA All-Star Game Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The capacity crowd of 18,645 at Madison Square Garden groaned  
after the two-time MVP dribbled the ball twice at halfcourt and 
launched an airball. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters, a U.S. Treasury Department employee who coincidently  
works in the Statistics of Income division, made a layup worth 
$10,000 and missed a free throw worth $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it was up to Cooper to earn Walters and his family a cool  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anyone can make the shoot, it's going to be Cynthia,''  
Walters said before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper went 1-for-7 from halfcourt while practicing with Walters  
at Columbia University on Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old Walters attended the game with his wife, Amie,  
and mother-in-law and brother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife wants to start a family in the next couple of years,  
so this will definitely help,'' Walters said of the $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters had practiced daily in his hometown of Germantown, Md.,  
since June 29. He was selected after applying for the shootout on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Buick Regal sponsored the $1 million Supercharged Shootout. The  
West team beat the East, 79-61, behind 14 points by Natalie 
Williams. Buick donated $25,000 to Project Cure to fight breast 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
                              	----	 
</P>
<P>
	 *YO-YO GRIFFITH:* All-Star Yolanda Griffith scored 10 points and  
grabbed five rebounds in 21 minutes to boost the Western Conference 
All-Stars to a 79-61 victory over the East. 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA's unheralded No. 2 pick has led the Sacramento Monarchs  
(10-5) to a second-place tie with Los Angeles in the Western 
Conference. The Monarchs finished 8-22 last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed Yo-Yo, Griffith had a stretch in late June where she  
made 36 of 58 shots (.621). She wears No. 33 and has the number 
tattoed on her right bicep in honor of Scottie Pippen's defensive 
work ethic. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29-year-old Griffith is averaging a third-best 19.5 points  
and league-leading 12.5 rebounds a game. The former ABL defensive 
player of the year leads the WNBA in double-doubles with 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffith's superb play may be responsible for the boost in  
attendance at Arco Arena, where the Monarchs are 5-1. Of the 10 
WNBA teams that had franchises in 1998, only Sacramento has enjoyed 
more fans in the stands (8,019) compared to last season (6,578). 
</P>
<P>
	But it's hard to catch her on television -- the Monarchs have  
just two nationally televised games. The final televised game is 
against Cleveland Friday on Lifetime Television. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAN SUPPORT:* The throngs of fans attending WNBA festivites in  
Manhattan proved they wanted to see their role models up close. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassiopeia Williams of Marietta, Ga., was among those waiting in  
line at the WNBA Store to get New York Liberty guard Teresa 
Weatherspoon's autograph. 
</P>
<P>
	She put her leg up on the table and had Weatherspoon sign her  
basketball shoe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teresa's my favorite,'' said Williams, 16. ``Attitude. All  
attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had a copy of Weatherspoon's ``Basketball for Girls''  
book tucked under her arm along with a handful of WNBA basketball 
cards. 
</P>
<P>
	A street fair with shooting contests and a chance to meet the  
players occured outside of Madison Square Garden Wednesday 
afternoon before the All-Star game. 
  	   	
</P>
