<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strange Adds Insight to Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Curtis Strange was never a media darling, even when he was  
capturing consecutive U.S. Open titles in the 1980s. Now, the 
traits that once were annoying to some are earning him praise. 
</P>
<P>
	In his third season as ABC's lead golf analyst, Strange brings  
an insight matched by few, if any, and a candor that may have irked 
many people in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	The 44-year-old is still active on the PGA Tour and doesn't  
expect to quit anytime soon. Each of the past seven weeks he has 
done double duty, playing in tournaments televised by ABC and then 
changing into his broadcasting attire and running upstairs to the 
18th tower. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's done a fabulous job, because it's not easy to do  
both,'' said CBS commentator David Feherty. ``I can't think of 
another golfer who has come off the course and broadcast the rest 
of the round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's because Strange is the only one out there.  
</P>
<P>
	The viewer is the clear winner when Strange pulls his version of  
a doubleheader. When he comes off the course, he is able to 
describe it better than anybody. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, Strange's exemption ran out after this past U.S.  
Open, since his last PGA Tour win was in 1989, and he isn't playing 
at this year's British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	You may be hearing a sigh of relief from Strange, especially  
after Thursday's first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the toughest course I've ever seen,'' he said after  
walking Carnoustie Golf Links twice before play began. ``Forget 
what par is. Low score wins. Here it's going to be survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strange admits his relationship with the media hasn't always  
been peaceful. But that's part of what makes him successful in his 
newest endeavor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never had a lot of patience when I played and I guess I  
rubbed some of the media the wrong way,'' Strange said. ``But I 
think that's good for TV because I'm blunt and to the point. If I 
were wishy-washy and everyone liked me, I don't think I'd be worth 
a darn on TV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strange hasn't won an event since he capturing back-to-back U.S.  
Opens (1988-89) -- the first to accomplish that since Ben Hogan did 
it in 1950 and 1951. Strange has played in 13 tournaments this year 
and ranks No. 154 on the money list with $113,263. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a full-time broadcaster now, but I'll always play some  
because I still enjoy it even though I don't play as well as I used 
to. But it's important for me to play in order to stay current.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC producer Jack Graham is trying to stay up on things as well.  
This year's telecast will look more Americanized than ever. In the 
past, the network strictly used the feed from the BBC. Now it has 
11 of its own cameras, plus two handheld ones on the course. 
</P>
<P>
	``That gives us a lot more flexibility about being able to cut  
back to players and give viewers tight shots and better graphics,'' 
Graham said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *KEEPING PACE:* Mark McGwire isn't the only one to fall off last  
year's pace. Although some of the baseball networks have increased 
ratings, a few haven't been as fortunate. 
</P>
<P>
	At this time last season, all of the networks were up from the  
year before, but this season Fox is the only winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first six weeks, Fox's Saturday game of the week is  
up 7 percent, Fox Sports Net is up 12 percent and FX is up 13 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	However, ESPN is down 7 percent through 49 games this season,  
and Turner has dipped 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox didn't fare so well with Tuesday's All-Star game, in which  
ratings dropped 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MOVING TRIBUTE:* NBC's Bob Costas, who will do play-by-play for  
this year's World Series, was at home for the All-Star game and had 
nothing but praise for Fox's coverage -- especially its pregame 
ceremony involving Ted Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was perfect and very moving,'' Costas said. ``You  
couldn't have asked for anything better. I think Fox did an 
excellent job presenting it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Costas cites lots of reasons for the All-Star game's declining  
ratings, not the least of which is overexposure. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was a kid, the All-Star game was so special because you  
didn't see these guys,'' he said. ``You never saw the guys from the 
other league. Now we see them every night on highlight shows on 
ESPN and CNN. People can see Mark McGwire any night of the week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* CBS' David Feherty will be analyzing broadcast  
partner and friend, Gary McCord, this weekend at the Ameritech 
Senior Open for the first time. ``The hardest part will be trying 
to be objective and professional,'' Feherty said. ... ESPN's cable 
rating for the Home Run Derby was a 7.5, down from a 7.7 last year. 
... FX announced Lawrence Taylor will be an analyst for its 
Toughman boxing series, and the cable network will also put on its 
third-ever boxing show, with WBA super welterweight champion David 
Reid (12-0) making his first title defense Friday at 10 p.m. EDT. 
... ESPN's Geoff Mason, who produced the Women's World Cup final, 
on choosing not to show a reaction shot of the Chinese team after 
losing: ``Guilty as charged. Quite candidly, we should have 
replayed (Brianna Scurry's) save and we didn't. That was a 
production mistake we made.'' ... ABC shows the MLS All-Star game 
Saturday at 3:30 p.m. EDT. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
