<DOCNO> APW19990715.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NextCard Sues Providian over Web Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Web-based credit company NextCard sued  
credit giant Providian for copyright infringement in a case that 
could set a precedent for how the law applies to Internet 
advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	In the suit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in San  
Francisco, NextCard accused Providian of copying a Web banner ad 
that features a descending thermometer to represent falling 
interest rates. NextCard said the ad is its most effective, with 
about 680,000 Web users clicking on it. 
</P>
<P>
	NextCard said Providian's ad infringed on its copyrights and  
trademarks, and represents unfair competition. NextCard asked the 
court to force Providian to stop running the ad and pay unspecified 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Providian's strategy at this point is apparently to deceive  
Internet users into thinking they were clicking on to NextCard's 
site,'' NextCard chief executive Jeremy Lent told the San Francisco 
Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Lent was Providian's chief financial officer before leaving to  
found NextCard several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	NextCard is the largest credit card company that operates only  
on the Web. Providian is the nation's ninth largest credit card 
issuer. Both companies are based in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no proprietary rights in banner ads,'' said  
Providian spokesman Marc Loewenthal. ``They are attention-getting 
devices that do not reflect any original work of authorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal and state laws define unfair competition and protect  
business trademarks, copyrights and proprietary symbols. But legal 
experts say there is little guidance on how the law applies to 
Internet ads. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a subject that's going to be one of the hottest in the  
next few years,'' said Joseph Cotchett, an attorney in Burlingame, 
Calif. ``It's going to spawn more litigation than you can 
imagine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Internet banners ads allow users to click and go to an  
advertiser's Web site, but they are becoming less effective as 
people learn to tune them out. Industry studies show that on 
average, users click on banner ads once out of every 200 times they 
view a Web page. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
