<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Downgrades Growth Numbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore's 1998 recession was deeper than  
originally thought and its recovery slower, according to revised 
economic growth figures released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a new method of calculation designed to reflect changes in  
the financial sector, the 1998 third-quarter gross domestic product 
contracted 1.9 percent, the Statistics Department said. Its earlier 
calculations showed a 0.6 percent decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-quarter GDP contracted 1.1 percent, the report said. The  
earlier calculation was 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's economic growth was revised downward to 0.3 percent  
from 1.5 percent, and this year's first-quarter growth was adjusted 
to 0.8 percent from 1.2 percent, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	GDP is the measure of all goods and services produced within a  
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the new way of measuring GDP reflects more  
accurately the adverse impact of the financial crisis, which 
seriously weakened financial services and the overall economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has estimated that Singapore's economy will show  
growth of up to 2 percent this year, but Deputy Prime Minister Lee 
Hsien Loong has said the forecast would be raised in August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
