<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case Vs. Mexico Ex-Financier Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A Mexican court has thrown out one of the  
last two charges remaining against a former financier accused of 
swindling his bank out of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The court granted an injunction Wednesday blocking a charge that  
Angel Isidoro Rodriguez Saez arranged for his bank, Banpais, to 
make 59 million pesos (now $6.3 million) in illegal loans to 
companies he owned. It ruled that the charge was filed two months 
after the statute of limitations had expired, Mexican news media 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez, known as ``El Divino'' -- ``The Divine One'' -- is one  
of several high-flying bankers from the early 1990s whose excesses 
and alleged corruption have made them symbols of the Mexican 
banking crisis that eventually required a government bailout, 
estimated at more than $65 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez fled to Spain as banking scandals emerged in 1994. He  
was arrested in Spain in July 1996 -- despite diving off his yacht 
in the Mediterranean in an effort to elude police -- and was 
extradited to Mexico last year on four criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the charges have now been dismissed. Rodriguez, who is  
free on bail, still faces a charge of violating stock trading laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
