<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coke Motion on Bias Suit Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday denied a request by  
The Coca-Cola Co. that would have barred a racial discrimination 
suit by four current or past employees from being extended to cover 
1,500 black salaried employees. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. District Court Judge Richard Story left open the  
possibility of turning down class-action status to the lawsuit as 
the case evolves. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a danger of reading too much into this, because all  
issues still must be resolved and a full and complete record must 
be created before I can make a decision on class action,'' Story 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, which was filed April 22, alleges Coca-Cola pays  
black employees less, offers them fewer promotions and gives them 
lower performance evaluation scores than whites. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs' lawyers are seeking class-action status for the  
suit, which would then cover about 1,500 black salaried corporate 
employees. Lead attorney Cyrus Mehri told the judge that in 
addition to the four who are now suing Coke, 100 other potential 
clients already have contacted his office. 
</P>
<P>
	He also submitted to the court a confidential document from  
Coca-Cola that Mehri said shows potential discriminatory policies 
within Coke. The document was obtained as part of the 
evidence-gathering known as the discovery process, and the judge 
has ruled that such material from Coke should not be made public. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's ruling cleared the way for a discovery process that  
could stretch into next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Story's action is ``important because this institution of the  
old South will be called to task for taking civil rights back in 
time,'' Mehri said. ``But we are sobered by the fact that this is 
not time for a victory dance, but a time to get back to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coke turned over 15,000 documents and a computer database on  
July 1. Plaintiffs' lawyers have 90 days to file a petition for 
class-action status. But they have argued that since they can't 
decipher the computerized records and because not all the requested 
documents have been turned over, the discovery period has not 
officially started. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke lawyers repeated arguments Thursday that since the suit  
asks for compensatory and punitive damages as well as a court order 
to stop alleged discriminatory practices, the case does not meet 
federal criteria for class-action status. 
</P>
<P>
	Lead Coca-Cola lawyer William Clineburg declined comment after  
the hearing, but Coke spokesman Rob Baskin said while the company 
was ``disappointed with the ruling ... we still recognize that it 
is a first step in a long legal process that will show that 
Coca-Cola has not in this case and does not discriminate.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
