<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Times Earnings Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times Co. reported an 11 percent  
rise in second-quarter income on higher advertising revenue and 
lower newsprint prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The company reported Thursday it earned $83.5 million, or 47  
cents per share, in its second quarter. The results did not include 
a $4 million pre-tax charge for expenses related to staff 
reductions at The Boston Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period a year ago, the company earned $75 million,  
or 38 cents a share. Excluding the effect of a one-time expense 
related to debt reduction, the year-ago profits were $78.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the quarter rose 4 percent to $779.4 million from  
$749.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The results exceeded analyst expectations of 45 cents a share,  
according to a survey by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertising revenues in the New York Times' newspaper business,  
which makes up 91 percent of the company's revenues, rose 6.6 
during the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains were strongest at The New York Times, where ad  
revenues increased 8.8 percent. Ad revenues at The Boston Globe 
also rose, posting a gain of 1.8 percent following two quarters of 
declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's total costs increased 2.7 percent in the quarter,  
mainly due to higher salaries and expenses related to a national 
expansion of The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsprint expenses for the company fell 10 percent in the  
quarter, as the average cost for the product fell 12.6 percent and 
the company increased its consumption of newsprint by 2.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from Internet-related businesses jumped 41.4 percent to  
$5.9 million compared to $4.2 million in the same period a year 
ago. The online ventures include nytimes.com, nytoday.com and 
boston.com. Unique registered users at The New York Times on the 
Web rose to 7.8 million from 6.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues slipped in the company's magazine business, which  
includes Golf Digest. The company attributed the decline to 
consolidation in the golf equipment industry and competition from 
other media outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's broadcast group, which includes eight  
network-affiliated television stations and two radio stations in 
New York City, posted an 8.1 percent increase in operating profits 
while revenues remained flat. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, the New York Times earned  
$144.9 million compared to $139.7 million in the same period a year 
earlier. Revenues rose to $1.52 billion from $1.47 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the company also announced it had named Lynn O.  
Matthews, publisher of the Sarasota Herald-Tribune in Florida, as 
president of the company's regional newspaper group. Matthews will 
replace James C. Weeks, who is retiring at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the New York Times fell 25 cents to $39 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
