<HEADLINE> Thrashers Make Trades, Sign Karlsson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The expansion Atlanta Thrashers announced a pair  
of trades Thursday and agreed to terms with Swedish center Andreas 
Karlsson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers, who appointed Curt Fraser as coach on Wednesday  
and will make their NHL debut in the fall, acquired left wing Jason 
Botterill from the Dallas Stars in exchange for defenseman Jamie 
Pushor. 
</P>
<P>
	In another deal, the Thrashers acquired right wing Martin  
Prochazka from the Toronto Maple Leafs in exchange for a 
sixth-round draft pick in the 2001 NHL entry draft, said Don 
Waddell, the club's general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The club also signed Karlsson, whose rights were acquired in a  
trade with the Calgary Flames following this year's NHL expansion 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Karlsson, 23, scored 18 goals and had 15 assists in 49 games  
last season with Leksand of the Swedish Elite League. 
</P>
<P>
	Botterill, 23, split last season with Dallas and Michigan, the  
Stars' top minor league affiliate in the International Hockey 
league. He was selected by Dallas in the first round of the 1994 
entry draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Pushor was acquired by the Thrashers in this year's expansion  
draft from the Anaheim Mighty Ducks. 
</P>
<P>
	Prochazka, 27, played in the Czech Republic last season and was  
a member of its 1998 gold medal-winning Olympic team. He played in 
29 games with Toronto during the 1997-98 season, scoring two goals 
and four assists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
