<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher Thursday, with oil  
stocks making a late surge to join rising telecommunications and 
media shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Buoying oil stocks was oil giant BP Amoco. In a presentation to  
analysts, a program of cost cuts, divestitures and investments was 
fleshed out by Chief Executive John Browne. He proposed to sell 
about $10 billion of assets and to raise capital expenditures by 
around $26 billion. BP closed up 26 pence (41 cents) at 1,285 pence 
($20.56). 
</P>
<P>
	Shell closed up 15 pence (24 cents), or 2.9 percent, and  
Paris-listed TotalFina also closed higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 594 European companies closed up  
3.40 points, or 1.1 percent, at 321.19, while the Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 295 companies in countries that joined 
the euro single currency, was up 2.99 points at 337.19. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index finished up 38.18 points at  
3960.67, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index was up 43.98 points at 
3905.92. 
</P>
<P>
	In Germany, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index was up 0.2 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Returning from Wednesday's Bastille Day market close, the Paris  
CAC 40 index was 1.5 percent higher. Milan's MIBtel index rose 0.4 
percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35 index was up 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Merger speculation regarding Britain's three major cable  
companies excited London, where the FTSE 100 share index rose 
through the session and closed up 1.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless Communications, which is 53 percent owned by  
Cable &AMP; Wireless, said it is continuing to discuss business 
opportunities with Telewest Communications and other telecoms 
companies. 

  	   	
</P>
