<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Reid To Square Off Against Kelly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- David Reid is a fighter with a golden  
future. He gets a kick out of talking about a golden moment in his 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	Mention The Punch, and both Reid and his trainer Al Mitchell  
still get emotional. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference this week at Bally's Park Place to hype his  
WBA super welterweight title defense against Australian Kevin Kelly 
Friday night, neither man paid much attention to a tape of Reid's 
fights until the third round of his 1996 156-pound Olympic final 
came on the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	That got their undivided attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was the greatest day of my life,'' Reid said Thursday.  
Needing a knockout to win, Reid knocked out Cuban Alejandro 
Duvergel with a right to the head and won a gold medal at Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	In his corner as head coach of the U.S. team was Mitchell, who  
has played such an important role in Reid's life that on Father's 
Day, Reid presented him with his WBA title belt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably a year now from it will be worth something,'' said  
Mitchell, who hopes by then Reid will have added another title to 
the WBA 154-pound championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell and Reid hope to get a fight against IBF 154-pound  
champion Fernando Vargas next spring. Vargas will defend his title 
against Raul Marque Saturday night at Stateline, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's going to win a couple more titles,'' Mitchell  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid already is scheduled defend against Keith Mullings Aug. 28  
at a site to be named. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday night in a ballroom at the Boardwalk Convention Center,  
the 25-year-old Reid, of Philadelphia (12-0, seven knockouts), will 
be making the first defense he won on a clear-cut decision over 
Laurent Boudouani of France March 6 at Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very good fighter,'' the 29-year-old Kelly (24-5-2, 11  
knockouts) said of Reid. ``He's very athletic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell said Kelly has good jab and speed, but ``the only thing  
I'm concerned about is he comes in with his head. I expect a good 
fight for seven or eight rounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight is scheduled to start at 11 p.m., EDT, and will be  
televised by FX. The telecast is set to begin at 10 p.m. and 
include a 10-round lightweight bout John John Molina (46-6, 31 
knockouts) of Puerto Rico, a former IBF junior lightweight 
champion, and James Crayton of Las Vegas (30-9-2, 19 knockouts). 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the show will be a 10-round junior welterweight match  
between Hector Camacho Jr. (22-0, 12 knockouts) and Mike Cooley 
(8-11-2, three knockouts) of Omaha, Neb. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
