<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKesson HBOC Restates Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Executives with drug and medical supplies  
wholesaler McKesson HBOC Inc. hope to put three months of turmoil 
behind them following a downward revision of the company earnings 
for the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The adjustment announced Wednesday follows an exhaustive audit  
of HBOC's accounting for the past three years, which were suspected 
to be in error because of improperly reported software sales at 
HBOC, a medical software company acquired by McKesson in January. 
HBOC is now known as Healthcare Information Technology Business, or 
ITB. 
</P>
<P>
	The restatements reduced San Francisco-based McKesson HBOC's net  
income by $152.2 million or 53 cents per share for the fiscal year 
ended March 31, 1999, $25.8 million and 9 cents for 1998, and $13.5 
million and 5 cents per share for 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McKesson rose $1.12 1/2 to $32.12 1/2 in late morning  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson's board of directors last month fired Chairman Charles  
W. McCall, who was seen as most responsible for the incorrect 
earnings statements. McCall was chairman of HBO &AMP; Co. before 
McKesson bought it. Mark A. Pulido, president and chief executive 
of the merged company, and Chief Financial Officer Richard H. 
Hawkins were allowed to resign effective July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for fiscal year 1999 was $84.9 million and earnings  
were 31 cents per share on revised revenues of $30.4 billion 
compared to net income of $304.6 million and earnings of $1.10 per 
share on revised revenues of $22.4 billion for the same period a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for fiscal year 1997 was $212.1 million and revised  
earnings were 80 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the disclosures today, and our commitment to new  
procedures and policies that aim to prevent this from happening 
again at McKessonHBOC, we can begin the process of rebuilding our 
relationships with investors and restoring credibility with the 
financial community, customers and employees,'' said John H. 
Hammergren and David L. Mahoney, newly named co-chief executive 
officers at McKesson HBOC, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of slowed growth in ITB's revenues, which the company  
attributed to an industrywide slowdown, McKesson HBOC warned its 
earnings for the first quarter ended June 30, 1999 will fall 
substantially short of a First Call survey of analysts projection 
of 49 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson HBOC also said Wednesday the U.S. Attorney's Office for  
the Northern District of California and the San Francisco District 
Office of the Securities and Exchange Commission has begun 
investigations in connection with the earnings restatements. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McKesson HBOC fell nearly 50 percent when it announced  
on April 28 it would have to restate some of its earnings reports. 
McKesson has been unable to recover. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
