<HEADLINE> Harness Driver Thrown From Horse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Harness driver Luc Ouellette was  
thrown from his horse, but escaped serious injury Thursday night 
before the seventh race at the Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Timely Scooter, the horse Ouellette was driving, crashed through  
a rail and unseated his driver. Both Ouellette and the horse 
escaped with just minor injuries. Ouellette was bruised, but was 
able to drive in the next race. 
</P>
<P>
	Ouellette, who turns 34 on July 22, was trying to get the  
3-year-old pacing colt up to the number 10 post position for the 
start of the seventh race. The colt, in his 22nd lifetime start, 
made a right turn into the rail the separates the track surface 
from the winner's circle and paddock and enclosure. 
</P>
<P>
	The force of the impact shattered the fence and sent Ouellette,  
the sport's leading money-winning driver with more than $5.3 
million in purses this year, hurled to the ground in the track's 
winner's circle. 
</P>
<P>
	``My intention was to leave the gate with him,'' Ouellette said.  
``He lagged off and I tapped to keep him up with the field. 
Apparently, he saw the entrance he comes in and out of and decided 
to leave the track. I just got the wind knocked out of me. My 
colors weren't even torn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Timely Scooter suffered a minor cut on his hoof.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has a small laceration of the left rear coronary band (top  
area of hoof),'' said state veterinarian Dr. Eli Perris. 
``Otherwise, he seems normal. He was able to walk back to the 
paddock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ouellette is scheduled to drive Mystical Shark in Saturday  
night's $1 million Meadowlands Pace. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
