<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Vows Strong Push on Farm Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration promises to make  
elimination of foreign barriers to American farm exports the 
centerpiece of upcoming world trade talks. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony Wednesday before a Senate Finance subcommittee on  
trade, administration witnesses said European efforts to sidetrack 
the upcoming round of global trade talks will not work. 
</P>
<P>
	David Aaron, under secretary of commerce for international  
trade, called Europe's tactics the ``ABA strategy -- anything but 
agriculture,'' hoping to include so many issues for negotiators to 
tackle that nothing gets accomplished in the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to reach a deal would preserve current European  
agriculture trade policies, which include high barriers blocking 
sales of many American farm products and trade-distorting 
production subsidies for their domestic crops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make agriculture the centerpiece for progress in  
the round,'' Aaron told the senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher said European  
farmers are the most protected in the world with EU programs 
accounting for 85 percent of total world spending on farm 
subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said U.S. negotiators will push for significant cuts in  
agricultural tariffs and the total elimination of export subsidies, 
which distort trade by driving down global prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is the host for a meeting of trade ministers  
from the 134 nations that belong to the World Trade Organization. 
The WTO conference in Seattle in late November and early December 
is the expected formal launch of a new round of talks with a goal 
of further lowering barriers to trade in manufactured goods, 
services and agriculture. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
