<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo's Main Index Closed Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Taking a cue from an overnight high-technology  
rally on Wall Street, the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index rose 
today for a second consecutive day. The dollar fell against the 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 74.00 points, or 0.40  
percent, closing at 18,431.86. On Wednesday, the average climbed 
176.77 points, or 0.97 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.92 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.20  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level 
of 120.59 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, trading was choppy as foreign investors  
remained enthusiastic buyers of Japanese stocks, but domestic 
financial institutions tried to lock in profits in blue-chip 
stocks, which have risen quickly this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Evans, a strategist at HSBC Securities Japan, said he  
expects the Nikkei index to test the 18,500 mark on Friday, a level 
it last touched in September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average was in negative territory in the morning, but  
the benchmark moved into positive territory after investors bought 
high-tech and international blue chips on dips in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	High-technology issues got a boost after the technology-rich  
Nasdaq Composite Index in New York rose 39.91, or 1.4 percent, to 
end at 2,818.14 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer-chip maker Intel Corp.'s forecast that its profit  
margins would expand in the second half of this year lifted the 
Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 765 million shares changed hands on the Tokyo  
exchange's first section, compared with Wednesday's turnover of 766 
million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the overall gain, decliners outnumbered advancers 637 to  
557, evidence of strong profit-taking pressure following recent 
sharp gains in stock prices, traders said. Meanwhile, 131 shares 
finished the day unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 14.66 points, or 0.98 percent, to finish at 
1,511.73. The TOPIX closed up 13.38 points, or 0.90 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was in a seesaw game between  
Japanese importers and interbank players, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryuichi Takami, senior trader at Sanwa Bank, said the demand for  
dollars by Japanese importers remained strong and dollar sales were 
also strong on diminishing fears of the Bank of Japan intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has sold yen and bought dollars several times  
in recent week to help keep export prices low and help sustain the 
nation's fragile economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.25 yen and 121.40 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 123.54 yen, up from  
123.34 yen late today in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.6800 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6600 
percent, driving its price down to 101.04 yen from 101.21 yen. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
