<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Fund Assets Are Down / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market  
mutual funds fell by $407.8 million in the latest week to $870.72 
billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category fell  
by $157.8 million to $720.42 billion for the week ended Wednesday, 
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund 
assets fell by $250 million to $150.30 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of institutional money market funds fell by $3.68 billion  
to $584.45 billion for the same period. Among institutional funds, 
taxable money market fund assets fell by $2.56 billion to $534.78 
billion; assets of tax-exempt funds fell by $1.12 billion to $49.67 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.455 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.459 trillion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds was  
4.41 percent in the week ended Tuesday, unchanged from the previous 
week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal published in 
Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day average yield 
rose to 4.36 percent from 4.34 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield held at the previous week's 4.51  
percent, and the 30-day compounded yield rose to 4.46 percent from 
4.43 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
58 days, up from 57 days, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts was 2.03 percent as of 
Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.  
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing 
checking accounts held steady at 0.86 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.19 percent  
on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 4.18 percent the 
previous week. Yields were 4.54 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 4.52 
percent; 4.78 percent on 2 1/2-year CDs, up from 4.73 percent; and 
4.94 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 4.92 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
