<HEADLINE> Mary Kay Convention Opens in Dallas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- They dream of one day driving a pink Cadillac.  
``Positive'' is their adjective of choice. And when Mary Kay 
cosmetics disciples mention the company's founder, they may get a 
little misty. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's just an incredible woman,'' gushed Karen Irwin of St.  
Louis. ``Unfortunately, I haven't met her. I mean, I feel like I 
have. From a distance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 40,000 Mary Kay makeup sellers have converged on  
Dallas this week from all around the country for this summer's 
two-week, 14-hotel convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Kay Ash herself doesn't make it to the national meetings  
these days. A plucky Texan who built the direct-sales company 30 
years ago, the aging Ms. Ash is recovering from a stroke and a 
broken leg. But her framed photos cast serene gazes over the Dallas 
Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The manicured fingers of Mary Kay reach far. The company has  
representatives in 29 countries, including Russia and China. Last 
year, 500,000 Mary Kay vendors sold more than $1 billion worth of 
merchandise worldwide, according to spokeswoman Shelley Whiddon. 
</P>
<P>
	The women who pay their $100 fee to join the Mary Kay sales  
force are handed a mantra, a set of priorities and a prescribed 
mental outlook along with the standard case of creams and powders. 
They must wear skirts or dresses. They must not drink or smoke. 
They must tell themselves, over and over, ``I am making other 
people's lives better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big sales bring lavish rewards -- diamond bar pins, diamond  
rings, cars and the ultimate prize: the pink Cadillac. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is struggling to shed its image as a work force for  
housewives only. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have this image of big, blond hair,'' said Ms. Irwin, a  
former corporate executive whose brown hair is cropped short. ``But 
we're teachers, CPAs, financial directors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After two marriages, a stint running a metaphysics bookstore and  
a few years driving a Federal Express truck, Sally Fairbanks of 
Orlando, Fla., joined the Mary Kay sales force. She liked the idea 
of setting her own hours, pulling down high pay and working outside 
the office. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women have come full circle,'' Ms. Fairbanks said,  
speedwalking into the convention center in a crush of perfumed 
women. ``We've got it all. Now we want to give some of it back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
