<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Boss Kicks Off American Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The Boss is back in town.  
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Springsteen kicked off his American tour Thursday night  
with a sold-out concert, the first in a 15-night stand at New 
Jersey's Continental Airlines Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Springsteen, who has been recording solo in recent years, has  
reunited with his E Street band for his first tour with them in 11 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour was also a reunion for fans Doug North of Morris Plains  
and pal Drew Santucci from Stanhope, who were among the fans 
milling around the parking lot hours before the 8 p.m. show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wonderful to get back together and remember how it was  
when we wore younger men's clothes,'' said Santucci, 38. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Horvath, 21, was seeing Springsteen for the first time.  
His high school basketball coach introduced him to the music when 
he was 14. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the way he dances. He gets so into his own music and  
it's really easy to relate to. He talks about stuff that everybody 
knows,'' Horvath said. 
</P>
<P>
	To celebrate the Freehold native's return and give early  
arrivals a fun way to kill time, the New Jersey Sports and 
Exposition Authority created a mini-boardwalk in the parking lot. 
It had volleyball courts, carnival games, stands selling 
sausage-and-pepper sandwiches and a DJ cranking out Springsteen 
songs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans snatched up 308,000 tickets for the 15 New Jersey shows  
from Thursday to Aug. 12. The 15-night stand in a single arena sets 
an industry record, breaking Springsteen's own mark of 11 shows in 
East Rutherford in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the first time Springsteen and his band have hit the road  
since a 1988 tour for Amnesty International. They have already 
finished a 17-city European tour. 
</P>
<P>
	After the New Jersey shows, they move on to Detroit, Boston,  
Washington, D.C., and Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the last great rock 'n' roll tour of the century,'' said  
Robert Santelli, a vice president at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame 
and Museum in Cleveland. ``He embodied a whole lot of New Jersey 
culture in his music. ... He gave a sense of pride to a lot of 
young people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
