<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Falkland Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton welcomes the agreement  
Britain and Argentina reached to reduce tension over the Falkland 
Islands, press secretary Joe Lockhart said today. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the accord demonstrated ``the determination of both  
Argentina and the United Kingdom to work cooperatively and 
constructively to promote the well-being and stability of the 
region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Britain and Argentina agreed Wednesday on a package of measures  
that included lifting a ban on Argentines visiting the islands, 
resuming direct flights from Chile and cooperating on fish 
preservation in the South Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures marked the most significant thaw in relations  
between the two nations since they went to war over the islands 
that Argentina calls the Malvinas in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. statement referred to both the Falklands and the  
Malvinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said Clinton congratulated British Prime Minister Tony  
Blair and Argentine President Carlos Menem for reaching the 
agreement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
