<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Milosevic Front Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- When Slobodanka Vojinovic heard that  
Serbia's most powerful opposition leader plans to launch his own 
wave of anti-government rallies, she rolled her eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anything,'' said the 31-year-old office worker,  
her voice weary. ``It's all the same as before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Not Again!'' response by the Serbs to a flood of protest  
rallies announced by various opposition groups is typical. Despite 
an overwhelming popular feeling that President Slobodan Milosevic 
should be ousted, most Serbs believe opposition leaders should go 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like any of them,'' declares Dragan Milovanovic, a  
photographer. ``Things have reached rock bottom, we need new 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Milovanovic, 32, pro-democracy leader Zoran Djindjic is an  
``actor.'' Another leader, Vuk Draskovic, is a little better, but 
still not good enough. Frowning, Milovanovic tries hard to remember 
a politician he likes: ``I've heard something good about 
somebody,'' he mutters, his voice trailing away into silence. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb skepticism about their pro-democracy leaders stems from the  
opposition's past performance. Instead of uniting to exploit 
massive anti-government feelings and protests to remove Milosevic 
from power, they feuded among themselves at crucial times. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past decade of Milosevic's rule, Serbs rose up against  
him four times, enduring police beatings and other hardship. But 
each of the protests collapsed, mainly because the opposition 
leaders were divided or they decided to make a deal with Milosevic. 
Their credibility now is near zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Serbia's defeat by NATO and virtual loss of Kosovo to  
the ethnic Albanian majority, discontent with Milosevic's rule is 
greater than ever. But trust in the opposition remains low. 
</P>
<P>
	``I welcome any anti-Milosevic activity, but I also wish they  
(the opposition) had some kind of strategy, some vision,'' lamented 
Dusan Stojkovic, 29. ``I wish there was more coordination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the main pro-democracy group, the Alliance for Change,  
has held rallies throughout Serbia, campaigning for Milosevic's 
resignation. Thousands have attended the protests, leading to 
expectations that they would grow. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the latest protests, some 5,000 people gathered  
Wednesday in the northern city of Subotica and clashed briefly with 
pro-government supporters before dispersing. The anti-Milosevic 
demonstration was called by the Alliance for Change and a coalition 
of local parties. 
</P>
<P>
	More violence was reported today in Belgrade, where  
pro-democracy activists said they were attacked while organizing a 
petition for Milosevic's ouster. Dragan Kopcalic, of the Democratic 
Party, said three people were hospitalized and one activist, 
Slobodan Djodjevic, was seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Draskovic with a now familiar move. On Tuesday, he  
announced separate protest rallies, with the first one to be held 
in Kragujevac on Saturday, only two days after the Alliance for 
Change plans its own rally in the same town. 
</P>
<P>
	Another opposition group planned protest in the northern town of  
Subotica today. Daily protests are being held in the southern city 
of Leskovac and a series of separate anti-Milosevic demonstrations 
planned into August is making it hard even for protesters to keep 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	``We welcome all actions against the government,'' Slobodan  
Vuksanovic from the Alliance for Change commented on Draskovic's 
decision to hold rallies. ``But we must be very careful not to 
disperse people's energy and patience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic's decision to rejoin the protest movement has left  
some Serbs shaking their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic in the past led the most massive anti-Milosevic  
protests, but joined the Milosevic-led government earlier this year 
only to be kicked out after criticizing the Serb leader's hardline 
policies during the NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	His constant vacillation has cost Draskovic in terms of popular  
support. But the bearded writer-turned-politician is still believed 
to be the one most capable of mounting serious anti-government 
demonstrations. And the fact that he was fired by Milosevic during 
the NATO bombing has helped him regain some of his former 
popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	Sociologist Boza Jaksic says all political figures must go --  
whether governing or in the opposition -- ``so that a democratic 
change could happen in Serbia.'' He says current opposition leaders 
``do not carry democratic potential'' because they are identified 
with past failures. 
</P>
<P>
	The most powerful protests of the past months were spontaneous,  
without input from any established political group. 
</P>
<P>
	In the western town of Valjevo, the citizens said they were  
protesting against both the government and the ``incompetent 
opposition.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
