<HEADLINE> Emilio Navaira Returns To His Roots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Tex-Mex singer Emilio Navaira has returned to  
his Spanish-language roots after making an unsuccessful attempt to 
make it big in the English-language country market. 
</P>
<P>
	The award-winning Texan was in Mexico City on Tuesday to promote  
his latest album ``Mi Primer Amor,'' or ``My First Love,'' which 
has 15 songs in Castellano Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't do very well singing in English, but I'm not  
disappointed. In this business there are good and bad moments. What 
is important is that we have been on the scene for 10 years,'' 
Navaira said. 
</P>
<P>
	Navaira has been honored 24 times by the Tejano Music Awards and  
was nominated for a Grammy. He started his career singing alongside 
Tejana music star Selena, who was shot to death in 1995 by the head 
of her fan club. 
</P>
<P>
	Navaira credits the success of Tex-Mex music in part to Selena.  
</P>
<P>
	``Selena was and continues to be the queen of Tex-Mex,'' he  
said. ``Her support of the genre was invaluable and we owe much to 
her.'' 
  	   	
</P>
