<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montgomery Ward Bankruptcy Exit OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Montgomery Ward &AMP; Co., the nation's  
seventh-largest department store chain, won approval Thursday to 
emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after the venerable retailer appeared headed for  
extinction, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Peter Walsh gave the go-ahead for 
Wards to do its business without protection from creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Wards would distribute more than $650 million to unsecured  
creditors, amounting to about 28 cents on the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its restructuring, the company also agreed earlier to  
sell its profitable Signature Group direct marketing unit to GE 
Capital Inc., its single largest creditor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based company in the past few years has sold or  
shuttered unprofitable stores and embarked on an ambitious makeover 
strategy that has brought more customers back into its remaining 
252 full-line stores. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
