<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> P&AMP;G, University Research Obesity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Scientists from Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. and the  
University of Cincinnati College of Medicine will collaborate in 
obesity research that P&AMP;G is supporting with up to $5 million, the 
medical school announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The project is designed to provide a better understanding of how  
appetite-controlling neurotransmitters in the brain help control 
eating and body weight. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers said they hope to learn why higher-fat diets can  
increase body weight and if the body becomes more efficient in 
storing fat when given a steady diet of higher-fat foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Woods, director of the university's Obesity Research  
Center, said the researchers want to find out why a high-fat diet 
can cause a person to eat more and become obese, and learn how body 
fat may alter the secretion of hormones that affect hunger. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, a professor of psychiatry, said the scientists plan  
experiments to examine several hormones that influence food intake 
and body weight through their interaction with each other and on 
the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the National Institutes of Health, obesity is  
second only to cigarette smoking as a cause of preventable deaths 
in the United States. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
