<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oracle Plans Boston-Area Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Software giant Oracle Corp. has announced plans to  
expand its area operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle, the No. 1 maker of database software, is looking for a  
new site in the Boston area to build a new facility for 975 
employees already located in the region, plus 1,000 new employees 
the company plans to hire over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle's East Coast telephone operations and one of its largest  
development facilities are already located in Boston. A 273-person 
center operated by Oracle in Nashua, N.H., will not be affected by 
the new facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle Corp. has recently shifted its focus from database  
software to Internet- and customer service-related software 
applications. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the company acquired Concord-based E-Travel, Inc. for  
$35 million. E-Travel makes software that allows consumers to book 
business trips on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to become an e-business as fast as we can,''  
Oracle CEO Jeffrey Henley told The Boston Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also is moving forward to challenge arch rival  
Microsoft Corp.'s dominance of the operating systems market. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, Oracle and Sun Microsystems Inc., maker of business  
computers, announced a pact to sell new business computers 
developed to blunt the dominance of Microsoft's operating software. 
The companies plan to use a combination of Oracle's software and 
Sun's computers to make a business computer that won't require the 
use of an operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Microsystems has a $250 million East Coast base located in  
Burlington. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
