<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Aide Was at Odds With Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's newest campaign  
strategist masterminded the tobacco industry ads opposing President 
Clinton's effort to fight teen-age smoking. His firm also has 
represented several other clients at odds with Clinton-Gore 
policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter Eskew is taking a leave of absence from his job as  
partner of the BSMG Worldwide public relations firm. But he will 
continue as a paid consultant even as he advises Gore, the firm 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A longtime Democratic political consultant, Eskew moved into the  
corporate world after working on the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1992, 
becoming head of the BSMG division that produced advertising to 
push client views on political issues. 
</P>
<P>
	BSMG has represented several well-known companies, including  
Northwest Airlines, Visa and Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Eskew personally developed the tobacco ad campaign that helped  
derail legislation, championed by Clinton and Gore, that would have 
raised cigarette taxes and curbed teen-age smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the Republican National Committee, Jim  
Nicholson, whose party killed the tobacco bill in the Senate, has 
accused Gore of hypocrisy for hiring Eskew. Anti-smoking activists 
and congressional watchdog groups also have questioned the move. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Al Gore really believed his own speechifying about values,  
he wouldn't hire a front man for the merchants of death, the 
tobacco industry,'' said Gary Ruskin, director of the Congressional 
Accountability Project. 
</P>
<P>
	Eskew did not return several calls seeking comment. But Gore  
campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said the vice president's stand on 
tobacco remains strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's worked hard to pass tobacco legislation and he's fought  
to keep tobacco out of the hands of children and he will continue 
to do so,'' Salazar said. ``This doesn't change that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eskew's ads portrayed the tobacco bill as a big government,  
tax-and-spend boondoggle. One ad warned that the bill would mean 
``half a trillion dollars in new taxes ... 17 new government 
bureaucracies. Cigarettes up to $5 a pack ... Huge job losses among 
farmers, retailers and small businesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another ad featured a noisy cuckoo clock and insisted  
``Washington has gone cuckoo again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Senate Republicans defeated the tobacco bill in June 1998,  
Clinton said, ``No one doubts that this came about, in part, 
because of an unanswered $40 million advertising campaign by the 
tobacco companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Novelli of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids called Gore's  
decision to hire Eskew ``a bitter irony.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy not only did this huge advertising campaign but it was  
a misleading advertising campaign, something that we're not going 
to soon forget,'' Novelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the other hand,'' he said, ``we are very sure that Gore's  
commitment to protecting kids from tobacco is real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1996, Gore brought delegates to the Democratic  
National Convention to the verge of tears when he told of the 
painful death of his older sister from smoking-related cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore promised to protect children from the dangers of smoking  
``until I draw my last breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president later admitted that he continued to receive  
annual checks from his family's tobacco farm for several years 
after his sister's death. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
