<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> OK, So What Would You Name a Horse? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	What's in a name?  
</P>
<P>
	In the case of racehorses, there's a lot of thought, and in some  
instances a touch of mischief. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of Edward A. ``Buddy'' Bishop, there's a lot of  
work, some laughs and an occasional headache. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Smells, sired by Odor in the Court, is a name Bishop,  
registrar of The Jockey Club, appreciates. 
</P>
<P>
	He also smiles at Don't Take Any, the name of a horse by Plugged  
Nickel out of Wooden, and Your Tent or Mine, whose dame was Wigwam. 
</P>
<P>
	There also are names that make Bishop cringe, or worse. It's his  
job and that of his staff to make sure vulgar or suggestive names 
aren't accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes one slips by.  
</P>
<P>
	``If we catch them (suggestive or vulgar names) before they  
race, we can call them back,'' Bishop said. Names can also be 
changed by the Board of Stewards or The Jockey Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Owner Mike Pegram has tried to slip several names past Bishop,  
who is on the alert. After having several names for a horse 
rejected by Bishop, Pegram finally got one accepted. It was 
Censored. In another instance, a frustrated Pegram submitted and 
had accepted Buddynamedme. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop said he and his staff has to approve the names about  
34,000 horses a year, and that 59 percent of the time the first 
name submitted is accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually six names are submitted, and a horse can be named at no  
cost up to Feb. 1 of his or her 2-year-old. There is a $50 fee 
after that and a $100 fee for name changes. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent name change was that of Columbine Is Sad, named long  
before the shooting incident at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``The owner said if he couldn't change the name, he would retire  
the horse,'' Bishop said. ``It was changed to Dake, a family 
name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five people check name requests, making sure they are within the  
rules, and then a final check in made by Bishop, who said, ``I'm 
the dirty old man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suggestive or double-entendre names are not the only ones Bishop  
and crew must guard against. ``In this day and age, you've got to 
be politically correct,'' he said, noting names that are 
inoffensive to some can insult members of religious and ethnic 
groups and minorities. Names such as squaw and injun are no-no's. 
</P>
<P>
	Classes of names not eligible for use include names consisting  
of more than 18 letters (spaces and punctuations marks county as 
letters); names ending in ``filly,'' ``colt. ``stud, ``mare,'' 
``stallion'' or any similar horse-related terms; names of persons 
without their written permission; names of famous people no longer 
living, without approval of the Board of Stewards, and names of 
notorious people. The Jockey Club doesn't want to hear about Jack 
the Ripper being the Kentucky Derby favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade names and copyrighted material also cannot be used as  
horse names, and names of horses currently active in racing or 
breeding cannot be duplicated. Also unacceptable are names similar 
in spelling or pronunciation to those already in use. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is a permanent list of names that can never be used  
again -- names such as Secretariat or Man o'War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
