<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injured Ford Workers OK Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Two workers injured in an explosion at  
Ford Motor Co.'s Rouge complex have accepted a settlement of $1 
million each plus part of their salaries until age 65, their lawyer 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Drouillard said he expects his clients to sign the  
No. 2 automaker's offer by the end of the month. Two of his other 
clients are considering the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Arrington, 47, of Detroit and another worker who was not  
identified accepted the offer, which requires them not to sue or 
comment, the Detroit Free Press reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to settle comes before any report on the blast  
cause has been released, and before any lawsuits have been filed 
against Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Six workers died and 14 were seriously injured in the explosion  
at the complex in Dearborn. So far, three lawsuits on behalf of 
workers have been filed against Rouge Steel, which co-owns the 
plant with Ford. If Rouge Steel played a role in the plant's 
maintenance, it could be found liable under a looser standard than 
the employers, attorneys said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo recently obtained by The Detroit News, Ford said it  
would make an offer totaling $30 million to the families of the six 
people killed and the 14 injured in the Feb. 1 explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Drouillard said he urged his clients to accept the offer because  
it might be difficult to win against Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	``The settlement is by no means an accurate reflection of the  
damages these people suffered,'' he told the Free Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Some other attorneys also are recommending acceptance of the  
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Norm Tucker, who represents one of those killed in the explosion  
at the complex's power plant, said recent efforts to cut down on 
jury awards help justify accepting Ford's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer reportedly includes Ford's paying the salaries,  
benefits and medical insurance for the injured workers, and the 
families of the six deceased workers, until they are or would have 
been 65. 
</P>
<P>
	The Free Press reported that some workers are holding out. They  
say they want to wait until the state report is released. That 
report will look at the cause as well as whether Ford committed any 
safety violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Some family members of the killed workers are upset that they  
would receive the same amount as injured workers. Other injured 
workers are irked because they say that they will not be allowed to 
talk about the blast after they sign the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	And some workers or families have yet to be contacted by Ford  
about the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford also would provide trust funds for the minor children of  
the workers killed and injured. The trust funds are valued at about 
$100,000 each, the News reported recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Each family also would receive a separate $25,000 payment that  
can be used for any purpose, including to pay for a memorial or to 
donate to charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokesman John Spelich has declined to discuss the offers.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
