<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 10:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese-American Monument Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Fine Arts Commission put off a decision  
today on what inscriptions should grace a planned monument near the 
Capitol honoring the patriotism of Japanese-Americans in World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some wonderful quotes, but there are too many of  
them,'' Chairman J. Carter Brown told the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested limiting the quotations as far as possible to  
statements by Presidents Truman, Ford and Reagan, praising the 
Japanese-Americans, and a listing of the internment camps. The 
three presidents and many others condemned the internments, ordered 
by President Franklin D. Roosevelt and upheld by the Supreme Court 
as a war measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The memorial, a 7-foot-3-inch granite wall, will list about 840  
names, including Japanese-American war veterans, ``of those who 
lost their lives, or are missing in action in service to their 
country.'' The wall would be the centerpiece of a quarter-acre park 
between Union Station and the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Inscriptions will be etched on each of six narrative panels and  
at the entrance and exit of the memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an effort to tell a 45-year story as succinctly as  
possible,'' said John Parsons, who was representing Interior 
Secretary Bruce Babbitt today before the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The presidential quotes under consideration:  
</P>
<P>
	Reagan: ``Here we admit a wrong. Here we affirm our commitment  
as a nation to equal justice under the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Truman: ``You fought not only the enemy, but you fought  
prejudice. ... And you won. Keep up the fight to make this great 
republic stand for what the Constitution says it stands for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford: ``Not only was evacuation wrong ... we have learned from  
the tragedy to forever treasure liberty and justice for each 
individual American, and resolve that this kind of action shall 
never be repeated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another proposed inscription says: ``Japanese-Americans were  
forced to abandon homes, friends, farms and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Allowed only what they could carry, more than 115,000  
individuals were evacuated to remote internment camps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese-Americans appealed against the restrictions in 1943,  
and the case reached the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Still another inscription would say: ``The court ruled that the  
adoption by government, in crisis of war and threatened invasion, 
of measures of public safety, is not wholly beyond the limits of 
the Constitution and is not to be condemned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1988 Congress approved reparations of $20,000 to each of  
those sent to the camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry Tsutsumida, executive director of the private group  
raising money for the Japanese-American Patriotism Memorial, said 
she knows of no objections to the inscriptions. She favors adding a 
quote from Rep. Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., one of two 
Japanese-Americans serving in the U.S. Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	A quote from Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii is proposed for the  
inscription at the exit: ``The lessons learned ... must remain ... 
as a grave reminder of what we must not allow to happen again to 
any group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also up before the Fine Arts Commission is a proposed memorial  
to Mohandas Gandhi, whose teaching of nonviolence helped bring 
independence to India. It too will be a small park, with a 10-foot 
statue of Gandhi, on Massachusetts Avenue facing the Indian 
Embassy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
