<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Killer Says He Wants To Live </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMERICUS, Ga. (AP) -- A man who tauntingly urged jurors to send  
him to the electric chair after admitting to two murders now says 
he wants to live. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Colwell's lawyer, Michael Mears, is seeking a new trial  
for Colwell in the July 1996 deaths of a couple gunned down in the 
parking lot of an Americus Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	Colwell is on death row at the state prison in Jackson.  
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge R. Rucker Smith has already rejected one  
new-trial motion, but Mears recently filed an amended motion that 
included a letter from Colwell. 
</P>
<P>
	``I very much want to go to a state mental hospital to get help  
to save my life,'' Colwell said in the June 28 letter to Mears. ``I 
am very sorry for killing those people. I don't want to continue to 
be a murderer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colwell, a former football star at Arizona Western College and  
Middle Tennessee State University, drew a smiley face next to his 
signature. 
</P>
<P>
	At his October trial, Colwell testified that he killed Mitchell  
and Judith Bell because he was depressed and wanted the state to 
kill him, something he lacked the courage to do himself. 
</P>
<P>
	He also taunted jurors with threats to return and kill or  
torture them and their families if they failed to give him a death 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney John R. Parks said Wednesday he doesn't  
believe Colwell's change of heart is grounds for a new trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
