<DOCNO> APW19990715.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Nixes Patient Suits vs. HMOs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Turning to one of the most contentious issues  
in the weeklong debate, the Senate today killed a Democratic 
provision that would have enabled some patients to sue their health 
plans. Health plans that fall under federal regulations cannot now 
be sued. The Senate voted 53-47 against the provision, which 
Democrats had argued would force insurers to put a patient's health 
before the company bottom line. President Clinton said he was 
bewildered by the rejection. ``The health insurers won't let them 
do it,'' Clinton said of the Republicans, who control the Senate. 
Republicans say the cost and expense of lengthy court fights would 
hurt patients. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Columbine Teens  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Urging Congress to heed ``the lobbyists who  
truly matter, our children,'' President Clinton today challenged 
lawmakers to pass gun control legislation before the nation's 
students return to classes in September. The president, joined by 
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Attorney General Janet 
Reno, met with more than 80 students from Colorado -- including some 
from Columbine High School -- to hear their concerns about the 
prospects of passage of tougher gun control laws. The president 
invited the students to the White House to help his campaign for 
mandatory background checks on buyers at gun shows, and to require 
child safety locks on handguns. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Says He'll Forgo Matching Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- After raising a record $37 million for his  
Republican presidential campaign, Texas Gov. George W. Bush 
announced today that he will not accept federal matching funds and 
the spending limitations that go with them. The Republican 
presidential front-runner said that if he accepts the matching 
funds his campaign would have been restricted by spending limits in 
early states like Iowa and New Hampshire. Bush will now be able to 
spend as much as he wants in pursuit of the Republican presidential 
nomination. Steve Forbes already has indicated that he won't accept 
matching funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Seeks End to Racial Profiling  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told the NAACP today that  
ending the practice of racial profiling by police departments would 
be a top priority in his presidential administration. ``If I'm 
elected president, ending racial profiling will be the first civil 
rights act of the new century,'' Gore said to a standing ovation, 
Gore told 3,000 NAACP members on the closing day of the 
organization's annual national convention. Black advocates say 
racial profiling, the police practice of singling out minorities 
for questioning at airports, on highways and on streets, is often 
at the crux of fatal shootings. 

</P>
<P>
	British Airways Fined $4 Million  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- British Airways was ordered today to pay $4 million  
to 61 French passengers whose plane made an unexpected stop in 
Kuwait the day the Gulf War began. The passengers were taken 
hostage by Iraq, who used them as ``human shields'' against 
U.S.-led bombings. France's highest court ruled that British 
Airways had exposed the passengers, who were headed from London to 
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, to the risk of war ``without good reason.'' 
The passengers accused the airline of stopping in order to drop off 
British commandos. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus Hijacker Killed in Greece  
</P>
<P>
	PALESTRA, Greece (AP) -- Police stormed a hijacked bus today,  
killing an Albanian immigrant after a two-day hostage drama that 
has escalated anti-immigrant furor across Greece. The five hostages 
were not injured in the raid, authorities said. The assualt came 
just 30 minutes after the hijacker, armed with two hand grenades, 
released two hostages. One of the grenades exploded during the 
raid, but it was not immediately clear how the hostage-taker was 
killed. The hijacker commandeered the bus yesterday to protest 
alleged police abuses. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 34; Nasdaq Up 8  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 34.52 points at 11,182.62. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,574-1,222. The Nasdaq was up 8.80 at 
2,826.93. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras To Sit Out Davis Cup Singles  
</P>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Pete Sampras, the No. 3 singles player  
in the world, will play only doubles for the United States in its 
Davis Cup quarterfinal against Australia. Today's draw cannot be 
changed except in case of injury. The singles matches tomorrow will 
be Todd Martin against Lleyton Hewitt and Jim Courier against 
Patrick Rafter. The pairings will be reversed on Sunday. Sampras 
will play doubles with Alex O'Brien on Saturday against Sandon 
Stolle and Mark Woodforde. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  




  	   	
</P>
