<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Warner Studio Chiefs Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The two leaders of Warner Bros.' movie,  
television and music division surprised Hollywood Thursday by 
announcing their resignations, ending one of the entertainment 
industry's longest-running success stories and leaving a huge 
management void. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel, chairmen and co-chief executives  
of Warner Bros. and Warner Music Group, said they will remain until 
Dec. 31, when their current contracts expire. They've worked 
together running Warner Bros. operations since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly and Semel are leaving at a time when their company appears  
to be on a roll, with recent box office successes of films such as 
``The Matrix'' and the ``Austin Powers'' sequel. Stanley Kubrick's 
final film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' debuts Friday and is expected to do 
well. Earnings for parent company Time Warner were up 8 percent in 
the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men said they wanted to pursue new ventures, but declined  
in an interview to elaborate, or say for sure if they would 
continue their partnership in any new undertakings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept asking myself if I wouldn't like to have one more  
challenge in my life,'' said Semel. ``If I was going to do that, 
this is the right time for both my company and myself to take that 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``At what point in your life do you decide you can, if you want,  
to try something else? For me it was when the company was healthy 
and things were going well,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	News of their departure worried Wall Street. Shares of Time  
Warner fell $1.43 3/4, or nearly 2 percent, to $75.87 1/2 on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's negative,'' said Jessica Reif Cohen, an analyst  
with Merrill Lynch. ``I think Bob and Terry are the most stable 
management team in entertainment history. They've had a long and 
successful run, but the company is very large and has a great 
breadth of management talent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Daly and Semel were successful partly because they  
avoided the infighting and ego conflicts that often mark Hollywood 
business relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty rare to have co-chairmen of a major entity, which  
in itself is part of an even larger entity, and not have their own 
egos get in the way of being partners and managing others,'' said 
James Goss, an analyst with Barrington Research Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin, Daly and Semel denied reports of friction with Time  
Warner Chairman Gerald Levin over concerns that their 
responsibilities were too broad. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just not the case. There's never been any friction  
between or amongst us, I can state that clearly,'' said Levin, who 
joined Daly and Semel for an interview. ``I don't know where this 
came from, but I'm the one who decided we should run our music 
company and studio together. I really believe in it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The current management structure will remain in place after  
Semel and Daly leave, Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm even more convinced they should be run together,'' Levin  
said. ``There is so much synergy between music and film and the 
possibility of doing things online.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Daly-Semel partnership began in 1980 when Daly was hired as  
chairman of the Warner Bros. studio, joining Semel, who was vice 
president and chief operating officer. Semel became chairman and 
co-CEO of Warner Bros. in 1994. The music division was combined 
with the movie and TV operations a year later and the pair was 
named co-CEOs. 
</P>
<P>
	When they started with the company, the film and television  
group had revenues of less than $1 billion. By the end of 1998, it 
reported revenues of approximately $6 billion. The film and 
television division and Warner Music Group reported combined 
revenues of an estimated $10 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Other successful films during the Daly-Semel era have included  
the ``Lethal Weapon'' and ``Batman'' movies, ``The Killing 
Fields,'' ``Driving Miss Daisy'' and ``Unforgiven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly and Semel said they had decidedly separately to leave, and  
began talking about their decisions privately about two months ago. 
They informed Levin and the Time Warner board on Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
