<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Libbey Drops Latest Oneida Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Glassware maker Libbey Inc. has abandoned  
its latest effort to acquire flatware giant Oneida Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida management rejected a $625 million offer earlier this  
month and has been adamantly opposed to Libbey's previous takeover 
bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo-based Libbey said Thursday it was disappointed with  
Oneida's response. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies want to become complete suppliers of table-top  
products: silverware, glassware, china, linen and other 
accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	Libbey, a leading glassware maker, made the $37.50 per share  
offer to Oneida shareholders in late June, its third attempt since 
1995 to control the world's largest silverware maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida, which has 4,700 employees worldwide and is based in  
Oneida, N.Y., also is a strong competitor of Libbey's in the 
glassware and other table-top products markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida board members said they rejected the proposal because it  
included ``substantial contingencies and uncertainties'' including 
concerns over financing and antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies are equal in size, but Oneida has become  
vulnerable to a takeover in the last year because it has gone 
through a major restructuring following a 30 percent drop in 
earnings in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Libbey had revenue of $439.5 million last year with profits of  
$25.4 million, off 30 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Oneida had sales of $465.9 million last year, but after years of  
growth, profits fell 32 percent to $19.8 million. That prompted the 
company to restructure and lay off 300 workers since January while 
closing two foreign plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Libbey rose 18 3/4 cents to $31.12 1/2, while shares of  
Oneida fell 75 cents to $27.75, both in trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
