<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush's Six-Month Total: $37 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush reported today that  
he had raised a record $37 million for his Republican presidential 
campaign -- even more than his earlier estimate -- and had more than 
$30 million in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	With a bank account of that size, the GOP front-runner announced  
in Iowa today that he will not accept federal matching funds and 
the spending limitations that go with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got limits that constrain a candidate,'' Bush said. ``I  
want to be in a position to respond. I want to be in a position to 
plan, and I want to be in a position to plan according to need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, publisher Steve Forbes once again exhibited his  
willingness to self-finance his campaign, contributing $6 million 
of his own money between April and June and raising an additional 
$2.7 million. During the first six months of the year, Forbes took 
in $9.5 million, including $6.6 million of his own money. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes reported spending $8.2 million through June 30, and the  
campaign reported debts of $1.4 million and a bank account balance 
of $1.2 million -- leaving the campaign $200,000 in debt. Bush, on 
the other hand, spent only $7.1 million during the first six months 
of the year and had a bank account balance of $30.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole reported  
raising $3.5 million during the first six months of the year, 
including $2.8 million between April and June. She had $1.8 million 
in the bank June 30. Dole's campaign reported that 43 percent of 
those contributing at least $200 were women. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our campaign is gaining strength and momentum,'' Dole said  
today. ``This campaign is on its way to making history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, former Sen. Bill Bradley reported  
raising $11.7 million during the first six months of 1999 and had 
$7.5 million in the bank as of June 30. The campaign said it had 
received more than $240,000 in contributions through its web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the ways our campaign is doing things differently is by  
working to bring new people into the process,'' campaign chairman 
Douglas Berman said. ``We believe that the Internet is a valuable 
tool in getting people involved in the campaign who might not have 
done so in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush already has raised more money than the $32 million that  
1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole took in for his entire 
campaign. Bush's campaign counted more than 74,000 contributors, 
with an average contribution of $467. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am honored and humbled by this outpouring of support from my  
fellow citizens,'' Bush said today. ``The fact that individual 
Americans care enough about the future of our country to send 
contributions ranging from $5 to a maximum of $1,000 says that my 
message of prosperity with a purpose is resonating in every 
community in this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other candidates also were scheduled to file their midyear  
reports today with the Federal Election Commission. Previously, 
Vice President Al Gore indicated he would raise $18.2 million to 
$18.5 million, and his Democratic challenger, former Sen. Bill 
Bradley, said he would raise $11.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, Sen. John McCain said he would raise  
$4.1 million, plus $2 million transferred from his Senate campaign 
account; Gary Bauer and former Vice President Dan Quayle said they 
would raise about $3.4 million apiece; and Lamar Alexander said he 
would raise $2 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
