<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Says He's 100 Percent Retired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *AP Sports Writers    	
</P>
<P>
	LONG GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- Remember when Michael Jordan said he was  
``99.9 percent'' sure he was finished with basketball? Well, bump 
it up to 100 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six months after announcing his retirement, Jordan said Thursday  
his days of playing basketball are definitely over. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, it's 100 percent,'' he said after playing in a pro-am  
with Raymond Floyd in the Ameritech Senior Open. ``A lot of you 
guys anticipated that I would be not happy in retirement. I'm at 
peace with the world. I wake up and do whatever, and I love that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan admitted he did feel ``a little bit of an itch'' during  
the playoffs, but he went out, played a few more rounds of golf and 
it went away. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as I'm busy, I don't think about it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He's played only three times in the last year, and in a sure  
sign his days of ruling the NBA are over, he no longer hears gossip 
firsthand. He hasn't even talked to Phil Jackson since Jackson took 
over as coach of the Los Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he hasn't worked out since the Chicago Bulls won their  
sixth NBA title in June 1998, Jordan still looks like he could suit 
up and play. He hasn't gained weight and there's not even a hint of 
a post-retirement pot belly. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not for lack of trying, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm working,'' he said, grabbing his stomach and laughing.  
``It just doesn't seem to want to pop out. It's not because I 
haven't tried. What you see is just a product of my metabolism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So what does His Airness do with all of his free time? Golf,  
golf and more golf. He plays two or three rounds a day and is down 
to a 4 handicap. Earlier this summer, he took a bunch of buddies to 
Ireland and Scotland, where they played 20 courses in 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of them had a hard time with two-a-days. But they have a  
better appreciation for Michael Jordan's love for the game,'' he 
said, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	While he's not ruling out the possibility of playing golf  
professionally someday, he also knows he's got a lot more work to 
do. On Thursday, he ran into trouble on the 18th hole, dribbling 
his drive into a marsh area and hitting a tree with his second 
shot. He finally picked up the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows I need some improvement. I'm not on Raymond's caliber  
yet,'' he said. ``Even the greatest athlete can have some 
humiliating situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan shot a 13-over 85 during the pro-am, and admitted he was  
a little nervous playing. The gallery was huge, with crowds lining 
every hole and fairway. Fans screamed out his name, and dozens of 
hands reached out to touch him as he walked between holes. 
</P>
<P>
	There were little kids wearing Jordan jerseys and business men  
and women still dressed in suits. People took pictures and everyone 
wanted an autograph. One woman even asked Jordan to sign her 
diploma from North Carolina, Jordan's alma mater. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan looked more at ease than he did last year, when his  
future was on everyone's mind. He bantered back and forth with the 
crowd, and playfully chastised a police officer walking with his 
group when the officer guzzled a Powerade -- a competitor of 
Gatorade, which Jordan endorses. 
</P>
<P>
	The funniest sight was on the 13th hole. Someone hung a bed  
sheet that read, ``Hey Mike, Remember Me!'' from the second story 
of a house overlooking the hole. Jordan laughed when he saw it, and 
chuckled again when he noticed a young man standing on top of the 
house with a video camera. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he'd fallen, it would be my fault,'' Jordan said. ``But  
it's amazing what people will do to gain your attention. But also 
pay their respects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Jordan's future, he has no firm plans other than to hang  
out with his friends and family and play more golf. He has no 
regrets that his attempt to buy the Charlotte Hornets fell through, 
and said it's still possible he will own a team someday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything's possible,'' he said. ``Other than me playing  
basketball.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 08:26:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ulster Unionists Nix Nominations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's major  
Protestant party refused today to nominate ministers for the new 
provincial administration, a long-delayed decision that threw years 
of peacemaking efforts into disarray. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ulster Unionists refused even to attend today's session of  
Belfast's year-old legislature. Their unexpectedly stubborn stand 
dealt a severe blow to British Prime Minister Tony Blair's hopes of 
forming an administration of Protestants and Catholics after a year 
of deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam  
announced that the British and Irish governments would meet next 
week to plan a comprehensive ``review'' summit with Northern 
Ireland's key parties, designed to salvage last year's Good Friday 
peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Mowlam said politicians should ``not seek to blame any party''  
for this ``very serious setback.'' She said, ``The reality is we 
either move forward together or we do not move forward at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart called  
the developments ``a setback.'' He said President Clinton 
``believes there's clearly a mandate among all the people for 
peace, and that the parties need to stay at this until they find a 
way to solve their differences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The legislature last year elected Ulster Unionist leader David  
Trimble to lead an intended four-party, 12-member Cabinet, the core 
institution envisaged in April 1998's peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trimble's badly divided party has refused to support the  
formation of any administration that includes the Irish Republican 
Army-linked Sinn Fein party unless the IRA starts to disarm, 
something the outlawed group has long refused to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble, who remained with his legislators at their party  
headquarters as other parties assembled at Stormont Parliament 
Building, said the effort to form the administration ``should not 
be crashed. It should be parked, which will lead to a review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defending his actions, Trimble said: ``It is quite unreasonable  
to expect us to bring into government an active and fully armed 
terrorist organization without any commitment by them to act purely 
in accordance with the democratic process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after proceedings began at Stormont, Trimble's Catholic  
deputy atop the unformed administration for the past year, Seamus 
Mallon, condemned the Ulster Unionists' tactics -- and immediately 
resigned as the Cabinet's would-be deputy first minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ulster Unionists ``are dishonoring this agreement. They are  
insulting its principles,'' said Mallon, deputy leader of the 
moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party, which represents most 
of Northern Ireland's substantial Catholic minority. 
</P>
<P>
	Mallon said Trimble also should resign and take the Ulster  
Unionists into a review process without ``the privileged position 
of first minister of this Assembly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern had pushed for weeks  
for the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein to sanction a compromise 
whereby the Protestant side would support Sinn Fein's entry into 
government in exchange for the IRA's rapid commitment to disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRA, however, remained silent on the initiative, and Sinn  
Fein emphasized that the outlawed group had given no commitment to 
meet the accord's expectation of total disarmament by next May. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be desirable if the IRA were to make a statement, but  
they have not done so,'' the Irish government's justice minister, 
John O'Donoghue, said in Dublin. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the British government ordered the Belfast  
legislature -- the only branch of provincial government established 
under terms of last year's accord -- to convene especially to fill 
10 Cabinet posts. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision had been postponed since October in the certain  
knowledge that the body's Protestant members would refuse to elect 
Sinn Fein candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Three posts each are earmarked for Trimble's Ulster Unionists  
and the SDLP. Two others each would go to Sinn Fein and to the 
Democratic Unionists, a hard-line Protestant party that strenuously 
opposes the Good Friday accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the legislature -- pointedly minus the Ulster Unionists  
-- went through an exercise today of electing, then immediately 
abolishing, an entirely Catholic administration from the SDLP and 
Sinn Fein. 
</P>
<P>
	Blair had hoped to devolve considerable powers to the new  
administration on Sunday. The British government took direct 
control of Northern Ireland in 1972 after abolishing its 
Protestant-dominated parliament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 08:26:14 </DATE_TIME>
