way to solve their differences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The legislature last year elected Ulster Unionist leader David  
Trimble to lead an intended four-party, 12-member Cabinet, the core 
institution envisaged in April 1998's peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trimble's badly divided party has refused to support the  
formation of any administration that includes the Irish Republican 
Army-linked Sinn Fein party unless the IRA starts to disarm, 
something the outlawed group has long refused to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble, who remained with his legislators at their party  
headquarters as other parties assembled at Stormont Parliament 
Building, said the effort to form the administration ``should not 
be crashed. It should be parked, which will lead to a review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defending his actions, Trimble said: ``It is quite unreasonable  
to expect us to bring into government an active and fully armed 
terrorist organization without any commitment by them to act purely 
in accordance with the democratic process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after proceedings began at Stormont, Trimble's Catholic  
deputy atop the unformed administration for the past year, Seamus 
Mallon, condemned the Ulster Unionists' tactics -- and immediately 
resigned as the Cabinet's would-be deputy first minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ulster Unionists ``are dishonoring this agreement. They are  
insulting its principles,'' said Mallon, deputy leader of the 
moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party, which represents most 
of Northern Ireland's substantial Catholic minority. 
</P>
<P>
	Mallon said Trimble also should resign and take the Ulster  
Unionists into a review process without ``the privileged position 
of first minister of this Assembly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern had pushed for weeks  
for the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein to sanction a compromise 
whereby the Protestant side would support Sinn Fein's entry into 
government in exchange for the IRA's rapid commitment to disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRA, however, remained silent on the initiative, and Sinn  
Fein emphasized that the outlawed group had given no commitment to 
meet the accord's expectation of total disarmament by next May. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be desirable if the IRA were to make a statement, but  
they have not done so,'' the Irish government's justice minister, 
John O'Donoghue, said in Dublin. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the British government ordered the Belfast  
legislature -- the only branch of provincial government established 
under terms of last year's accord -- to convene especially to fill 
10 Cabinet posts. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision had been postponed since October in the certain  
knowledge that the body's Protestant members would refuse to elect 
Sinn Fein candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Three posts each are earmarked for Trimble's Ulster Unionists  
and the SDLP. Two others each would go to Sinn Fein and to the 
Democratic Unionists, a hard-line Protestant party that strenuously 
opposes the Good Friday accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the legislature -- pointedly minus the Ulster Unionists  
-- went through an exercise today of electing, then immediately 
abolishing, an entirely Catholic administration from the SDLP and 
Sinn Fein. 
</P>
<P>
	Blair had hoped to devolve considerable powers to the new  
administration on Sunday. The British government took direct 
control of Northern Ireland in 1972 after abolishing its 
Protestant-dominated parliament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
