<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Students To Talk Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton was joining with more than  
80 students from Colorado -- including some from Columbine High 
School -- to ``send a message to Congress'' for tougher gun control 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The president invited the students to the White House to help  
his campaign for mandatory background checks on all buyers at gun 
shows, and to require child safety locks on handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton would use  
the occasion to tell the students and Congress that ``the tragedy 
of Littleton should not be forgotten and that Congress needs to 
move forward expeditiously with the kind of sensible gun control 
legislation that the Senate passed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The April 20 shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton left  
15 dead, including the two killers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart denied that Clinton was using the students  
inappropriately for political purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that what the president is doing is politicizing  
it,'' Lockhart said. ``He thinks that these actions should be 
taken, and these students who are coming here today on their way to 
the Hill feel very strongly about it. And they'll make their 
message known. I don't think they see this as a political issue. 
They see this as an issue of safety for themselves and for their 
fellow students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The students' visit was organized by Handgun Control Inc. and  
SAFE (Sane Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic), a political 
action group formed in the aftermath of the Columbine tragedy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
