<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Star Wars' Helps Hasbro Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Hasbro Inc.'s second-quarter earnings  
climbed almost six-fold from a year ago, fueled by robust demand 
for its ``Star Wars'' toys, Furby dolls and computer games. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's second-largest toy maker reported Thursday that it  
earned $32.3 million, or 16 cents a share, for the quarter ended 
June 27, compared with $5.5 million, or 3 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $875 million, compared to $572  
million in the same quarter a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro's results topped Wall Street analysts expectations of 10  
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pawtucket, R.I.-based company's stock rose $1.43 3/4 to $27.62 1/2  
Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, boosted by the big 
quarterly profit gains as well as an upbeat outlook from Hasbro for 
the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had worried in recent months that the much-hyped ``Star  
Wars: Episode I: The Phantom Menace'' toys weren't selling as well 
as many had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	But the second-quarter results showed that strong demand for  
merchandise tied to the movie, and some products sold even better 
than the company had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	The company now expects to realize $650 million in ``Star Wars''  
toy sales this year, up from the company's original projection of 
$500 million to $600 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the strength in its ``Star Wars'' line, Hasbro's  
earnings benefited from continued demand for its interactive Furby 
dolls, computer software, and toys tied to the fantasy Japanese 
cartoon Pokemon and British children's television show Teletubbies. 
</P>
<P>
	If Hasbro's sales and profits keep up this pace, analysts said  
the company may be on track to become the nation's biggest toymaker 
by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beating Mattel is still a very attainable goal for Hasbro,''  
said Cliff Annicelli, associate editor of Play Things magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro spent $147 million in the second quarter to repurchase  
almost five million shares of its common stock. About $90 million 
of that money went to repurchase most of the Dreamworks film 
studio's equity interest in Hasbro. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, Hasbro earned $46.08  
million, or 22 cents a share, compared with $13.25 million, or 6 
cents a share. Sales were $1.54 billion, up from $1.05 billion a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasbro owns the Playskool, Kenner, Tonka, Milton Bradley, Parker  
Brothers and Galoob toy and game brands. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
