<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Nixes Patient Suits vs. HMOs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today killed a Democratic provision  
that would have enabled some patients to sue their health plans. 
Health plans that fall under federal regulations cannot now be 
sued. The Senate voted 53-47 against the provision, which Democrats 
had argued would force insurers to put a patient's health before 
the company bottom line. The sponsor of the doomed amendment, Sen. 
Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said: ``This is what the patients' bill of 
rights is all about.'' Republicans countered by saying patients 
would actually suffer because of the cost of lengthy court fights. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Ireland Peace Prospects Damaged  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's major  
Protestant party refused today to nominate ministers for the new 
provincial administration, a long-delayed decision that threw years 
of peacemaking efforts into disarray. The Ulster Unionists refused 
even to attend today's session of Belfast's year-old legislature. 
Their unexpectedly stubborn stand dealt a severe blow to British 
Prime Minister Tony Blair's hopes of forming an administration of 
Protestants and Catholics after a year of deadlock. In response, 
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam announced that the 
British and Irish governments would meet next week to plan a 
comprehensive ``review'' summit with Northern Ireland's key 
parties, designed to salvage last year's Good Friday peace accord. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Welcomes Barak to White House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton welcomed Israeli Prime  
Minister Ehud Barak today, promising that ``America will walk with 
you'' in the search for peace. Barak pledged to ``inject new 
momentum into the peace process. Speaking before three hours of 
talks, Clinton hailed the Israeli leader as the most decorated 
soldier in Israel's history. Referring to the historic White House 
handshake between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and the late 
Israeli leader Yitzhak Rabin, Clinton said: ``As we have seen 
before at this house ... what first seems unlikely -- even 
impossible -- can actually become reality when the will for peace is 
strong.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Says He'll Forgo Matching Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- After raising a record $37 million for his  
Republican presidential campaign, Texas Gov. George W. Bush 
announced today that he will not accept federal matching funds and 
the spending limitations that go with them. The Republican 
presidential front-runner said that if he accepts the matching 
funds his campaign would have been restricted by spending limits in 
early states like Iowa and New Hampshire. Steve Forbes already has 
indicated that he won't accept matching funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Columbine Teens  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Urging Congress to heed ``the lobbyists who  
truly matter, our children,'' President Clinton today challenged 
lawmakers to pass gun control legislation before the nation's 
students return to classes in September. The president met with 
more than 80 students from Colorado -- including some from Columbine 
High School -- to hear their concerns about the prospects of passage 
of tougher gun control laws. The president invited the students to 
the White House to help his campaign for mandatory background 
checks on buyers at gun shows, and to require child safety locks on 
handguns. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Workers Can Seek Compensation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON AP) -- Thousands of federal contract workers exposed  
to toxic and radioactive substances at nuclear weapons facilities 
will be eligible for federal compensation under a new policy, 
administration officials said today. The new initiative to be 
announced later today by the Energy Department will end years of 
litigation between the government and workers who were exposed over 
three decades at weapons production facilities. ``This is long 
deserved and long overdue,'' said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. 
``Many of the men and women who helped us win the Cold War worked 
in extremely sensitive conditions and were exposed to extremely 
hazardous substances.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 45; Nasdaq Up 15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 45.60 points at 11,193.70. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,602-1,243. The Nasdaq was up 15.76 
at 2,833.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Pampling Takes British Open Lead  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Australian Rodney Pampling is the  
unlikely leader in the clubhouse with an even-par 71 on a day at 
the British Open when defending champion Mark O'Meara shot 83 and 
five-time champion Tom Watson could do only one stroke better. 
Carnoustie more than lived up to its reputation as a brutal test of 
golf, with scores soaring on the first day of play amid the wind 
and knee-deep rough of the seaside links. ``If the average player 
had to play out there, he'd probably quit the game,'' David Duval 
said after shooting 79. ``A lot of pros, too.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
