<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starter Winning Bid Is $46 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- A consortium of five companies  
successfully bid $46 million for the trademark and sports apparel 
inventory of Starter Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, approved by Chief Judge Peter Walsh of the U.S.  
Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del., is expected to be completed 
in 15 days. 
</P>
<P>
	New Haven, Conn.-based Starter, which makes sports apparel  
bearing professional and college team logos, has been under Chapter 
11 bankruptcy protection since April 19. The company listed assets 
of $118.1 million and liabilities of $120.5 million in its 
bankruptcy filing. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's licensing agreements with the major league sports  
must be renegotiated by the new owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The consortium was led by Columbus, Ohio-based Schottenstein  
Stores Corp., whose Value City Department Stores Inc. would receive 
the inventory. The other members of the consortium are LogoAthletic 
of Indianapolis, which is a partner of Puma NA, maker of athletic 
shoes and gear; Sol Werdiger of Outer Stuff Ltd. and Franco Apparel 
Group, both of New York; and Parthenon Capital of Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very excited and we believe the group that was put  
together will take Starter to a higher level ... and make it one of 
the preeminent brands in the country,'' said Jay Schottenstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Starter has a manufacturing plant in Cedar Rapids, Iowa; a  
distribution center in Memphis, Tenn.; and 18 retail outlets 
nationwide. In June, Ozer Group of Massachusetts was named to 
oversee the liquidation of Starter's retail outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	The company sold assets of its Memphis plant to Daisy Tech  
International for $2.5 million. The assets of a facility in Iowa 
went to Valley Products, Inc., of Cedar Rapids, Mich., for 
$125,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Starter Corp. founder David A. Beckerman announced  
his resignation as president and chief executive officer. Beckerman 
founded the company in 1971, and it quickly became one of the 
largest manufacturers of team-licensed sportswear, holding 
contracts with the National Football League, National Basketball 
Association, Major League Baseball, National Hockey League, more 
than 150 colleges and universities, and World Championship 
Wrestling. 
</P>
<P>
	With its signature team jacket, Starter also marketed clothing  
and accessories bearing its own name and logos to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	But the company was forced into bankruptcy because company  
executives couldn't come up with a new game plan to compete with 
big names like Nike and Adidas, which could afford to take chances 
and even lose money in exchange for exposure on the playing field 
and in the locker room, industry analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, the company also was shoved to the sidelines by  
mainstream apparel retailers that wanted a piece of the action, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the company's 1997 annual report, Beckerman admitted Starter  
was being marginalized by the competition. He said the company also 
faced difficulties because of increasing royalty and marketing 
expenses demanded by the leagues. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
