<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rugova Returns to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo Albanian political leader  
Ibrahim Rugova made his long-awaited return from wartime exile 
today, declaring he is still president of the province as crowds of 
supporters chanted his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the warm welcome, Rugova faces what likely will be a  
stern test of his power to unify Kosovo's Albanians and temper 
their desire for vengeance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I am president,'' said the pacifist leader, who twice won  
in unrecognized elections in Kosovo, as he crossed into the Serb 
province from neighboring Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very happy to be back in a free Kosovo,'' said Rugova,  
returning from exile in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the mass return of hundreds of thousands of ethnic  
Albanians to Kosovo just weeks after the end of mass expulsions by 
the Serbs ``a miracle of God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And in a message to Kosovo Serbs fearful of retribution by  
ethnic Albanians, he declared: ``We ... are not in favor of seeing 
any other ethnic group moving out of Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people cheered and threw flowers in nearly every  
town he passed through on the drive north to Pristina, the 
provincial capital. Some chanted ``Rugova! Rugova!'' 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 1,500 people applauded his arrival for a meeting with  
the chief U.N. administrator in Kosovo, Sergio Vieira de Mello. 
Rugova was accompanied by Christopher Hill, Washington's ambassador 
to Macedonia and envoy to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	A pacifist moderate, Rugova could help the United Nations  
establish critical support from Kosovo's majority Albanian 
population for its efforts to rebuild demolished institutions and 
re-establish political life. 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova said he intended ``to work with the international  
community,'' adding: ``I am very happy to be part of the 
reconstruction of economic and democratic life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Rugova's popularity has diminished during his extended  
exile. A rival, Kosovo Liberation Army leader Hashim Thaci, has in 
the meantime staked his claim as the ethnic Albanians' sole leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he needed time to secure support, Rugova resisted  
pressure from Thaci to return after NATO troops arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova's authority also was eroded by wartime photographs  
showing him shaking hands with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic and by statements made during his house arrest in 
Pristina during the Serb offensive that made it appear he was 
taking a more conciliatory position. He said the statements were 
made under duress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe political life in Kosovo will have a new  
direction,'' said Eqrem Kryeziu, an official of Rugova's Democratic 
League of Kosovo, who was with a delegation that greeted him at the 
border. ``I don't believe he has lost support, because we have 
political maturity that overcomes these secondary matters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the presence of 32,000 NATO soldiers, the international  
community has been unable to stop growing attacks by ethnic 
Albanians against Serbs and Gypsies, accused of aiding Yugoslav 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	De Mello has expressed ``increasing alarm'' over the attacks and  
appealed to Kosovo Albanian leaders to discourage acts of 
vengeance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Killings, kidnapping, forced expulsions, house burnings and  
looting are a daily occurrence,'' he said in a statement Wednesday. 
``They cannot be excused by the suffering that has been inflicted 
in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Thaci has called directly on ethnic Albanians to stop the  
attacks, Rugova and his party have been less forceful -- despite 
their long-standing calls for pacifism. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still stand by our position against violence,'' Milazim  
Krasniqi, a Democratic League spokesman, said. ``At the same time, 
we ask that every single Serb who committed atrocities be 
punished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations also is seeking ethnic Albanian support for a  
multiparty council to create consensus for Kosovo's physical and 
political reconstruction. The Serbs have refused to participate, 
and no Albanian leader has yet agreed to join. 
</P>
<P>
	The absence of a single leader of Kosovo's Albanian population  
has hampered U.N. efforts at establishing a functioning 
administration and reopening state-run enterprises, most critically 
radio and television. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Kouchner, who is replacing de Mello as head of the U.N.  
mission, also arrives today. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile in the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade, several  
pro-democracy activists were attacked while they organized signing 
of a petition for the ouster of President Slobodan Milosevic, an 
opposition official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragan Kopcalic, of the Democratic Party, said three people were  
hospitalized and one activist, Slobodan Djodjevic, was seriously 
injured. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
