<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accused Ex-Deputy Found Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- A retired California sheriff's deputy who  
vanished after providing tissue samples that linked him to the 1985 
slaying of a colleague was found dead in an apparent suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles police said a love triangle may have led to the  
slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA tests unavailable 14 years ago were performed on blood and  
hair evidence, implicating Ted Eugene Kirby in the death of Los 
Angeles County sheriff's Sgt. George Arthur. 
</P>
<P>
	A manhunt for Kirby ended Wednesday when a television reporter  
and photographer who were searching the 54-year-old's Spokane 
neighborhood found a decomposed body three blocks from his home. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, Denise, told authorities he left June 30 without  
explanation after having provided the DNA samples. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Los Angeles authorities issued a capital murder  
warrant for Kirby. They said the samples linked him to the June 1, 
1985, shooting death of Arthur. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Pomeroy, Los Angeles deputy police chief, said the FBI  
was confident the body was that of Kirby, who retired in 1996 
before moving to this eastern Washington city. 
</P>
<P>
	A handgun was found with the body, which ``appeared to have some  
sort of head trauma,'' said Spokane County sheriff's Deputy David 
Reagan. ``There is nothing inconsistent, at this time, with this 
being a suicide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	KHQ-TV reporter Gary Darigol said he and a photographer began  
searching the hilly, wooded neighborhood after hearing reports that 
Kirby might have been suicidal. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur was 37 when he was shot in his van moments after leaving  
work at the Men's Central Jail in Los Angeles. Detectives believe 
Kirby, who also worked at the jail, hid inside the van. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur was behind the wheel when he was shot, causing the  
vehicle to crash. Witnesses said they saw a man crawl from the 
wreckage and limp away. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, however, there was no DNA technology to link  
possible suspects to hair and blood samples found in the van. In 
April, investigators reopened the case and took saliva and other 
DNA samples from several people, including Kirby. 
</P>
<P>
	A love triangle may have been the motive, police sources told  
the Los Angeles Times. Detectives said Wednesday that Kirby might 
have killed Arthur out of jealousy, but they did not elaborate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
