<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Gun Control Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After listening to a group of Colorado  
teen-agers, President Clinton urged Congress on Thursday to pass 
gun control legislation before school resumes this fall. ``Don't 
allow the victims at Columbine to have died in vain,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, joined by Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and  
Attorney General Janet Reno, met at the White House with 95 
students who made the trip to Washington to lobby Congress on gun 
control legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the students attended Columbine High School in Littleton,  
Colo., site of the most deadly of all the school shootings. The 
April 20 Columbine shootings left 15 dead, including the two 
killers. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton emerged from the meeting saying the young people were  
``plainly impatient'' with Congress for moving so slowly on gun 
legislation and deserved to return home believing that lawmakers 
would heed their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ask Congress to reaffirm these young people's faith in  
America, in our system of democracy,'' Clinton said. ``There are 
less than two months now before the start of a new school year. 
Let's show all our children that, when it comes to making their 
classrooms and communities safe from gun violence, America did not 
take a summer vacation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But prospects for speedy action were delayed further during the  
day in Congress, a result of parliamentary difficulties and the 
pledge of one senator, Bob Smith, I-N.H., to thwart any efforts at 
compromise. Officials said it could be 10 days or longer before 
formal negotiations can even begin, depending on how far Smith 
wishes to carry his campaign in opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, efforts to advance the issue are in limbo, for  
the second time, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., will be 
unable to keep a pledge to begin formal talks on compromise 
legislation. He first pledged to do so before lawmakers took a 
weeklong break over the Fourth of July. He then passed the word he 
would act this week, but those plans, too, have been put off. 
</P>
<P>
	As the students made their way from the White House to Capitol  
Hill, Hastert announced that he and House Minority Leader Dick 
Gephardt, D-Mo., have formed a ``bipartisan working group on youth 
violence'' that will identify areas of consensus on proposals to 
reduce violence among young people and call them to the attention 
of House leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Capitol, students posed for photos with members of  
Congress and then broke up into small groups to lobby individual 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not want anyone else to lose a friend or a loved one like  
I did,'' said Erin Flynn, a Columbine student. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't let you go into a new school year without this  
Congress taking action,'' said Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt told the students, ``You can be tremendously helpful in  
talking to a broad range of members about your feelings, your 
thoughts, what's important to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The students also spoke with Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., who  
was elected to Congress on a gun-control stance after her husband 
was shot to death by a gunman aboard a Long Island commuter train 
in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	She told the students they can expect formidable opposition from  
the National Rifle Association, but should have faith that most 
Americans are on their side. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember when I first started lobbying, a lot of doors were  
closed in my face,'' McCarthy said. ``Unless Congress hears from 
the American people, we will have a tough time with the NRA 
leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore presented seven of the teens with an  
autographed tally of the May 21 Senate vote on requiring a 
background check for all firearms transactions at gun shows and 
pawn shops. The students were asking House members to support the 
Senate measure, which passed with the help of Gore's tie-breaking 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to have to counterbalance the gun lobby with a  
family lobby that's more powerful,'' Gore told them. 
</P>
<P>
	The students' trip was organized by Handgun Control Inc. and  
SAFE (Sane Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic), a political 
action group formed in the aftermath of the Columbine tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want action, not excuses, and we call on the rest of  
America to join with us,'' said David Winkler, a recent graduate of 
George Washington High School in Denver and a leader in SAFE. He 
said tougher gun control measures are needed now, noting that on a 
typical day, 13 children are slain in gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a Columbine every day,'' Winkler said. ``The problem is  
that the wrong people have easy access to firearms. We do not call 
for the abolition of guns. We call for reasonable gun legislation. 
Our country needs simple laws that are easy to understand and easy 
to enforce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president invited the students to the White House to help  
his campaign for mandatory background checks on all buyers at gun 
shows, and to require child safety locks on handguns. He criticized 
lawmakers for delaying gun legislation, noting that three months 
have passed since the Columbine tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't allow the victims at Columbine to have died in vain,''  
Clinton said. ``We must not lose the urgency of our mission.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
