<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Praises Greenspan's Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore sent a strong signal  
Thursday that he would favor reappointing Alan Greenspan to another 
term as chairman of the Federal Reserve, calling his performance 
``A-plus-plus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Greenspan's future, the Democratic presidential  
hopeful told reporters that it has been his policy and that of 
President Clinton to avoid discussing personnel matters until it 
was time for a decision. Greenspan's current term as chairman does 
not end until June 20, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gore added, ``I'll send you the clearest signal I think is  
appropriate to send. ... I personally believe that no one could 
have possibly done a better job. I think he has done an outstanding 
job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said there had been times ``when I have doubted that. But  
fewer and fewer because I think the overall record is one of really 
an outstanding A-plus-plus performance. And so you can interpret 
that I hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's strong endorsement follows similar comments from the camp  
of the Republican presidential front-runner Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Lindsey, an economic adviser to Bush, has said that  
Clinton should not wait until Greenspan's term is over but announce 
now that he is reappointing Greenspan as a way to remove a major 
threat of market uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greenspan has come to be seen as the economy's indispensable  
man and the prospect that he might depart when his term expires 
next June is creating uncertainty about the future course of 
monetary policy,'' Lindsey wrote in an opinion piece for the Wall 
Street Journal on July 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taken together, this is a potent recipe for economic trouble --  
the most effective remedy for which is for President Clinton to 
reappoint Mr. Greenspan at once for another term,'' wrote Lindsey, 
who served as a Fed board member with Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Clinton said earlier this month that he has yet to  
have a discussion with Greenspan about the Fed job. But there is a 
widespread view in Congress that Clinton is likely to ask Greenspan 
to stay on given that it would be difficult for Clinton, serving 
his last year in office, to win approval in the 
Repubican-controlled Senate for any other nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, 73, a prominent Republican economist, was first  
appointed Fed chairman in 1987 by Ronald Reagan. He is serving his 
third four-year term, having been reappointed by Presidents Bush 
and Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
