<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meeting With Barak Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton launched a new U.S. drive  
for Mideast peacemaking today, looking to Israeli Prime Minister 
Ehud Barak for a formula to reopen negotiations with the 
Palestinians and to affirm he will give up West Bank land to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is holding to the idea that Israel's security depends on  
land-for-peace accords with all the Arabs. And from Barak the 
president hopes to hear that the stalled agreement to yield an 
additional 13.1 percent of the territory will be implemented soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak met this morning with his advisers at Blair House, the  
presidential guest house across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House endorsed Barak's statement that the United  
States should allow Israel and the Arabs to play the lead role in 
peacemaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States government and the president have always  
taken the view that we are best served when we act as a facilitator 
or honest broker,'' press secretary Joe Lockhart said. ``And that 
no peace agreement can be imposed from the outside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was planning on a three-hour meeting with Barak in the  
White House residence. After Barak sees Vice President Al Gore, 
Clinton, Barak and their wives will go to Camp David, Md., by 
helicopter for dinner there and breakfast together the next 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The personal relationship is very important,'' Lockhart said,  
and is an opportunity for Clinton ``to get to know the prime 
minister better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president and his advisers are openly exuberant that Barak  
is apt to tell them what he is prepared to concede to the 
Palestinians and Syria and what will remain for hard bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Palestinians are showing patience. ``It's not a question  
of trusting Mr. Barak. It's a question of allowing him the 
opportunity, and we will allow him the opportunity with all the 
good will we have,'' senior Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath 
said at a conference in Geneva, Switzerland, on the West Bank and 
Gaza. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Shaath added, ``We don't like to see him delay much  
longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Helsinki, meanwhile, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat urged  
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who co-brokered a peace plan 
for Kosovo, to help get the Middle East peace process back on 
track. Finland currently holds the European Union presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We urge ... (Ahtisaari) to play a similar role in the peace  
process in the Middle East region because he enjoys prestige, 
respect and appreciation of all parties,'' Arafat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Momentum is what the administration seeks, according to key  
strategists, and in Barak they believe they have found an Israeli 
leader who, while cautious, will also take risks for peace with the 
Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm eager as a kid with a new toy,'' Clinton said,  
anticipating their White House talks today and Monday and over two 
dinners in between. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that we can begin to energize the peace process in the  
Middle East on terms that are just and fair and will guarantee 
genuine security for Israel and a way of living for the 
Palestinians,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Clinton intends to sound out Barak on prospects for  
reopening stalled negotiations with Syria in which President Hafez 
Assad had been assured by the last Labor-led government he could 
get back the strategic Golan Heights enclave for the right peace 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	While formal talks have been in suspension for three years,  
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu disclosed Wednesday that 
while he was in office Syria secretly agreed to a long-term 
Israeli-staffed early warning station on the heights in the event 
of a negotiated Israeli withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials privately have blamed Netanyahu  
for causing the Arabs to distrust Israel and the peace process -- 
and are crediting his successor, Barak, with a cautious but keen 
commitment in making peace. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet, before flying here, Barak said he preferred the United  
States scale back its role as ``policeman and judge'' and let 
Israel and the Arabs work out their problems directly. 
</P>
<P>
	And State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the United  
States intervened in the talks between Israel and the Palestinians 
in October at the Wye River resort in Maryland only when they were 
near collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, the more the parties can do themselves, the less we  
will need to be involved,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak also said that while he would resume an Israeli troop  
pullback in the West Bank, he would not stick to the tight 
timetable stipulated by the Wye land-for-security agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians disagreed with him on both points, suggesting  
that difficulties lie ahead. Ahmed Abdel-Rahman, secretary-general 
of the Palestinian Cabinet, said Wednesday the Wye accord must be 
implemented before Israel and the Palestinians could open 
negotiations on a final peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	But the administration again took a conciliatory stance toward  
Barak. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said ``there is nothing inconsistent'' between  
implementing the Wye accords while also proceeding with 
negotiations on a final settlement. ``Those two can happen at the 
same time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the State Department spokesman said, ``modest adjustment''  
in the timetable or in various provisions of the Wye accords were 
acceptable to the United States if the parties agreed on them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
