<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Passes Republican HMO Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans, rolling over Democrats in  
a week of party-line votes, approved a modest set of patient 
protections today aimed at millions of Americans who fear 
cost-conscious HMOs may deny them needed care. ``This bill 
addresses the real problems many Americans face,'' said Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. President Clinton called the 
bill unacceptable and aides said he would veto it. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Presidential Pay Raise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted overwhelmingly today to give  
members of Congress a $4,600 pay raise in January and to double the 
next president's salary to $400,000. Lawmakers voted 276-147 to 
increase their own pay, rolling up nearly 2-1 margins among 
Republicans and Democrats alike. They then voted 334-82 to reject 
an effort by conservatives trying to prevent the presidential pay 
boost. The vote on legislators' salaries underlined the favorable 
political climate for the first raise since January 1998 and the 
second since 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Plays Down Bomb Report  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration sought to minimize  
the importance of China's announcement today that it had built a 
neutron bomb, noting that intelligence reports for years have shown 
that Beijing has tested such a weapon. But in light of heightened 
tensions between China and Taiwan and the West, officials took care 
to note that the U.S. nuclear arsenal is vastly superior to 
China's. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Ireland Peace Process Damaged  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The struggle to form a Northern  
Ireland government imploded today in chaos and anger, as the main 
Protestant party boycotted a crucial vote because of the Irish 
Republican Army's refusal to disarm. The British and Irish 
governments, which have spent months trying to coax the Protestants 
of the Ulster Unionist party to accept the Catholics of Sinn Fein 
as government colleagues, conceded that the damage could take 
months to repair. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanian Leader Returns to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Welcomed by flower-throwing  
supporters but facing a province dominated by rivals eager to 
exploit his absence during the war, Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim 
Rugova returned from self-imposed exile today. Rugova is hoping to 
reclaim authority eroded by his decision to go abroad during the 
war and by perceptions he cooperated with Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic over the past months. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Barak Meet in Washington  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak met with  
President Clinton today and promised to carry out accords to give 
the Palestinians control over another chunk of West Bank territory. 
``America will walk with you,'' Clinton told the new prime 
minister, as they stood together in the Rose Garden under a 
broiling summer sun. Clinton is determined to see Israel give up 
land on all fronts in exchange for pledges of peace from the Arabs. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Warner Studio Chiefs Resign  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The two leaders of Warner Bros.' movie,  
television and music division surprised Hollywood today by 
announcing their resignations, ending one of the entertainment 
industry's longest-running success stories and leaving a huge 
management void. Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel, chairmen and 
co-chief executives of Warner Bros. and Warner Music Group, said 
they will remain until Dec. 31, when their current contracts 
expire. They've worked together running Warner Bros. operations 
since 1980. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Open Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks started higher early Friday,  
bolstered by a further rally in high technology issues on Wall 
Street. The Nikkei rose 145.59 points to 18,577.45 in the first 30 
minutes of trading. On Wall Street Thursday, the Dow rose 38.31 
points to 11,186.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Mariners' New Ballpark Opens  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After 22 1/2 seasons in the climate-controlled  
Kingdome, the Mariners moved into Safeco Field, which has a 
retractable roof but no heating or air conditioning. At $517 
million, it is the most expensive baseball stadium ever. Like a 
curtain rising on a new act, the 22-million-pound retractable roof 
opened an hour before Seattle played the San Diego Padres. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians shutout Pirates 2-0  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Bartolo Colon regularly hit 101 mph on the  
radar gun during eight shutout innings, extending his scoreless 
streak against the Pittsburgh Pirates to 17 innings as the 
Cleveland Indians won 2-0 tonight. Roberto Alomar's double in the 
third off Jason Schmidt (8-7) drove in both runs as Cleveland 
improved to 3-1 in Three Rivers Stadium, which almost has become a 
Jacobs Field South for the Indians. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
