<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House OKs $4,600 Pay Raise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the economy, budget surpluses and  
congressional popularity surging, the House today voted 276-147 to 
let lawmakers receive a cost-of-living pay raise exceeding $4,600. 
There was little debate on the issue. Leaders of both parties had 
the House vote on the pay hikes as the chamber began debating a 
bill financing the Treasury Department for the coming fiscal year. 
By law, legislators get automatic annual cost-of-living increases 
unless Congress votes against it. The Treasury measure is the 
traditional vehicle for the pay increases. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Suits vs. HMOs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today killed a Democratic provision  
that would have enabled some patients to sue their health plans. 
The Senate voted 53-47 against the provision, which Democrats had 
argued would force insurers to put a patient's health before the 
company bottom line. Health plans that fall under federal 
regulations cannot now be sued. The sponsor of the doomed 
amendment, Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., had said: ``This is what 
the patients' bill of rights is all about.'' But Republicans said 
patients would suffer because of the cost of lengthy court fights. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Hosts Barak at White House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton promised new Israeli Prime  
Minister Ehud Barak today that ``America will walk with you'' in 
the search for peace. At the White House, Barak pledged to bring 
new momentum to the peace process. Speaking before three hours of 
talks, Clinton hailed the Israeli leader as the most decorated 
soldier in Israel's history. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Shuns U.S. Matching Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has raised  
a record $37 million for his Republican presidential campaign, said 
today he will shun federal matching funds. The GOP front-runner 
said that if he had accepted the matching funds his campaign would 
have been restricted by spending limits, a key worry in early 
primary states like Iowa and New Hampshire. Millionaire rival Steve 
Forbes also won't take matching funds. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Ireland Peace Prospects Damaged  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Leaving years of peacemaking  
efforts in disarray, Northern Ireland's major Protestant party 
refused today to nominate ministers for the new provincial 
administration. The Ulster Unionists declined even to attend 
today's session of Belfast's year-old legislature. But Britain's 
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam announced that the British and 
Irish governments would meet next week to plan a comprehensive 
``review'' summit with key parties. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Columbine Teens  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Urging Congress to heed ``the lobbyists who  
truly matter, our children,'' President Clinton today challenged 
lawmakers to pass gun control legislation before the nation's 
students return to classes in September. The president met with 
more than 80 students from Colorado -- including some from Columbine 
High School -- to hear their concerns about the prospects of passage 
of tougher gun control laws. The president invited the students to 
the White House to help his campaign for mandatory background 
checks on buyers at gun shows, and to require child safety locks on 
handguns. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Workers Can Seek Compensation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON AP) -- Thousands of federal contract workers exposed  
to toxic and radioactive substances at nuclear weapons facilities 
will be eligible for federal compensation under a new policy. The 
new initiative, to be announced later today by the Energy 
Department, will end years of litigation between the government and 
workers who were exposed over three decades at weapons production 
facilities. ``This is long deserved and long overdue,'' Energy 
Secretary Bill Richardson said. ``Many of the men and women who 
helped us win the Cold War worked in extremely sensitive conditions 
and were exposed to extremely hazardous substances.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Rise; Dow Is Up 22.80  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today amid further evidence  
that the economy's strength still hasn't sparked rapid inflation. 
Just before the close, the Dow industrials were at 11,170.90, up 
22.80. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,602-1,286. The Nasdaq was 
at 2,832.32, up 14.19. 

</P>
<P>
	Pampling Leads British Open Golf  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Australian golfer Rodney Pampling  
held the clubhouse lead today with an even-par 71 at the British 
Open. Scores were soaring on the first day of play amid the wind 
and knee-deep rough of the seaside links. David Duval shot a 79, 
defending champion Mark O'Meara had an 83 and five-time champion 
Tom Watson was at 82. 

</P>
