<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Business Targets Family Leave Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Business groups are asking Congress to revamp  
a 1993 law that requires employers to give workers up to 12 weeks 
of unpaid medical leave. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration wants to expand the law to cover more  
employees, but Robert Verdisco, president of the International Mass 
Retail Association, said in a statement that ``clarifying and 
resolving'' problems with the law would make it ``more useful and 
easier to understand and comply with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said he suspects some opposition  
is coming from employers who would prefer not to have to comply the 
Family and Medical Leave Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I seem to be hearing from those who are looking through  
regulatory process as a way of undoing some of the legislation we 
achieved,'' Dodd said during a hearing Wednesday before the Senate 
Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee's panel on children 
and families. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 5 will mark the sixth anniversary of the law, which was  
intended to help employees balance the demands of work and family 
life. It applies to public agencies, public schools, and private 
employers with 50 or more workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The law has been a ``tremendous success,'' said John R. Fraser,  
deputy administrator of the Labor Department's wage and hour 
division. By Sept. 30, the department had received only 13,600 
complaints, ``an extremely small number given the millions of 
workers who have taken time off,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, he said, the Labor Department found no evidence of  
widespread problems or abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Edward Harold, a New Orleans lawyer who represents  
businesses in employment-related matters, said there are problems 
stemming from the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The confusion that leads all these people to my door is not a  
product of the act itself,'' he said, but of the rules developed by 
the Labor Department, Harold said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that many of the regulations were written not to  
implement Congress's intent, but rather to expand the rights of 
employees beyond what Congress intended,'' Harold said. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems include getting enough information from employees on  
health problems that might qualify for the leave, and trying to 
determine what constitutes a ``serious illness,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has proposed revising the law to:  
</P>
<P>
	--Make it apply to any business with 25 or more employees. The  
law now covers only about half of the work force, Dodd said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow eligible employees to take an additional 24 hours of  
unpaid leave each year to participate in their children's school 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow states to create innovative ways of using unemployment  
compensation payments to support people taking parental leave. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
