<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TNT Explores News Photography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A freed prisoner of war receives a joyous  
welcome home. An accused presidential assassin is shot to death. A 
black football player is viciously mauled on the field by his white 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	The camera shutter clicks, and these singular moments are frozen  
in a single frame for our wonder or anguish. Go ahead and find the 
proverbial thousand words -- or thousand feet of film -- that can 
beat a great picture. 
</P>
<P>
	At a time when detractors have tarred photojournalism with the  
paparazzi's sensationalist brush (and when the media has, in some 
cases, tarred itself) a new documentary reminds us of the righteous 
power of the news photograph. 
</P>
<P>
	Six Pulitzer Prize-winning pictures and the stories and  
photographers behind them are the focus of ``Moment of Impact,'' 
showing 8 p.m. EDT Sunday on Turner Network Television. Actor Sam 
Waterston (``Law &AMP; Order'') is the host. 
</P>
<P>
	As a slender national photo album (there are no international  
pictures), the program displays evidence of our best behavior and 
our worst, our depths of cruelty and heights of compassion. All 
that is within the camera's grasp when it is wielded by those with 
skill and judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mixing interviews with the photographers and their subjects,  
film footage and the award-winning pictures, ``Moment of Impact'' 
provides insight into the technical and decision-making process 
leading to each photograph or series of photos. 
</P>
<P>
	The program also manages some tidy historical context and a good  
measure of drama, using effective but not excessive re-creations to 
build to an event's crucial moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Since photography was added to the Pulitzers in 1942, more than  
100 people have received the prize. Some of the half-dozen profiled 
in ``Moment of Impact'' excelled on stories of national importance, 
jostling with the pack for the most telling shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Others were alone in capturing small-town or seemingly mundane  
events that would not have become widely known were it not for the 
photographer's extraordinary eye. 
</P>
<P>
	A family tragedy in Pottstown, Pa., in 1978, was just such a  
case. Thomas J. Kelly III, then working for the Pottstown Mercury 
News, heard a police scanner report of a family held hostage at a 
farmhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	He arrived to find officers surrounding the home. Inside,  
Richard Greist held his pregnant wife and 5-year-old daughter 
captive. Kelly edged in close and had a clear field when the child 
emerged, bloodied from stab wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always thought you could take pictures of anything and then  
not use them if they were too terrible,'' Kelly says in the film. 
``But I couldn't take a picture of her that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then Douglas Weaver, a detective and now Pottstown's police  
chief, swooped in on the girl. Kelly snapped the image of her tiny, 
limp body clutched by Weaver, who wore a smile of sweet relief. Her 
obscured face provided a measure of privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``For days and months and even now I still feel the moments I  
was down there at that scene. ... It will affect me forever,'' 
Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	An exhilarating event, the 1973 homecoming of freed Vietnam POWs  
at Travis Air Force Base in California, was indelibly captured by 
veteran Associated Press photographer Sal Veder. 
</P>
<P>
	As the family of Lt. Col Robert L. Stirm rushed to embrace him --  
with Stirm's miniskirted daughter, her arms stretched as wide as 
her grin, leading the charge -- Veder precisely captured the moment. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to anticipate action. Everything looks routine, then  
suddenly all hell breaks loose,'' Veder says in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Also documented in ``Moment of Impact'':  
</P>
<P>
	-- Stanley J. Forman's shocking photos for the Boston Herald  
American of the failed 1975 rescue by firefighters of a mother and 
child, who tumble to the ground when an apartment's fire escape 
collapses. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Don T. Ultang and John Robinson, of the Des Moines Register &AMP;  
Tribune, and their 1951 record of the racially motivated attack on 
Drake University's black gridiron star, Johnny Bright, by players 
on the all-white Oklahoma A&AMP;M team. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Annie Wells' photos for The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa,  
Calif., of the desperate rescue of a girl facing death in a 
flood-swollen river. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Bob Jackson's stunning 1963 photo for the Dallas Times Herald  
of the shooting of Lee Harvey Oswald in the aftermath of President 
John F. Kennedy's assassination. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's determination to be among the photographers  
contributing to the record of the tragedy is remarkable. He, in 
essence, stalked the participants and history to ensure that he got 
a piece of it. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least one photographer expresses mixed feelings about his  
honor. In the film, Kelly recalls the many images he made capturing 
Pottstown's small-town warmth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are the kind of pictures you wish you were rewarded for.  
It's good to win the top photo prize in the world, but I wish it 
was for something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television:  
</P>
<P>
	HOW THE CELEBRITY HALF LIVES: E! Entertainment Television peeks  
into the homes of the rich and famous in ``Celebrity Homes,'' 9 
p.m. EDT Friday. In this episode, Crystal Bernard (``Wings'') 
provides a tour of her 11,000-square-foot Tuscan villa, former 
``Baywatch'' cast member Alexandra Paul invites us into her Malibu 
beach house and ``Days of Our Lives'' star Louise Sorel offers 
decorating tips. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
