<HEADLINE> Snyder Group Takes Over Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Redskins officially have a new  
owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Snyder and his group of investors closed their purchase  
of the team Wednesday, ending three decades of ownership under the 
Jack Kent Cooke family. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder's $800 million offer to buy the team was approved by NFL  
owners last May. His group of investors includes Mortimer 
Zuckerman, owner of U.S. News &AMP; World Report, Zuckerman's business 
associate Fred Drasner, and members of Snyder's immediate family. 
</P>
<P>
	At 34, Snyder is the youngest majority owner in the NFL.  
</P>
<P>
	``Over the next few days we're going to celebrate, and then  
we'll get down to the work at hand. Our commitment is to bring 
winning football back to Washington,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder continued to keep mum about his plans for the team. His  
only firm position has been that he plans to retain the Redskins 
name despite objections from some Native American groups. 
  	   	
</P>
