<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners Prepared To Let Umps Walk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As umpires began what might be the final eight  
weeks of their baseball careers, management officials said they are 
prepared to let the men in blue resign en masse and replace them 
all. 
</P>
<P>
	And in an escalation of the conflict, officials of the Major  
League Umpires Association planned a conference call Friday with 
minor league umpires that could lead to a walkout by them. 
</P>
<P>
	Union head Richie Phillips said 220 of 228 minor league umpires  
had voted to form a union, with two abstaining, but management 
refused to negotiate with it. Union lawyer Pat Campbell said a 
walkout could ``happen sooner rather than later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They are forced to live two to a room in second-rate motor  
lodges, as opposed to minor league hockey officials who are in 
Marriotts and Hiltons,'' Phillips said. ``They have no pension plan 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations  
in the commissioner's office, said the minor league move was 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not surprised by it,'' Alderson said. ``I heard he might  
make an effort like this in the near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At some major league ballparks, including Yankee Stadium, The  
Ballpark in Arlington and the Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum, 
umpires were booed when they took the field Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to get killed. Sandy Alderson has bashed us, and  
people believe what they read or see,'' National League umpire Ed 
Montague said. ``They're going to believe the umpires are always 
the bad guys. We're on the bottom of the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials said they are not inclined to challenge the  
umpires' decision to quit over the tension that began when Roberto 
Alomar spat at an ump in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad. It's very, very sad,'' commissioner Bud Selig said.  
``I will have plenty to say in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While baseball is leaning toward hiring a new set of umpires,  
Selig will make the final decision, said several officials who 
spoke on the condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``That reaction typifies the smugness, the arrogance that has  
led us to where we are, and it exemplifies the lack of appreciation 
for the umpires,'' Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alderson is expected to take a hard-line approach with umpires,  
who would get up to $400,000 each in severance pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is either a threat to be ignored, or an offer to be  
accepted,'' Alderson said after Phillips made his announcement 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips said he had submitted the resignations of 57 of the 68  
major league umpires, effective Sept. 2, 4 1/2 weeks before the end of 
the regular season. The American and National League offices said 
Thursday they hadn't received them yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that doesn't happen, because that's when the pennant  
races start heating up and you want your best back there working 
the games,'' said catcher Jeff Reed, whose bumping incident with 
umpire Tom Hallion led to the latest escalation in tension. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the remaining umpires will soon add their resignations,  
Phillips said. Three haven't been heard from and two, John Shulock 
and Darryl Cousins, aren't union members because they joined the AL 
staff as strikebreakers during the seven-week walkout in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	If the umps do quit, owners could hire umpires from minor  
leagues, high schools and colleges, as they have during previous 
work stoppages. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son plays college ball and I've seen those umpires  
intimidated by college coaches,'' Montague said. ``What happens 
when they go to Atlanta and New York with 50,000 in the stands? You 
think those guys are going to be intimidated by Bobby Cox or Joe 
Torre?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players agreed the quality of umpires would go down.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big difference, there's no doubt about it,'' Chicago  
Cubs first baseman Mark Grace said. ``They are the best at what 
they do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While hiring new umps, owners could use legal maneuvers to avoid  
or delay handing over $15 million in termination pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``When push comes to shove, the fans know the umpires are the  
real people of baseball,'' Phillips said. ``They are not phonies; 
they go out and work hard. They are blue-collar workers, like the 
fans. The fans understand there's a certain amount of grime and 
grit that's associated with the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the view held by some players. After umpire Greg Kosc  
had to leave in the middle of a game on a hot and humid afternoon 
earlier this month, New York Yankees catcher Jorge Posada said: 
``They're not prepared, they're not in shape. It's a shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosc was hospitalized, and Phillips said the umpire was  
diagnosed with diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they'd like every umpire to weigh 175 pounds,'' AL  
umpire Jim McKean said. ``But that's not going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Posada apologized the day after his remark. Nonetheless,  
Phillips called him ``a jerk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Greg Kosc, who doesn't have an ounce of body fat on him, is in  
better shape than Posada,'' he said. ``But I think the relationship 
between the players and the umpires is good. There are some players 
who are jerks. There are some pitchers who make $11 million who 
think every pitch they throw is a strike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether all umpires would follow through on their  
threat. In March, about 50 umpires voted to give Phillips a new 
five-year contract, but about a dozen voted against him, wanting to 
bring in Ron Shapiro, the agent for Cal Ripken and many other 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro is much less confrontational in negotiations than  
Phillips, but Shapiro told umpires he wouldn't become involved as 
long as the majority of them backed their longtime leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires have been angry since Alomar spat at John Hirschbeck  
three years ago and was suspended for five games, a punishment they 
deemed too lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no support,'' McKean said. ``(The NFL) came out in  
support of their officials, said they were the best in the world. 
... You never hear that about us. The only thing you hear about us 
is negative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions rose even higher earlier this month when NL president  
Len Coleman suspended Hallion for three days for bumping a player, 
the first such action that baseball officials could remember. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
