<HEADLINE> Dimissal Sought in Redskins Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Washington Redskins general manager Charley  
Casserly and former team president John Kent Cooke asked a federal 
judge to dismiss a lawsuit by New York real estate developer Howard 
Milstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Milstein sued the men in May, claiming they worked together to  
have the NFL reject his $800 million bid to purchase the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooke and Casserly filed motions Thursday in U.S. District Court  
claiming Milstein voluntarily decided to drop his application for 
the team, making invalid his claim that someone else caused him 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the bid was withdrawn, there was no way to know whether  
NFL owners would have approved it, they said in the court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is nothing more than a mean-spirited and vindictive lawsuit  
against Charley Casserly for ulterior purposes that have nothing to 
do with the allegations in the complaint,'' Casserly's motion said. 
</P>
<P>
	Milstein's suit claims that Cooke, with Casserly's help, ``used  
league officials and certain owners themselves to unfairly block 
our bid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milstein had reached an agreement with the trustees of the  
estate of the late Jack Kent Cooke, the father of John Kent Cooke, 
in January to buy the team for $800 million. He withdrew the bid 
during an NFL owners' meeting in April after it became apparent he 
did not have the 24 votes among 31 owners needed for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The team was sold instead to Daniel M. Snyder, a 34-year-old  
Maryland-based media entrepreneur. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
