<DOCNO> APW19990715.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA To Investigate Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The country's biggest coal-burning power  
plants are suspected of releasing far more smog-causing pollution 
than allowed by law, prompting an industry-wide investigation by 
the Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials said Thursday that utilities found to exceed  
the emissions levels allowed under the Clean Air Act could be 
forced to install new pollution control equipment and possibly face 
civil penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	A Clinton administration official familiar with the  
investigation said authorities suspect a large number of coal-power 
utilities profited by polluting the air beyond legal health-based 
limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials discussed the investigation only under condition  
of not being further identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry spokesmen acknowledged that utility executives were  
holding discussions with the EPA. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not been advised of any specific allegations,'' said  
Pat Hemlepp, a spokesman for the American Electric Power Co., one 
of the largest operators of coal-burning power plants, largely in 
the Ohio Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA investigation, although industry-wide, is focusing on  
more than 100 coal-burning power plants -- many of them in the 
Midwest and Ohio Valley -- that were allowed to continue operating 
under the 1990 Clean Air Act without having the pollution-control 
devices required of newer plants. 
</P>
<P>
	This ``grandfather'' provision assumed, however, that the plants  
would not be modernized or retrofitted so as to expand electricity 
production, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	In examining six power plants and a variety of state and  
industry records, EPA investigators have found that under the guise 
of routine maintenance, there have been major capital improvements 
in the plants that allow increased electricity generation, 
officials said. This, in turn, has led to increases in releases of 
smog-causing nitrogen oxide in violation of the Clean Air Act, they 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, the investigators found utilities had added  
distribution pipes and new turbines to expand electricity 
generation, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law, utilities must obtain new permits, requiring  
additional pollution controls, if they expand the power plants 
beyond what they were in 1990. But investigators found significant 
increases in electricity generation and pollution and few requests 
for permits. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA investigation found nitrogen oxide smokestack emissions  
had increased by 1,000 tons per year at one of the plants examined, 
although the utility had not sought a permit requiring new 
pollution controls. Normally, an increase of as little as 40 tons 
should trigger a permit requirement, one official said. The release 
of 1,000 tons of nitrogen oxide is equivalent to the amount coming 
from 150,000 cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50 largest coal-burning electric power plants produce nearly  
4.5 million tons of smog-causing nitrogen oxide a year with three 
companies -- American Electric Power Co., Southern Co. and the 
Tennessee Valley Authority -- accounting for about 1.3 million tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Electricity generation accounts for 29 percent of nitrogen oxide  
emissions, the rest coming from transportation to a lesser extent 
industrial sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Two environmental groups released a study this week that showed  
electricity generation from coal-burning plants had increased 16 
percent between 1992 and 1997, resulting in an additional 755,000 
tons of nitrogen oxide emissions annually. The groups used EPA and 
Energy Department figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``These findings back up what we've been saying for the last  
couple of years: The old plants are not living up to modern 
pollution standards,'' said Rebecca Stanfield of U.S.PIRG, one of 
the authors of the study. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Mostly Unchanged / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were little changed Thursday after  
another economic report showed no sign of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the government's benchmark 30-year Treasury bond  
dipped 1/32 percent, or 31 1/4 cents per $1,000 in face value, as its 
yield hovered around Tuesday's 5.91 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported that consumer prices held steady  
in June for the second straight month -- the best showing since 
1986, when prices actually fell three months in a row. The report 
gives further evidence that the U.S. economy is not overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation erodes the value of fixed-rate securities, such as  
Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ongoing fear of inflation held back any significant  
gains in bond prices, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader Treasury market, prices of short-term securities  
rose 1/32 percent and intermediate securities rose 1/32 point to 
1/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were unchanged at 4.70  
percent while the discount held steady at Wednesday's 4.58 percent. 
Six-month yields were unchanged at 4.67 percent, as the discount 
held at 4.50 percent. One-year yields were unchanged at 4.96 
percent as the discount held at 4.72 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.19 percent from 5.00 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 to 119 13/32. The average yield to 
maturity was 5.50 percent, down from 5.51 percent Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
