<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuke Workers Can Seek Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON AP) -- Thousands of federal contract workers exposed  
to toxic and radioactive substances at nuclear weapons facilities 
will be eligible for federal compensation under a new policy, 
administration officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The new health care initiative to be announced later today by  
the Energy Department will conclude years of litigation between the 
government and workers who were exposed during more than three 
decades of the Cold War at weapons production facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is long deserved and long overdue,'' said Energy  
Secretary Bill Richardson. ``It's time to stop spending money 
litigating against these workers and focus our efforts on getting 
them the help they need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is expected to cost about $13 million a year over the  
next 10 years, department officials said. It was unclear how many 
of the contract workers will seek compensation or qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to reverse years of policy and make the workers  
eligible for federal compensation marks the first time the federal 
government has acknowledged that nuclear weapons production caused 
illnesses in thousands of workers during the Cold War years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the men and women who helped us win the Cold War  
worked in extremely sensitive conditions and were exposed to 
extremely hazardous substances,'' Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers for private contractors at many weapons production  
facilities accounted for the vast majority of the employees at the 
plants. Richardson said those workers ``deserve to receive the same 
occupational illness benefits available to regular federal 
employees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Longtime weapons production workers have complained for years of  
illnesses. Their advocates have said the workers suffered from 
cancers and lung disease because of long-term exposure to 
beryllium, mercury, uranium, asbestos and other materials under 
inadequate safety standards set by the Energy Department and its 
predecessor, the Atomic Energy Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	According to officials, the compensation plan will allow workers  
to claim lost wages, and medical and rehabilitation costs for 
illnesses linked to their exposure to beryllium while working at 
nuclear bomb factories and nuclear production facilities. The 
claims would be considered by the Labor Department. 
</P>
<P>
	While the claims initially must be linked to illnesses from  
exposure to beryllium, other illnesses may be added later, 
officials said. An independent panel of scientists was to examine 
possible expansion of coverage to other toxic or radioactive 
exposures. 
</P>
<P>
	Beryllium is a rare chemical element associated with several  
metallic alloys used in atomic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Although private contract employees made up the vast majority of  
the workforce at the nuclear facilities, they have been ineligible 
to apply for federal compensation. They also have been unable to 
collect under state worker compensation programs because the state 
programs were designed for injuries, not occupational illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	To qualify under the new program, a medical panel would have to  
determine that any illness was related to the worker's employment. 
</P>
<P>
	The program applies to workers across the federal weapons  
complex involved in production of plutonium and the manufacture and 
assembly of America's nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the workers were employed at the Oak Ridge weapons  
complex in Tennessee. Others worked at the Nevada Test site, the 
Hanford nuclear reservation in Washington state, the Rocky Flats 
facility near Denver, Colo., the Idaho National Environmental 
Engineering Laboratory, the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New 
Mexico and the Savannah River Site in South Carolina. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
