<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed the morning session higher  
Friday, bolstered by a rally in high-technology issues on Wall 
Street. The dollar edged lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 147.21 points,  
or 0.79 percent, to close the morning session at 18,579.07. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 74.00 points, or 0.40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.91 yen in early trading, down a marginal  
0.01 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but above its late New York 
level of 120.83 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, shares in high-technology and blue chip  
exporters gained following advances in their U.S. counterparts in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 38.31  
points to 11,186.41 at Thursday's close. The technology-rich Nasdaq 
Composite Index climbed 21.24 points to a new all-time high of 
2,839.37. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 17.49 points, or 1.16 percent, to 1,529.22 
points at the end of the morning session. The TOPIX closed down 
14.66 points, or 0.98 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar fell slightly against the yen  
after Japanese Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi Sakaiya said a 
120 yen per dollar exchange rate is appropriate for Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar decline was limited after the Nihon Keizai  
financial newspaper reported Friday that the Bank of Japan bought 
dollars the previous day to stop the U.S. currency from falling 
below the 120 yen mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Zembei Mizoguchi, head of the international bureau at Japan's  
Ministry of Finance, declined to comment Friday on whether Japan's 
central bank had intervened in the foreign exchange markets 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizoguchi said, however, he is ``watching the foreign exchange  
markets carefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haruhiko Kuroda, Japan's vice finance minister for international  
affairs, Thursday also declined to comment on the reported BOJ 
move. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ has on several occasions in recent weeks intervened in  
currency markets to support the dollar against the yen in an effort 
to safeguard the country's fragile recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more costly abroad, and  
therefore less competitive, while reducing exporters' foreign 
revenues in terms of the Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro traded at 123.42 yen, down from  
123.54 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7450 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.6800 percent, driving 
its price down to 100.47 yen from 101.04 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
