<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rights Abuses in Sudan Cited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defending the appointment of a special human  
rights envoy for Sudan, a top State Department official on Thursday 
called that country ``perhaps the world's worst'' rights abuser. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice, briefing reporters,  
noted that slavery and religious persecution are widespread in 
Sudan, and she also cited the ``horrible'' consequences of its long 
running civil war on the civilian population. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said President  
Clinton will appoint a special envoy to deal with the rights 
situation in Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice, who heads the State Department's Africa bureau, said the  
envoy also will call attention to the humanitarian crisis in Sudan 
and seek to muster international support for an effective response. 
</P>
<P>
	The envoy, who has yet to be named, also will reinforce U.S.  
support for a regional effort to bring an end to Sudan's civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice was joined at the news conference by Gayle Smith, an  
African affairs expert at the National Security Council. They 
highlighted recent gains in efforts to end wars in both Congo and 
Sierra Leone. 
</P>
<P>
	They also hailed the decision at this week's Organization of  
African Unity Summit in Algiers to exclude from future summits any 
governments that come to power by undemocratic means. Rice called 
the resolution ``groundbreaking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two officials spoke on the eve of a House of Representatives  
vote on legislation to provide increased access of African textiles 
and other products to U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice noted that eligibility criteria will limit beneficiary  
countries to those which are taking what she called ``important and 
necessary reforms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another administration official predicted the legislation will  
pass by a comfortable margin. A similar proposal failed to win 
congressional approval last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Royce, R-Calif., chairman of the House International  
Relations subcommittee on Africa, told a news conference he also 
expected a favorable vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bipartisan legislation is critical to the U.S.-Africa  
relationship. It has been the centerpiece of what this Congress has 
been doing to reorient U.S. relations with Africa, moving away from 
an aid relationship to one based on trade by promoting markets in 
Africa,'' Royce said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., said, ``A new generation of leadership  
is emerging in sub-Saharan Africa...As Africa changes, so should 
U.S. policy. Our goal must be to help Africa become fully 
integrated into the world economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Donald Payne, D-N.J., called the legislation ``a stepping  
stone for Africa's future. This is a bipartisan piece of 
legislation that will make the economic development of sub-Saharan 
Africa a reality.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
