<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Gains in GOP Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- George W. Bush has increased his lead for  
the Republican presidential nomination in a poll of New Hampshire 
Republicans, according to a poll released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Support for Bush, the governor of Texas and national  
front-runner in the GOP race, increased from 38 percent in June in 
an independent poll by the American Research Group Inc. of 
Manchester, to 47 percent in the firm's latest poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona received 13 percent, compared to 10  
percent in June, while Pat Buchanan had 9 percent, compared to 5 
percent in June. Elizabeth Dole's support dropped to 7 percent from 
15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The sampling of 450 Republican registered voters in the state  
holding the nation's first presidential primary was conducted July 
8-12. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleased,'' McCain told WMUR-TV of Manchester. ``I think  
the kind of campaigning I'm doing in New Hampshire has paid a 
dividend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky said the poll results suggest  
``Elizabeth Dole is falling apart, while Steve Forbes is spending 
all this money and not gaining any ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Polls this far out are meaningless,'' said Juleanna Glover  
Weiss, spokeswoman for Forbes, the wealthy publisher, who was at 2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole spokesman Ari Fleischer said the McCain campaign has put  
more resources into New Hampshire than the Dole campaign has. 
``This is all part of Senator McCain's strategy to spend early, 
peak early and get an early artificial bump in the polls,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, who won the 1996 New Hampshire primary, ``has emerged  
as the conservative alternative to the establishment candidates,'' 
said Bay Buchanan, the candidate's senior adviser and sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Commentator Alan Keyes was at 4 percent; former Vice President  
Dan Quayle at 3 percent; former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander at 2 
percent; conservative activist Gary Bauer at 1 percent; and New 
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, who has announced he is leaving the GOP, 
at 1 percent. Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, a recent entry into the race, 
and Ohio Rep. John Kasich, who dropped out this week, each got less 
than 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 415 registered New Hampshire Democrats questioned, 48  
percent preferred Vice President Gore, 32 percent preferred former 
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley and 20 percent were undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier New Hampshire polls, Bradley had cut into Gore's  
lead. Gore led 61 percent to 9 percent in February, but only 45 
percent to 30 percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The error margin in the New Hampshire poll for both Democrats  
and Republicans was plus or minus 5 percentage points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
