<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nextel Earnings Off; CEO To Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RESTON, Va. (AP) -- Nextel Communications chief executive Daniel  
Akerson is leaving the wireless calling company, which on Thursday 
reported better-than-expected quarterly results. 
</P>
<P>
	Akerson will become co-chairman of Eagle River Investments, a  
private company owned by Nextel investor Craig McCaw. Eagle River 
holds McCaw's interests in Nextel, Nextlink and Teledesic. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Donahue, Nextel's president and chief operating officer,  
became president and chief executive as of Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Akerson will continue to serve as chairman of Nextel until  
January, at which time McCaw will assume that post. Akerson will 
remain on Nextel's board of directors and operations committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves came as Nextel reported that it nearly halved its  
second-quarter loss compared with a year ago as revenues jumped 88 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding one-time factors, Nextel had an operating loss of  
$134.1 million for the three months ended June 30. In the same 
period last year, operating losses totaled of $266.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Nextel posted a net loss of $267.7 million, or $1.04  
per share, down from a loss of $491.4 million, or $1.94 a share, a 
year ago. The latest figures include a gain of $70.3 million from 
the sale of Nextel's stake in Nextband, while the year-ago data 
includes a charge $133.2 million for debt payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-quarter revenues totaled $793.1 million, up from $421.4  
million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Nextel, based in Reston, Va., attributed the strong showing to  
growth in both wireless telephone and paging services. 
</P>
<P>
	The company added 440,000 domestic subscribers in the second  
quarter and increased its average monthly digital revenue per 
subscriber to $74, Nextel reported. In addition, usage per 
subscriber climbed to an average of 425 minutes per month, up 25 
minutes from the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	At last count, Nextel had 3.6 million wireless subscribers in  
the United States, with a network covering 92 of the top 100 
markets in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``That $74 average revenue per user is the best in the  
industry,'' said Bear Stearns analyst David Freedman. ``This 
company still won't make money for a couple more years. The 
important thing is they are breaking through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freedman said Ackerson's departure was not an ouster, and that  
the transition in senior management should go smoothly. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Nextel rose $2 to close at $54.68 3/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
