<DOCNO> APW19990715.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners Prepared To Let Umps Walk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Get ready for the amateur umps. Baseball owners  
are prepared to let the men in blue resign en masse and replace 
them all. 
</P>
<P>
	Management officials said Thursday they are not inclined to  
challenge the umpires' decision to quit over the tension that began 
when Roberto Alomar spat at an ump in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But while baseball is leaning toward hiring a new set of  
umpires, commissioner Bud Selig will make the final decision, said 
the officials, who spoke on the condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``That reaction typifies the smugness, the arrogance that has  
led us to where we are, and it exemplifies the lack of appreciation 
for the umpires,'' union head Richie Phillips said. ``They tried it 
before, it wasn't successful. They tried it in '79, it wasn't 
successful. They tried it in '84, it wasn't successful. I guess 
periodically they have to try that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips said he had submitted the resignations of 57 of the 68  
major league umpires, effective Sept. 2, 4 1/2 weeks before the end of 
the regular season. The American and National League offices said 
Thursday they hadn't received them yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the remaining umpires will soon add their resignations,  
Phillips said. Three haven't been heard from and two, John Shulock 
and Darryl Cousins, aren't union members because they joined the AL 
staff as strikebreakers during the seven-week walkout in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	If the umps do quit, owners could hire umpires from minor  
leagues, high schools and colleges, as they have during previous 
work stoppages. They also could use legal maneuvers to avoid or 
delay handing over $15 million in termination pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``When push comes to shove, the fans know the umpires are the  
real people of baseball,'' Phillips said. ``They are not phonies; 
they go out and work hard. They are blue-collar workers, like the 
fans. The fans understand there's a certain amount of grime and 
grit that's associated with the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the view held by some players. After umpire Greg Kosc  
had to leave in the middle of a game on a hot and humid afternoon 
earlier this month, New York Yankees catcher Jorge Posada said: 
``They're not prepared, they're not in shape. It's a shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosc was hospitalized, and Phillips said the umpire was  
diagnosed with diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Posada apologized the day after his remark. Nonetheless,  
Phillips called him ``a jerk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Greg Kosc, who doesn't have an ounce of body fat on him, is in  
better shape than Posada,'' he said. ``But I think the relationship 
between the players and the umpires is good. There are some players 
who are jerks. There are some pitchers who make $11 million who 
think every pitch they throw is a strike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips maintains umpires are caught in the fight over who will  
supervise them. Selig wants to shift authority after this year from 
the league presidents to Sandy Alderson, his executive vice 
president for baseball operations. Alderson is expected to take a 
harder approach with the umpires, who would get up to $400,000 each 
in severance pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is either a threat to be ignored, or an offer to be  
accepted,'' Alderson said after Phillips made his announcement 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips called Alderson's comment a ``knee-jerk reaction.''  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a great deal of tension within baseball,'' Phillips  
said. ``I think you have various people trying to seize power in 
the game. I think we're going to have to see this power move play 
out before there's any real direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether all umpires would follow through on their  
threat. In March, about 50 umpires voted to give Phillips a new 
five-year contract, but about a dozen voted against him, wanting to 
bring in Ron Shapiro, the agent for Cal Ripken and many other 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro is much less confrontational in negotiations than  
Phillips, but he told umpires he wouldn't become involved as long 
as the majority of them backed their longtime leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires have been angry since Alomar spat at John Hirschbeck's  
face three years ago and was suspended for five games, a punishment 
they deemed too lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions rose even higher earlier this month when NL president  
Len Coleman suspended umpire Tom Hallion for three days for bumping 
a player, the first such action that baseball officials could 
remember. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
