<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Edges Higher Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro edged higher against the dollar  
Thursday, bolstered by statements from the president of the 
European Central Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0219, up  
from $1.0209 late Wednesday. It reclaimed ground for a second day 
after hitting a low of $1.0108 against the U.S. currency during 
trading on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wim Duisenberg, president of the European Central Bank,  
supported the euro in comments following the regular monthly 
meeting of the ECB and hinted at higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank council left its key interest rates unchanged Thursday,  
as widely expected, and no further changes are expected this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But asked whether the bank was moving toward a bias in favor of  
tightening monetary policy -- meaning raising rates -- Duisenberg 
said ``you could see a tightening bias slightly creeping in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rising interest rates would make returns more attractive on  
holding assets denominated in euros. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's clear potential for a stronger'' euro, Duisenberg also  
said, citing an improving European economy and the central bank's 
anti-inflation stance. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 120.83 Japanese yen in late New  
York trading Thursday, up from 120.59 yen, and rose to 1.5739 Swiss 
francs from 1.5727, and 1.4816 Canadian dollars from 1.4810. The 
British pound rose to $1.5654 from $1.5637. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth 1.9139 German 
marks, down from 1.9152, and 6.4185 French francs, down from 
6.4250. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
