<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reed Hopes Umps Stick Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jeff Reed, whose run-in with Tom Hallion prompted  
the umpire's almost unheard of suspension, said Thursday he hopes 
the men in blue don't quit in September when the pennant races heat 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want your best back there working games,'' Reed said.  
``I'm sure that's going to cause some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before he was waived by Colorado on July 2, Reed was involved in  
a confrontation with Hallion, who was suspended three games, a 
penalty that begins July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	That punishment is only the latest in the list of grievances  
among the unhappy umpires, who say they will quit baseball Sept. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed's confrontation last month came after Rockies pitcher Mike  
DeJean, while walking to his dugout after an inning, complained to 
third base umpire Terry Tata about a check-swing call. Hallion, 
working at home plate during the game at San Diego, told DeJean to 
get in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	DeJean said he told Hallion he was going to the dugout. At that  
point, DeJean and manager Jim Leyland were ejected. During the 
ensuing argument, it appeared Hallion made contact with Reed and 
Rockies pitching coach Milt May, a charge Tata denied after the 
game on Hallion's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one of those spur of the moment things,'' said Reed,  
now with the Chicago Cubs. ``I'm sure Tom was upset about some 
things and he might have snapped a little bit. That stuff happens 
in baseball. Ballplayers can do it just as easy as an umpire 
snapping. You try to control your emotions, but this is an 
emotion-filled game. That stuff happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpire Ed Montague, working in Pittsburgh on Thursday night,  
said umpires have to stand up for themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say umpires are arrogant and they talk about the case of  
Tom Hallion,'' Montague said. ``Every single umpire believes Tom 
was wrong. Two years ago I had a case with (Atlanta manager) Bobby 
Cox where I snapped. It's a game of emotion. We're not robots. But 
that's what they want. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't let the players walk all over you. I'm not the game.  
I believe in letting the players play. But if ... happens, I'm 
going to handle it. You're a policeman on the field. We've battled 
for everything we've got. It's always a battle.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
