<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue To Appeal Proposed Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Purdue is appealing an NCAA committee's  
recommendation to sanction its men's basketball program for alleged 
rule violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed sanctions won't take effect until the appeal is  
resolved, which may take several months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We filed formal notification that we intend to appeal,''  
athletic department spokesman Jim Vruggink said Thursday. ``That 
sets in motion a chain of events that will resolve the issue. I 
would imagine that it will be around October before the process is 
complete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA confirmed it had received the notice of appeal. That  
gives Purdue 30 days to file the appeal, after which the NCAA will 
have 30 days to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the NCAA's response, Purdue would have another two  
weeks to file a rebuttal, if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA's Committee on Infractions found last month that  
Purdue's basketball program had committed several violations and 
recommended two years' probation and sanctions including the loss 
of scholarships and a limit on recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the committee recommended forcing Purdue to forfeit 24  
games in the 1996 season in which the athletes appeared and 
returning 90 percent of the money the school received for competing 
in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We, frankly, are surprised, disappointed and puzzled by some  
of the recommendations,'' athletic director Morgan Burke said when 
the recommendations were made last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if the findings are upheld on appeal, we consider some of  
the recommended penalties to be inappropriate and excessive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a two-year investigation, the committee said a bank loan  
was granted to a prospective athlete and financial help was 
provided by an Indianapolis businessman to the mother of an 
athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, the committee said former assistant Frank Kendrick  
arranged the contacts between the athletes and the outside parties. 
Kendrick, who has said he would appeal individually, has since been 
reassigned at his request. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
