<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates Over Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A jury deliberated for a second day  
Thursday without reaching a verdict in an antitrust case filed 
against Microsoft Corp. by a small Danbury software company. 
</P>
<P>
	Deliberations were scheduled to resume Friday morning.  
</P>
<P>
	Bristol Technology Inc. claimed during a six-week civil trial  
that Microsoft cut off its access to Windows source code -- software 
blueprints -- hampering its ability to do business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs --  
such as word processors and spreadsheets -- written to work with 
Windows to be converted to run on computers with different 
operating systems such as Unix. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies had a three-year contract in which Microsoft  
gave Bristol access to source code it needed to create Wind/U. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol sued in August, claiming it was unable to reach an  
agreement with Microsoft for a new contract for the latest versions 
of Windows NT, a top program for running computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends the company tried repeatedly to negotiate a  
new contract with Bristol. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 08:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets rebounded Thursday  
after sharp falls in recent sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose for a second  
straight day as high-tech companies got a boost from a 1.4-percent 
rally overnight in Wall Street's technology-rich Nasdaq Composite 
Index. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei gained 74.0 points, or 0.40 percent, to close at  
18,431.86. On Wednesday, the average had gained 0.97 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar slipped against the  
Japanese yen. In late trading, the dollar bought 120.64 yen, down 
0.48 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo, but above its late New York 
level of 120.59 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares bounced back after plunging to their lowest  
levels in four weeks on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index rose 183.32 points, or 1.4 percent, to  
13,758.89. The Hang Seng had tumbled 2.9 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were expecting meetings this week between creditors  
and executives of debt-ridden Guangdong Enterprises (Holdings) 
Ltd., which defaulted on debts of more than U.S. $4 billion, to 
produce an agreement on its restructuring plans. That would benefit 
local companies, including banks that are owed millions. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the market closed, company officials denied they were  
coming close to any agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, share prices rose after finance officials said the  
government was ready to step in to curb the recent fall, triggered 
by escalating tensions between Taiwan and China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weighted Price Index rose 29.38 points, or 0.37 percent, to  
7,918.04. It had dipped 7.7 percent in the past three sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Vice Finance Minister J.C. Wang said that the  
government will use its stock stabilization funds to buy shares 
when the time seems right to support the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said there were already indications that government was  
buying select banking and blue-chip electronics shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui infuriated Beijing this week by  
saying that the relations between China and Taiwan should be 
handled on a ``state-to-state'' basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Beijing, which insists that they are two political entities  
within the same country, has threatened to use force against Taiwan 
if Lee declares the island's independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stocks rose as local investors bought low-priced  
stocks after two days of declines. The SET index rose 2.70 points, 
or 0.5 percent, to 496.70. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares fell as investors remained on the  
sidelines awaiting results of the general elections scheduled to be 
announced July 21. The JSX Composite Index fell 0.7 percent, or 
4.340 points, to 660.542. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares fell as local blue chips received  
little interest from retail investors, who have dominated trading. 
The Composite Index fell 6.35 points, or 0.8 percent, to 844.86 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rose on the central bank's assurance  
it will not raise interest rates. The PSE index gained 8.37 points, 
or 0.3 percent, closing at 2,579.33. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares rallied following three days of  
declines, after Moody's Investors Service improved the ratings of 
nine local banks, and as interest rate worries subsided. The Kospi 
index jumped 28.47 points, or 3 percent, to 982.14. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Singapore shares fell as a recent rally ran out of  
steam. The Straits Times Index dropped 20.91 points, or 1.0 
percent, to 2,157.72. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian stocks rose on buying in leading financial  
and resources stocks. The All Ordinaries Index gained 10.6 points, 
or 0.3 percent, to 3,065. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand stocks rose, led by forest products  
concern Carter Holt Harvey Ltd., which rose on expectations of 
stronger demand for paper products. The NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 
15.69 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,185.24. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
