<DOCNO> APW19990715.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 10:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Milwaukee Stadium Deaths Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Milwaukee Brewers postponed their game  
tonight in a gesture of respect to three workers who died when a 
huge crane collapsed while lifting part of the roof for the team's 
new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane, nicknamed ``Big Blue,'' was lowering a piece of the  
$400 million stadium's retractable roof in place when it broke in 
half and came crashing down Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like two bombs going off. It was like two explosions,''  
said Gary Craig, who lives near the stadium, called Miller Park. 
``When I went outside I looked around and saw the helicopters 
hovering over the stadium, and I could see that the crane was 
gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the cause of the accident had not been determined, winds  
were gusting to 26 mph. The collapse left a heap of broken, twisted 
metal sitting in the center of the new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was positioned outside of the park. The three people  
killed were in a basket attached to another crane in the stadium 
bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are looking at all possible causes, Milwaukee  
County Sheriff Lev Baldwin said at a news conference today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Was it the wind? Was it something that happened with the  
crane? We're not sure yet,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The primary concern now is the structural integrity of what is  
left of the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire Chief Larry Gardner described the rubble as ``pick-up  
sticks. Which one is going to fall next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the dead were identified as Jerry Starr and Jeff Wischer,  
35. The identity of the third was not immediately released. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium will be finished, but it is too early to speculate  
on a timetable, Brewers Vice President Laurel Prieb said today. The 
43,000-seat, grass-field ballpark had been scheduled to open next 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no idea as to whether there will be a delay or not,''  
Prieb said. 
</P>
<P>
	The roof, the stadium's most unusual feature, is being built by  
Mitsubishi. The huge crane, soaring 567 feet into the air, was used 
to lift seven sections of a roof structure with a total weight of 
12,000 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi offered condolences today and said it is cooperating  
fully in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the injured was a 64-year-old crane operator who was  
ejected from the crane's cabin and fell 20 or 30 feet, said Mark 
McLaughlin, a spokesman for Froedtert Memorial Lutheran Hospital. 
The man was listed in stable condition today with a broken hip and 
broken right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Another person was treated for a dislocated collar bone and  
released from Columbia Hospital, said spokeswoman Kathy Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who suffered minor injuries were treated at the scene.  
</P>
<P>
	Rescue personnel used dogs to search the rubble Wednesday night  
for any other victims, but none were found, Frank said. Everyone 
known to be at the site was accounted for. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers postponed tonight's game with Kansas City at County  
Stadium, which is adjacent to their future home, out of respect for 
the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was built by Neil F. Lampson Inc., based in Kennewick,  
Wash. Company spokesman Bruce Stemp said it's too early for company 
officials to speculate on the cause of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was designed to hold 1,500 tons, said John Mlaker, who  
worked on its design in 1979. ``Big Blue'' is one of four cranes of 
its size in the world and the largest crane in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, several workers were injured when a steel girder  
being lowered into position collided with an aerial basket. And on 
May 10, a worker fell 60 feet from the retractable roof and was 
hospitalized for about a week with multiple injuries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton, Israeli Leader Meet in D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak presented  
himself to President Clinton on Thursday as ``a messenger of 
change'' in the Middle East and promised to carry out accords to 
give the Palestinians control over another chunk of West Bank 
territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``America will walk with you,'' Clinton told the new prime  
minister, as they stood together in the Rose Garden under a 
broiling summer sun, taking questions from American and Israeli 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	They then walked purposefully to the residential part of the  
White House where Barak laid out his priorities for peacemaking 
with the Palestinians while Clinton used the 2 1/2 hour session to 
encourage Israel's most decorated soldier to recapture lost 
momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are approaching the moment of truth,'' Barak told the  
president, according to a senior Israeli official. ``There are 
dangers and there are hopes and we have to find a way to approach 
the risks and enhance the hopes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On specifics, Barak was quoted as telling Clinton that he was  
prepared for ``a painful compromise'' with Syria over the 
Israeli-held Golan Heights, which President Hafez Assady is intent 
to recover after 32 years. 
</P>
<P>
	While Barak did not outline the steps he would take in  
peacemaking with Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians, he told 
Clinton that Israel would not return to the pre-1967 lines -- its 
boundaries before capturing the West Bank, Gaza and the Golan 
Heights in the Middle East war that year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the settlements will remain under Israeli sovereignty  
and Jersualem will remain Israel's capital,'' Barak was quoted as 
telling Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Later they were dining and then spending the night at Camp  
David, Md., the presidential retreat identified with Mideast 
peacemaking ever since an agreement between Israel and Egypt was 
reached there two decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Easing away from public statements supporting Palestinian  
aspirations for a homeland and a right to return many thousands of 
refugees to Israel, the president said in a joint news conference 
earlier , ``We certainly should be doing nothing to prejudge the 
final status issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also reconsidered the ebullient statement he made in a  
Democratic fund-raiser Tuesday in Coral Gables, Fla., that he was 
as eager as ``a kid with a toy'' to receive a new Israeli prime 
minister. 
</P>
<P>
	This was translated in Hebrew to suggest Clinton intended to  
deal with Barak as if he were a plaything -- an allusion Clinton 
rejected Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In American English it means I am very excited about the  
prospect of the rejuvenation of the peace process, and that's all 
it means,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, in their statements and body language, Clinton and Barak  
projected a joint determination to work together toward a peaceful 
resolution of conflict in the Mideast. 
</P>
<P>
	``For more than a half-century,'' Clinton said, referring to the  
birth of Israel with the support of President Truman in 1948, ``the 
United States has stood proudly with Israel and for the security of 
its people and its nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And now, he said, as Barak proceeds with implementing the Wye  
River accords, ``America will help as you move forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Barak pledged to ``inject new momentum into the  
peace process, and to put it back on all tracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While he had urged the United States on his way here to back off  
trying to be the ``judge'' of issues between Israel and the Arabs, 
Barak declared ``we need American leadership and support all the 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On two thorny issues, meanwhile, Barak took a tough stand.  
</P>
<P>
	He said that while he was not going to authorize any new Jewish  
settlements on the West Bank and in Gaza, where the Palestinians 
plan to establish a state, Barak said he was also not going to 
dismantle any existing ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The 200,000 Israeli Jews who live among 2 million Arabs had the  
approval of the Israeli government and ``we are responsible for 
them,'' Barak said. ``I believe in strong blocks of settlement that 
will include most of the settlers in Judea-Samaria and the Gaza 
Strip,'' he said, using the Old Testament Hebrew name for the West 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Barak said he would like to see the embassies of all  
countries relocated to Jerusalem from Tel Aviv. Clinton has blocked 
transfer of the U.S. Embassy, saying that was part of the issue of 
Jerusalem's future that depended on negotiations with the 
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak was meeting with Vice President Al Gore after his talk  
with Clinton. Then, Clinton, Barak and their wives were going by 
helicopter to Camp David. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a rare gesture of friendship for the new Israeli leader,  
and also an opportunity for Clinton to try out his persuasive 
powers in a relaxed setting. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is determined to see Israel give up land on all fronts  
in exchange for pledges of peace from the Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians are showing patience. ``It's not a question of  
trusting Mr. Barak. It's a question of allowing him the 
opportunity, and we will allow him the opportunity with all the 
good will we have,'' senior Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath 
said at a conference in Geneva concerning the West Bank and Gaza. 
</P>
<P>
	In Helsinki, meanwhile, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat urged  
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who co-brokered a peace plan 
for Kosovo, to help get the Middle East peace process back on 
track. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
