<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 09:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Meeting Columbine Students  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton this hour is joining with  
more than 80 students from Colorado -- including some from Columbine 
High School -- to ``send a message to Congress'' for tougher gun 
control laws. The president invited the students to the White House 
to help his campaign for mandatory background checks on all buyers 
at gun shows, and to require child safety locks on handguns. The 
April 20 shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton left 15 
dead. The students' visit was organized by Handgun Control Inc. and 
SAFE (Sane Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic), a political 
action group formed in the aftermath of the Columbine tragedy. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Says He'll Forgo Matching Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George Bush said today that he  
would forgo federal matching funds to maintain ``strategic 
flexibility'' in his campaign for the presidency. ``After looking 
at the numbers, cash on hand of $30 million, I've decided not to 
accept federal matching funds during the course of this campaign,'' 
Bush said while campaigning in Iowa. The Republican presidential 
front-runner said that if he accepted the matching funds his 
campaign would have been restricted by spending limits in early 
states like Iowa and New Hampshire. 

</P>
<P>
	Three ValuJet Suspects Surrender  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Three men charged in the deadly 1996 ValuJet crash  
surrendered to the FBI today, with one suspect reiterating that he 
was under orders to sign forms allowing mislabeled oxygen canisters 
onto the flight. Daniel Gonzalez, former vice president of 
maintenance contractor SabreTech Inc., and mechanics Eugene 
Florence and Mauro Valenzuela arrived at FBI headquarters 
accompanied by their lawyers. A court appearance is planned for 
later in the day. The men are charged with conspiracy and making 
false statements that led to the 1996 crash in the Everglades that 
killed 110 people. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Launches Mideast Peace Drive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today is launching a new  
U.S. drive for Mideast peacemaking, looking to Israeli Prime 
Minister Ehud Barak for a formula to reopen negotiations with the 
Palestinians and to affirm he will give up West Bank land to them. 
Clinton is holding to the idea that Israel's security depends on 
land-for-peace accords with all the Arabs. And from Barak the 
president hopes to hear that the stalled agreement to yield an 
additional 13.1 percent of the territory will be implemented soon. 
The two leaders are to make a joint statement at the White House 
later today. 

</P>
<P>
	Former S. African Leader Implicated  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Former President P.W. Botha  
has been implicated in the 1985 killings of eight anti-apartheid 
activists, the Truth and Reconciliation Commission said today. A 
former police death squad commander nicknamed ``Prime Evil'' and 
other officials said the activists were killed in an operation 
approved by the Cabinet ministers and the former president, the 
commission said. The policemen are applying for amnesty in exchange 
for their testimony. The 83-year-old Botha was convicted last year 
of refusing to appear before the commission, but won an appeal last 
month when the court ruled the subpoena technically invalid. 

</P>
<P>
	81 Nations Enter Math Olympics  
</P>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Five-hundred math wizards from 81  
countries gathered today to test their wits at the 40th 
International Mathematical Olympiad. The high school students will 
work through seven days of advanced tests on algebra, geometry and 
combined mathematics at Bucharest's main polytechnic institute. 
Over the years, China, Russia, Romania, the United States, Iran and 
Hungary have produced the top students. The American Association 
for Mathematical Olympiads says more 80 percent of former American 
competitors are now millionaires. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 10; Nasdaq Up 10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 10.77 points at 11,158.87. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,506-1,093. The Nasdaq was up 10.44 
at 2,828.57. 

</P>
<P>
	Pampling Takes British Open Lead  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Carnoustie Golf Links more than  
lived up to its reputation today as players battled deep rough and 
narrow fairways on their way to some astronomical scores in the 
first round of the British Open. Rounds in the 80s abounded. Among 
the victims were rookie sensation Sergio Garcia who shot an 18-over 
89, and defending champion Mark O'Meara, who finished with 83. 
Through it all emerged a most unlikely clubhouse leader. Rodney 
Pampling, a 30-year-old Australian playing in his first Open, used 
an eagle on the par-5 14th to shoot even par 71. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
