<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 05:40:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Rise Sharply / Jobless Claims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits rose sharply last week to its highest level 
in a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that 310,000 Americans filed new  
claims for jobless benefits for the week ending July 10 -- up by 
11,000 from the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first increase in weekly jobless claims after two  
consecutive declines and left the claims at their highest point 
since June 5 when they were at 326,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for claims, which smooths out  
week-to-week volatility, also was up to 303,250. That was the 
highest level since June 26 when they were at 307,250. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's increase was larger than economists had been  
expecting, but still kept claims at a level indicating that the 
nation's job market remains exceptionally healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago the government reported that unemployment for the  
month of June crept up to 4.3 percent, still near a 29-year low, 
and even with the increase in the jobless rate the nation's 
businesses added a sizeable 268,000 new jobs to their payrolls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that for the week ending July 3,  
12 states and territories reported declines in jobless claims, 
while 39 had increases. The state data lag a week behind the 
national figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest decline in applications for jobless  
benefits was Florida, down 1,172, a decrease officials attributed 
to fewer layoffs in the construction, trade and service industries 
as well as in agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states with large decreases were: Washington, down 927;  
South Carolina, down 597; New Hampshire, down 527; and Maryland, 
down 400. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest increase was Missouri, up 5,457, an  
increase officials blamed on layoffs in the automobile and 
transportation industries. Other states with big increases were: 
New York, up 3,921; California, up 3,448; Michigan, up 3,294; and 
Wisconsin, up 2,299. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
