<DOCNO> APW19990715.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 10:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Milwaukee Stadium Deaths Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Milwaukee Brewers postponed their game  
tonight in a gesture of respect to three workers who died when a 
huge crane collapsed while lifting part of the roof for the team's 
new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane, nicknamed ``Big Blue,'' was lowering a piece of the  
$400 million stadium's retractable roof in place when it broke in 
half and came crashing down Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like two bombs going off. It was like two explosions,''  
said Gary Craig, who lives near the stadium, called Miller Park. 
``When I went outside I looked around and saw the helicopters 
hovering over the stadium, and I could see that the crane was 
gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the cause of the accident had not been determined, winds  
were gusting to 26 mph. The collapse left a heap of broken, twisted 
metal sitting in the center of the new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was positioned outside of the park. The three people  
killed were in a basket attached to another crane in the stadium 
bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are looking at all possible causes, Milwaukee  
County Sheriff Lev Baldwin said at a news conference today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Was it the wind? Was it something that happened with the  
crane? We're not sure yet,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The primary concern now is the structural integrity of what is  
left of the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire Chief Larry Gardner described the rubble as ``pick-up  
sticks. Which one is going to fall next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the dead were identified as Jerry Starr and Jeff Wischer,  
35. The identity of the third was not immediately released. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium will be finished, but it is too early to speculate  
on a timetable, Brewers Vice President Laurel Prieb said today. The 
43,000-seat, grass-field ballpark had been scheduled to open next 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no idea as to whether there will be a delay or not,''  
Prieb said. 
</P>
<P>
	The roof, the stadium's most unusual feature, is being built by  
Mitsubishi. The huge crane, soaring 567 feet into the air, was used 
to lift seven sections of a roof structure with a total weight of 
12,000 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi offered condolences today and said it is cooperating  
fully in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the injured was a 64-year-old crane operator who was  
ejected from the crane's cabin and fell 20 or 30 feet, said Mark 
McLaughlin, a spokesman for Froedtert Memorial Lutheran Hospital. 
The man was listed in stable condition today with a broken hip and 
broken right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Another person was treated for a dislocated collar bone and  
released from Columbia Hospital, said spokeswoman Kathy Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who suffered minor injuries were treated at the scene.  
</P>
<P>
	Rescue personnel used dogs to search the rubble Wednesday night  
for any other victims, but none were found, Frank said. Everyone 
known to be at the site was accounted for. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers postponed tonight's game with Kansas City at County  
Stadium, which is adjacent to their future home, out of respect for 
the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was built by Neil F. Lampson Inc., based in Kennewick,  
Wash. Company spokesman Bruce Stemp said it's too early for company 
officials to speculate on the cause of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane was designed to hold 1,500 tons, said John Mlaker, who  
worked on its design in 1979. ``Big Blue'' is one of four cranes of 
its size in the world and the largest crane in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, several workers were injured when a steel girder  
being lowered into position collided with an aerial basket. And on 
May 10, a worker fell 60 feet from the retractable roof and was 
hospitalized for about a week with multiple injuries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
