<DOCNO> APW19990715.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alou Returns to Dome for Workouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Moises Alou made it welcome home night Thursday  
for the Houston Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	On the day manager Larry Dierker returned to the dugout for the  
first time since having a seizure June 13, Alou also arrived at the 
Astrodome to continue his comeback from knee surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Alou said he expects to play later this season and general  
manager Gerry Hunsicker called Sept. 1 a realistic date for the 
return of the All-Star left fielder. 
</P>
<P>
	Alou wrecked his knee when he fell off a treadmill at home  
during workouts prior to reporting to spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Alou hit .312 and set career highs with 38 home runs  
and 124 RBIs. He had 34 doubles and scored 104 runs as Houston won 
its second straight NL Central title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been through the frustrating part,'' Alou said. ``That's  
why I haven't been here where I would feel sorry for myself. But 
now I need to be here to get my mind ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to be here with the guys and hope the leg tells me I am  
ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros were one percentage point behind Cincinnati in the NL  
Central at the All-Star break. They began the second half Thursday 
night at home against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pleasure to sit in front of my locker with a baseball  
shirt and shoes and see my teammates,'' Alou said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Happy As Sampras Sits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Pete Sampras wasn't kidding, after all.  
</P>
<P>
	The Australians barely suppressed their glee Thursday when U.S.  
captain Tom Gullikson made it official at the Davis Cup draw: 
Sampras, arguably the greatest singles player in history, will play 
only doubles in the quarterfinal duel starting Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras chose team camaraderie over the common sense that his  
presence in singles would make the U.S. team stronger. Gullikson, 
forced to accept that decision, wore the worried look of a man who 
knew he would face a lifetime of second guesses if the gamble 
fails. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a few skeptics expected Gullikson to announce that  
Sampras had changed his mind, or had been persuaded by his 
teammates, to join the singles fray. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Gullikson submitted his lineup at noon -- which cannot  
be changed except for injury -- Sampras was posted in the doubles 
with Alex O'Brien, and Todd Martin and Jim Courier were posted for 
singles. 
</P>
<P>
	After tennis balls bearing the players' names were drawn from  
the magnificent silver Davis Cup, Martin was set to open against 
fast-rising 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt on the hardcourt of the 
Longwood Cricket Club. That match will be followed by Courier vs. 
two-time U.S. Open champion Patrick Rafter. 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's doubles, Sampras and O'Brien will take on Mark  
Woodforde and Sandon Stolle. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Martin is scheduled to play Rafter before Courier  
takes on Hewitt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very sensitive as far as being here this week,'' said  
Sampras, who originally hadn't planned on playing Davis Cup this 
year, but changed his mind after being inspired by the U.S. team's 
victory over Britain in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``After what Jim and Todd did in England, the last thing I  
wanted to do was kind of come along and jump on the bandwagon. That 
is why I have said for the past couple of months that I was just 
going to play doubles. Jim and Todd deserve to play singles. They 
have shown, not only this year but the past couple of years, their 
commitment to Davis Cup. I haven't been in the same boat. ... I 
just never felt comfortable, two months ago, a month ago. I don't 
feel comfortable now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gullikson said the decision was made by ``consensus'' of all the  
players and himself. Martin said he would have stepped aside if 
Gullikson thought that would make the team better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we have come to a decision that I think most of the  
guys are very comfortable with, and we will make the most of it,'' 
Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all feel good about it,'' Gullikson said, not very  
convincingly. ``I feel good about it. The players feel good about 
it. If other people don't feel good about it, that is their 
problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Australians certainly feel good about it.  
</P>
<P>
	Australian captain John Newcombe said if he had been in  
Gullikson's shoes with, say, Rafter making a decision like Sampras, 
he would never have considered benching Rafter in singles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't like to be in Gully's shoes if we win, either,''  
Newcombe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodforde, one of the world's best doubles players, thought  
Sampras would have a difficult time adjusting to doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously he is one of the best singles players around at the  
moment, but that doesn't necessarily mean that he is going to be a 
great doubles player,'' Woodforde said. ``I think, given the 
opportunity to play more matches, sure, he definitely could be with 
that serve. It is a big, big plus. I just can't see how he can just 
walk out there and believe he can play good doubles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodforde's regular doubles partner, Todd Woodbridge, is  
injured, but Stolle has plenty of experience playing doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras didn't seem too worried about not having played doubles  
much. He's won only two doubles titles in his career -- in 1995 with 
Martin on the grass at Queen's Club, and in 1989 with Courier on 
clay in Rome. He's 3-1 in Davis Cup doubles, the loss coming with 
Martin against Woodforde and Woodbridge on hardcourt in Washington 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is still the same sport out there -- keep it in the lines  
and serve big and return well,'' Sampras said. ``I have practiced 
quite a bit with Alex this week, and I think we feel pretty good. I 
can play good doubles. I know I can. So I think we are going to be 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The best-of-five match format will put a lot of pressure on  
Sampras and O'Brien if the opening singles are split. But Newcombe 
thought the opening match -- Martin vs. Hewitt -- would be the key. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the draw came out very well for us,'' Newcombe said.  
``It is a must-win situation for them in that first match, which 
puts a tremendous amount of pressure on Todd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin will have the added pressure knowing that he is on the  
court instead of Sampras, who is fresh from winning his sixth 
Wimbledon title, and that, on paper, he is expected to beat Hewitt. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be some anxious moments for them in that first  
match,'' Newcombe said. ``If we lose the first match, we are not 
going to be as worried as they will be if they lose the first 
match.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 08:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMD President Quits After Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Computer chipmaker Advanced Micro  
Devices Inc. announced a second-quarter loss, stemming from tough 
competition from Intel Corp. and low sales of a benchmark chip. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings report released Wednesday was followed by the  
resignation of company president and chief operating officer S. 
Atiq Raza. But Raza cited personal reasons for his resignation and 
said his departure was not related to the company's financial 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``My decision to leave AMD was a difficult one,'' he said. ``I  
have enjoyed the challenges of helping to restore competition in 
the microprocessor market. 
</P>
<P>
	Raza's unexpected announcement came as AMD reported a loss of  
$162 million, or $1.10 per share, for the three months ended June 
27. The loss was less than the $1.26 predicted by industry analysts 
surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	In the year-ago period, AMD lost $64.6 million, or 45 cents per  
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Including a one-time, after-tax gain of $259 million from the  
sale of its subsidiary Vantis, as well some charges, AMD recorded 
net income of $79.9 million for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterly revenues totaled $595 million, up from $526 million in  
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	In late morning trading, shares of AMD were up 6 1/4 cents to  
$18.06 1/4 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Several weeks ago, AMD warned that it would suffer a significant  
second-quarter loss because production problems with its most 
popular microprocessor, the K6, would hurt sales. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, W.J. Sanders III, chairman and chief executive  
officer of AMD, said the company's short-term future rested with 
its new Athlon processor. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the face of Intel's intensifying aggression in the consumer  
sector of the PC market, where our AMD-K6-2 processor family ... 
has achieved substantial market share in both desktop and portable 
PCs, further gains in unit market share or revenue growth are 
unlikely,'' he said. ``The key to resuming growth and expanding 
margins is the recently introduced AMD Athlon processor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The world's first seventh-generation processor, Athlon is the  
highest-performance processor for PCs available. Initial shipments 
of Athlon processors, including 600-megahertz versions, began in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	AMD ranks second in the microprocessor market in terms of market  
share, behind Silicon Valley rival Intel. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Anti-Milosevic Front Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- When Slobodanka Vojinovic heard that  
Serbia's most powerful opposition leader plans to launch his own 
wave of anti-government rallies, she rolled her eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anything,'' said the 31-year-old office worker,  
her voice weary. ``It's all the same as before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Not Again!'' response by the Serbs to a flood of protest  
rallies announced by various opposition groups is typical. Despite 
an overwhelming popular feeling that President Slobodan Milosevic 
should be ousted, most Serbs believe opposition leaders should go 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like any of them,'' declares Dragan Milovanovic, a  
photographer. ``Things have reached rock bottom, we need new 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Milovanovic, 32, pro-democracy leader Zoran Djindjic is an  
``actor.'' Another leader, Vuk Draskovic, is a little better, but 
still not good enough. Frowning, Milovanovic tries hard to remember 
a politician he likes: ``I've heard something good about 
somebody,'' he mutters, his voice trailing away into silence. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb skepticism about their pro-democracy leaders stems from the  
opposition's past performance. Instead of uniting to exploit 
massive anti-government feelings and protests to remove Milosevic 
from power, they feuded among themselves at crucial times. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past decade of Milosevic's rule, Serbs rose up against  
him four times, enduring police beatings and other hardship. But 
each of the protests collapsed, mainly because the opposition 
leaders were divided or they decided to make a deal with Milosevic. 
Their credibility now is near zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Serbia's defeat by NATO and virtual loss of Kosovo to  
the ethnic Albanian majority, discontent with Milosevic's rule is 
greater than ever. But trust in the opposition remains low. 
</P>
<P>
	``I welcome any anti-Milosevic activity, but I also wish they  
(the opposition) had some kind of strategy, some vision,'' lamented 
Dusan Stojkovic, 29. ``I wish there was more coordination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the main pro-democracy group, the Alliance for Change,  
has held rallies throughout Serbia, campaigning for Milosevic's 
resignation. Thousands have attended the protests, leading to 
expectations that they would grow. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the latest protests, some 5,000 people gathered  
Wednesday in the northern city of Subotica and clashed briefly with 
pro-government supporters before dispersing. The anti-Milosevic 
demonstration was called by the Alliance for Change and a coalition 
of local parties. 
</P>
<P>
	More violence was reported today in Belgrade, where  
pro-democracy activists said they were attacked while organizing a 
petition for Milosevic's ouster. Dragan Kopcalic, of the Democratic 
Party, said three people were hospitalized and one activist, 
Slobodan Djodjevic, was seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Enter Draskovic with a now familiar move. On Tuesday, he  
announced separate protest rallies, with the first one to be held 
in Kragujevac on Saturday, only two days after the Alliance for 
Change plans its own rally in the same town. 
</P>
<P>
	Another opposition group planned protest in the northern town of  
Subotica today. Daily protests are being held in the southern city 
of Leskovac and a series of separate anti-Milosevic demonstrations 
planned into August is making it hard even for protesters to keep 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	``We welcome all actions against the government,'' Slobodan  
Vuksanovic from the Alliance for Change commented on Draskovic's 
decision to hold rallies. ``But we must be very careful not to 
disperse people's energy and patience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic's decision to rejoin the protest movement has left  
some Serbs shaking their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic in the past led the most massive anti-Milosevic  
protests, but joined the Milosevic-led government earlier this year 
only to be kicked out after criticizing the Serb leader's hardline 
policies during the NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	His constant vacillation has cost Draskovic in terms of popular  
support. But the bearded writer-turned-politician is still believed 
to be the one most capable of mounting serious anti-government 
demonstrations. And the fact that he was fired by Milosevic during 
the NATO bombing has helped him regain some of his former 
popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	Sociologist Boza Jaksic says all political figures must go --  
whether governing or in the opposition -- ``so that a democratic 
change could happen in Serbia.'' He says current opposition leaders 
``do not carry democratic potential'' because they are identified 
with past failures. 
</P>
<P>
	The most powerful protests of the past months were spontaneous,  
without input from any established political group. 
</P>
<P>
	In the western town of Valjevo, the citizens said they were  
protesting against both the government and the ``incompetent 
opposition.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
