</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Will Forgo Matching Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With his campaign's bank balance bulging at  
$30 million, George W. Bush said Thursday that he would forgo 
federal matching funds in his race for the Republican presidential 
nomination, freeing him from the spending limits that his poorer 
rivals will have to abide by. 
</P>
<P>
	Multimillionaire publisher Steve Forbes, who is largely  
financing his own campaign, is the only other GOP candidate to 
reject the matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush reported raising a record $37 million during the first six  
months of the year -- more than either Bob Dole or President Clinton 
took in during their entire 1996 campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	It was more than the rest of the Republican field combined and  
also eclipsed the Democratic front-runner, Vice President Al Gore, 
whose campaign raised $17.5 million, plus an additional $2 million 
for legal and accounting expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican front-runner has three times more cash on hand  
than Gore, who reported $9.4 million in the bank. Gore's Democratic 
challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley, reported raising $11.7 
million and had $7.5 million in the bank as of June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Watergate-era campaign finance laws, the federal  
government will match the first $250 of each individual's 
contributions to a candidate. In exchange, candidates agree to 
limit the amount of money they spend on their campaigns -- the cap 
is expected to be about $40 million next year -- and how much they 
spend in each state. 
</P>
<P>
	If he wins the nomination, Bush could still choose to receive  
full federal funding for the general election, which was $61.8 
million for each major party candidate in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush already has raised almost as much as he could spend under  
the limits. By forgoing the federal matching funds, he frees 
himself from any restriction on campaign spending during the 
primaries, although he still can't accept individual contributions 
of more than $1,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got limits that constrain a candidate,'' Bush said. ``I  
want to be in a position to respond. I want to be in a position to 
plan, and I want to be in a position to plan according to need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He can spend millions, for example, in Iowa and New Hampshire,  
where other candidates will be limited to an estimated $1.1 million 
and $660,000 respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``In what will be in all probability just a three or four-week  
race, he will have the funds needed to run a full-fledged 
campaign,'' said Anthony Corrado, a professor of government at 
Colby College in Waterville, Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain, also seeking the GOP presidential  
nomination, quickly criticized Bush's decision, saying he may be 
``unintentionally adding to the already widespread cynicism of the 
American people regarding the influence of special interest money 
in politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Corrado noted, however, that the other candidates would benefit  
somewhat. The federal election fund faces a shortfall this election 
cycle because fewer Americans are contributing through their income 
tax returns. Candidates had faced the prospect of delayed payments, 
but taking Bush out of the pool means the other candidates will get 
their money sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other 2000 presidential candidates, Forbes also is  
turning down federal funds, as he did in 1996, but he is financing 
much of his GOP campaign himself. Through June 30, Forbes had 
raised $2.9 million and contributed $6.6 million of his own money. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes outspent Bush during the first half of 1999, $8.3 million  
to $7.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush relied on a broad network of contributors. His campaign  
reported that more than 74,000 people have given an average of $467 
so far this year. Nearly 27,000 have given the maximum of $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's home state, Texas, was his most fertile fund-raising  
ground, an Associated Press computer analysis of his quarterly 
spending report found. Bush took in 10,269 contributions totaling 
$7 million from the Lone Star State from April through June. 
</P>
<P>
	California was second, with 4,132 contributions totaling $3.6  
million. In Florida, where brother Jeb is the governor, 2,949 
contributors kicked in $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush took in almost $700,000 from political action committees  
and more than $110,000 from members of Washington lobbying firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the federal spending limits, Bush will be able to keep  
raising and spending money up until the national political 
conventions next summer. In 1996, Dole ran up against the spending 
limits in the spring and couldn't respond to Clinton and the 
Democrats, who spent millions of dollars on TV ads attacking him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm mindful of what happened in 1996,'' Bush said. ``I'm not  
going to let it happen to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, campaign finance experts said Bush's decision will lead  
to a further erosion of the Watergate-era reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It means we've entered a new era of presidential  
politicking,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the 
Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington research group. ``This 
is going to be financed by private donors, not the public at large. 
We're getting closer to a market-driven presidential economy, where 
the market rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Simon, acting president of Common Cause, said Bush's  
position could hurt him next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is opting to choose unlimited fund raising at the expense  
of the law designed to safeguard the integrity of our presidential 
elections,'' said Simon, whose group supports overhauling the 
campaign finance laws. ``His decision means that the 2000 election 
may be the most expensive ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Republican political consultant Eddie Mahe said campaign  
finance reform won't be much of an issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have spent the money wisely, you have overwhelmed the  
fact of how you got the money,'' Mahe said. ``'I'm not taking any 
taxpayers' money to buy balloons.' Tell me how you're going to lose 
on that line.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Ponders Fender Question </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMPTON, Ga. (AP) -- It's a change that would strike at the very  
name of open-wheel racing. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Indy Racing League returns to another high-banked track,  
Atlanta Motor Speedway, there's serious debate about adding fenders 
to the cars for the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruton Smith, who owns four tracks where the IRL stages five of  
its 11 races, is pushing the idea mainly as a way of improving 
safety -- a primary concern since flying debris killed three fans 
and injured eight during the May 1 race at Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith owns the North Carolina track and the similarly designed  
1.54-mile oval south of Atlanta, where the Kobalt Mechanics Tools 
500 will be held Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, the drivers are cool to making such a drastic  
change. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe some people would like to see that kind racing on  
ovals,'' said Kenny Brack, winner of the Indianapolis 500 and 
defending IRL champion, ``but if they do, they should go to a 
sports car race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the prototype developed by Smith's organization -- with  
fenders covering all four wheels -- looks similar to a Le Mans-type 
endurance car. 
</P>
<P>
	``Open-wheel racing has its own mystique, its own special  
history in American motorsports,'' said Billy Boat, Brack's 
teammate with A.J. Foyt Motorsports. ``I don't think you need to 
drastically change the formula.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly, though, open-wheel racing is struggling in America. The  
IRL and its more established rival, Championship Auto Racing Teams 
(CART), have been at odds since 1996, while NASCAR Winston Cup 
racing has blossomed in popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	While more than 150,000 fans routinely pack the grandstands for  
Winston Cup's season-ending race in Atlanta, there probably won't 
be much more than 30,000 for the IRL event. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR racing is the main source of income for Smith's tracks in  
Atlanta, North Carolina, Texas and Las Vegas, so he's reluctant to 
continue playing host to IRL events if there are concerns for fan 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, the IRL's executive director, said he plans to meet  
with Smith this weekend to discuss the fender proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Bruton is a great promoter and he's always trying to  
think of ways to make the sport better,'' Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mehl and others have concerns about whether fenders would  
actually make the sport safer. While they might help contain the 
tires and suspension systems that break off in crashes, they 
wouldn't be as secure as the wall of metal that surrounds the tires 
on a Winston Cup car. 
</P>
<P>
	``You think putting a piece of fiberglass around the tire is  
going to stop all debris?'' Brack asked. ``I don't think so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IRL already has taken steps to improve safety on high-banked  
tracks like Atlanta and Charlotte, which were originally designed 
for the slower Winston Cup cars. 
</P>
<P>
	A wheel-tether system -- designed to keep tires from flying loose  
from the car -- was implemented after the tragedy in North Carolina. 
Also, new engine regulations have drastically reduced speeds at the 
IRL's fastest tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Boat won the pole for the league's inaugural Atlanta  
race at more than 224 mph. During Thursday's opening practice 
session, the fastest laps were around 216 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	A car with fenders would undoubtedly increase speeds, since the  
exposed tires of an open-wheel car account for 40 percent of the 
aerodynamic drag, according to Mehl. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, sports cars have shown a tendency to lift off the  
track. During the 24 Hours of Le Mans last month, a car flew 60 
feet into the air and flipped five times. Fortunately, the wreck 
occurred on a road course, far away from any fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Such an accident could be disastrous at a facility like Atlanta,  
where massive grandstands are located right next to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they're going after safety, that's the wrong approach,''  
Boat said. ``A lot of aerodynamic issues become more of a factor 
when you put a body on something that's going 220 mph.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's proposal is not entirely based on safety concerns.  
Fenders also would allow more distinctive color schemes and provide 
additional room for advertising, no small consideration in a sport 
driven by corporate cash. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest problem we have is identifying the drivers and the  
cars for the fans,'' said Sam Schmidt, who drives for Treadway 
Racing. ``If there's more space on the car, there's more room for a 
Rainbow Warrior paint scheme (the colors of NASCAR star Jeff 
Gordon) and on and on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But safety will be the deciding factor in the debate over  
fenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want to be real cautious,'' Mehl said. ``You're  
talking about a long history of open-wheel racing.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
