<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golf Barely Surviving British Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Golf was invented 550 years ago just  
a few miles down the grim, gray coast. After Thursday, the surprise 
is that it didn't die here as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the average player had to play out there,'' David Duval  
said after walking off with a 79, ``he'd probably quit the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of pros, too.''  
</P>
<P>
	Carnoustie is simply the hardest place in the world to play  
championship golf. At 7,361 yards, it's the longest course ever 
used for the British Open. Seven of the par-4s are 459 yards or 
longer, none with landing areas wide enough to park a half-dozen 
cars side by side. 
</P>
<P>
	The rough is tall enough in places to tickle your nose. No more  
than two consecutive holes play in the same direction, giving the 
raking winds several shots at any golfer who crosses them. Water, 
in the form of a meandering stream known as Barry Burn, comes into 
play on 11 holes; seven feature out-of-bounds on the left. Even the 
driving range has a water hazard. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Danny Kaye played here and below his name in the visitors'  
book scribbled one word: murder. Scotsman Sam Torrance, who's 
played golf on this side of the Atlantic for four decades and 
hadn't missed any of the previous 27 Opens, pulled out of this one 
20 minutes before his scheduled tee time. According to a statement 
from the Royal &AMP; Ancient Championship Committee, he told officials 
``he felt he was not happy enough with his game to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In hindsight, most of the 156 players who went ahead with their  
opening rounds probably wished they'd said the same thing. Not to 
worry; most of them will get what they want soon enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could actually be a place where people wished they'd miss  
the cut,'' said reigning U.S. Open champion Payne Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Most won't have to wish. The only round of even-par or better  
was recorded by a little-known Australian pro named Rodney 
Pampling. His wife, a sports psychologist, helped him map out a 
plan to attack the course. Her work can only get tougher from here 
on out. 
</P>
<P>
	Pampling, a former greenskeeper, went out in the second group at  
7:25 a.m., enjoyed relatively mild breezes for four holes and found 
his way back to the clubhouse several hours later with a 71. 
Instead of heading back to the driving range, Pampling went 
straight to a barber shop, somehow convinced less wind resistance 
would serve him better than more practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Pampling didn't say where he got his hair cut, but he must have  
traveled some distance. Judging by the height of the rough at 
Carnoustie, there haven't been any sharp objects in the vicinity 
for several weeks, which turned out to be a good thing. Just 
getting around the links proved dangerous enough for most of the 
golfers. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who shot 79, said the toughest thing about playing  
``was trying not to injure yourself.'' He was not kidding. Tiger 
Woods, who spent parts of his day hacking free of rough en route to 
a 74, said: ``You could get hurt out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the golfers suffered nothing worse than injured pride.  
The average score was 78.3. Fifty-seven golfers failed to break 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Scotsman Sandy Lyle, who won the 1985 Open but has been in a  
career slump since his 1988 Masters victory, believed his game was 
coming around until he set foot on Carnoustie. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has probably set me back six months,'' he said. ``All this  
hard work I've been doing getting my swing organized -- it's just 
torn apart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was little consolation to be had after shooting 85, but  
Lyle found some in the misery of playing partner Fred Funk. 
</P>
<P>
	``When someone like Fred Funk, who's known for accurate play and  
hitting fairways all the time, shoots 83, you know it's 
impossible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Lyle didn't know at the time was that after their round,  
Funk withdrew. He injured his shoulder hitting out of the rough he 
so rarely encounters. 
</P>
<P>
	The moaning and groaning was severe enough, finally, to put  
Michael Bonallack, secretary of the R &AMP; A, on the defensive. 
</P>
<P>
	When the players straggled in after practice rounds and  
complained the fairways were too narrow, the rough was too high, 
and the course too hard, Bonallack sweetly shot back, ``Too hard 
for what?'' 
</P>
<P>
	But by the end of the day, he was in full retreat.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to punish the golfers or make them look  
silly,'' he said. ``Far from it. We feel very sorry for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not sorry enough to change a thing.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
