<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cruise Publicist Keeps Eye on Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tom Cruise's publicist is hoping to keep  
close tabs on broadcasts involving the star's racy new movie, 
``Eyes Wide Shut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PMK, the publicity firm that represents Cruise, distributed a  
waiver to media at a preview for ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' asking to see 
rough cuts in advance of any TV reports featuring interviews with 
the actor. 
</P>
<P>
	The waivers gave Cruise representatives the option to veto  
segments prior to broadcast and specified that unused video ``will 
be destroyed'' and news outlets must, if asked, ``supply evidence 
of such destruction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood'' were among  
those handed the waiver. ``Entertainment Tonight'' didn't sign the 
waiver, spokeswoman Kristy Barrett said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	PMK's Pat Kingsley has said the request to see advance footage  
was a mistake and that the requirement was rescinded. 
</P>
<P>
	But everyone interviewing Cruise had to sign a revised waiver  
with the pledge that ``the interview and the program will not show 
the artist in a negative or derogatory manner.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gore: No More Racial Profiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told the NAACP Thursday  
that ending the practice of racial profiling by police departments 
would be a top priority in his presidential administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to end the shameful practice of racial profiling,''  
Gore told 3,000 NAACP members Thursday on the closing day of the 
organization's annual national convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, the front-runner who is facing former New Jersey Sen. Bill  
Bradley for the Democratic presidential nomination, struck several 
themes popular with members of the largest and oldest civil rights 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	They included support for tighter gun laws, a federal hate  
crimes law, the launch of an investment fund to boost trade with 
African nations and quality preschool for all children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we have to rise to the challenge and do right by our  
children,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Black advocates say racial profiling, the police practice of  
singling out minorities for questioning, is often at the crux of 
fatal shootings, such as the killings of young blacks by police 
under questionable circumstances in New York, Pittsburgh and 
Riverside, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm elected president, ending racial profiling will be the  
first civil rights act of the new century,'' Gore said to a 
standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore repeated his call for strong national gun safety  
provisions, saying handgun purchasers should be required to have 
photo licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to create a family lobby that will be more  
powerful than the gun lobby,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The photo license provision is part of an anti-crime agenda Gore  
has outlined this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore took up the anthem again while addressing the College  
Democrats of America at their national convention in Washington. He 
accused the GOP of doing ``the bidding of the NRA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also promised the students that he would carry on the legacy  
of the civil rights movement, by focusing on eliminating 
discrimination and helping those who have been left out of the 
nation's prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	``All over the country there are people who are misperceived,''  
Gore said. ``Those individuals who are misperceived hold the keys 
to our future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the most important missions of the country in the future,  
Gore added, will be to prove that people of all different 
backgrounds can benefit from working together. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's address to the 500 students was interrupted a few times  
by several animal rights activists in the audience. They began 
chanting ``burn bunnies, lose votes'' during the first part of 
Gore's speech. The vice president tried to diffuse the incident by 
saying, ``Let's hear it for the First Amendment. Let's hear it for 
free speech.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the students started chanting again, the vice president  
spoke directly to them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be glad to speak with you later if you want to actually  
exchange ideas,'' he said. Hotel security eventually led the 
activists out of the hall. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech Monday to Boston city police officers, Gore  
announced a plan for ``gang-free zones'' with curfews on individual 
gang members and a ban on ``gang-related clothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore focused on reducing rural crime on campaign stops in Iowa  
on Tuesday and Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The $350 million New Africa Infrastructure Fund, which will be  
the largest equity investment fund ever developed by the Overseas 
Private Investment Corporation, is expected to attract an 
additional $2 billion in financing capital to countries in 
sub-Saharan Africa at no cost to U.S. taxpayers, Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund is expected to create nearly 7,000 new jobs and $50  
million in annual revenues for the countries involved while 
generating new markets for U.S. products. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 00:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Star Likes Her Golf Noisy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Something was missing.  
</P>
<P>
	Brandi Chastain, one of the heroes in the American soccer team's  
World Cup victory, was trying her hand at golf. The ball was on the 
tee, the driver was in her hands and she was about to swing. Then 
it came to her. 
</P>
<P>
	``In soccer we have noise,'' she shouted to the fans around her,  
who had hushed as golf galleries do when a shot is about to be 
made. ``So don't be afraid. I'm serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans let loose with ``USA!'' and ``Go for the goal.''  
Satisfied, Chastain clubbed the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Golf was a little different Wednesday at the Wykagyl Country  
Club. Soccer jerseys and ponytails were the order of the day as 
preteen girls swarmed to see soccer stars Chastain, Mia Hamm and 
Julie Foudy. They played an exuberant 18 holes, bantering with fans 
and insulting each other across the fairways. 
</P>
<P>
	When Chastain got more sod than ball on one shot, Foudy shouted,  
``I hate when that happens.'' And when Chastain was asked to reveal 
her handicap, she said, ``Julie's my handicap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soccer stars played with pros Meg Mallon and Karrie Webb in  
the best-ball pro-am tournament of the Japan Airlines Big Apple 
Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Well before they teed off, the soccer players attracted uncommon  
early morning attention as they warmed up on the club's driving 
range. Among the scores of youngsters was Allison Kowalski, 6, of 
Wayne, N.J., who sneaked inside the spectator ropes and got her 
jersey -- already labeled with Hamm's name and number -- autographed 
by all three stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Staci Whinfield and Allison Farina, both 11 and from Cheshire,  
Conn., staked out a spot alongside the cart path between the 
driving range and the first tee, hoping for a chat with Hamm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't figured out what to say yet,'' Staci said.  
``Probably just `Hi' and `You're my hero.''' 
</P>
<P>
	As Hamm and Foudy teed off before a crowd of 200, the starter  
announced that he'd never seen that many people at 8:30. 
</P>
<P>
	The foursome that included Hamm and Foudy was just ahead of the  
one that included Chastain, and they managed to rib each other 
whenever they were close enough. Just as Chastain was about to hit 
a tee shot, Foudy shouted from the fairway of the next hole, ``Head 
down! Watch your knees!'' And Hamm added, ``Breathe through your 
eyelids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once, as Chastain was sizing up a putt, a fan shouted, ``Kick  
it!.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be better if I did,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hamm poked fun at Chastain's outfit, shouting, ``You look good,  
except for that one long sock.'' Chastain, who at the moment of 
victory on Saturday tore off her jersey and revealed her sports 
bra, kept her sleeveless shirt on, but did doff a gray sweater she 
wore during warmups. 
</P>
<P>
	The soccer champs were asked by officials not to delay the  
tourney by signing autographs, but Chastain broke the rule a couple 
of times. When the women finished their 18 holes, they signed 
autographs for 40 minutes on balls, magazine covers, jerseys and 
even faces. 
</P>
<P>
	As they ran out of time, adults were asked to leave the line,  
then older children, leaving just the smiling, adoring youngest 
fans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
