<HEADLINE> Gossip Columnist, Critic in Tiff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Gossip columnist Liz Smith as The New York Times  
chief theater critic? 
</P>
<P>
	Not exactly meant as a compliment, Smith said Wednesday, even  
though the suggestion came from Ben Brantley, the man who already 
holds the job. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in the August issue of W, Brantley playfully  
makes the proposal after saying that part of Broadway's problem is 
certain theatergoers are unreceptive to challenging plays and 
musicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was dishing tourist crowds and inattentive, unappreciated  
audiences -- the man in the street whom Brantley obviously considers 
not clever enough to appreciate what he appreciates,'' Smith wrote 
in her column. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, the 'man on the street' is whom I write for, and I think  
they're a pretty smart lot, overall,'' Smith added. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley and Smith have disagreed in the past, most forcefully  
over the Tony-winning production of ``Annie Get Your Gun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his review last March of ``Annie,'' Brantley called the  
revival of the Irving Berlin musical ``acrid smog'' and said its 
star, Bernadette Peters, was ``misdirected and miscast in a role 
forever associated with its orginator, Ethel Merman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith responded with a spirited defense of Peters and the show,  
adding ``Sometimes, one would like to take ... Brantley, string him 
up in Shubert Alley and just let the fellow hang there, watching 
the rest of us enjoy and love the theater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet their dust-ups have all been good-natured, according to a  
spokesman for Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brantley is a really smart guy. He loves the theater. We agree  
to disagree,'' Smith wrote Wednesday. ``That's America to me!'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
