<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Couple Accused of Holding Girl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A city social worker and her husband have been  
accused of luring a young Nigerian girl to this country with the 
promise of a better life and then forcing her into servitude for 
nearly a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosper Emeka Udogwu, 48, a proofreader, and Ifeoma Ezeonu  
Udogwu, 39, the social worker, were arrested Wednesday accused of 
conspiracy, harboring an alien, involuntary servitude and witness 
tampering. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Udogwu was suspended from her city job as a child  
evaluation specialist who chooses appropriate homes for foster 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say the couple brought the then-13-year-old girl,  
who was a baby sitter for Mrs. Udogwu's sister in Nigeria, to the 
United States in 1989 and promised she would go to trade school, 
learn how to sew and ``enjoy a better life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, she was beaten, forced to do the family's chores and  
threatened by the couple, authorities say. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Tritz, a lawyer for Udogwu, said prosecutors unfairly give  
the impression that the girl was ``chained in the basement and 
beaten at every turn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he said, she was treated well, even enjoying trips to  
Disney World and a trip home during which she gave her family 
$4,000 in gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman, now 22, was identified court papers only as ``Girl  
A.'' Prosecutors say she arrived in the United States in August 
1989 and was told she was responsible for cooking, cleaning, yard 
work, laundry and the caring for and feeding of the Udogwu 
children. The family now has four children, ages 6, 7, 12 and 13. 
</P>
<P>
	They also said she was told she would be stripped naked and  
returned to Nigeria if she did not obey the couple, who are 
naturalized U.S. citizens but are from Nigeria. The couple 
allegedly warned her that they could cause her brother to lose his 
job and her family to suffer financially. 
</P>
<P>
	During the next nine years, the girl was forbidden from speaking  
to anyone outside the home, from using the telephone and from 
collecting the mail received at the Udogwu residence, prosecutors 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she was permitted to attend public high school.  
</P>
<P>
	The couple periodically beat the girl with their hands, belts,  
slippers and a Nigerian-style broom made with sticks whenever she 
did something wrong, the complaint said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tritz said Udogwu brought the girl to this country after he was  
told by her mother that he was the child's father. He said she 
sought help from the authorities only after he discovered she was 
not his daughter and reported that fact to immigration authorities, 
jeopardizing her ability to stay here. 
</P>
<P>
	``This places a cloud over the allegations made by this woman,''  
Tritz said. ``At the appropriate time, her credibility will be 
questioned in a very large way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
