<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Storms Cause Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Storms sweeping through Arizona drenched the  
Grand Canyon, producing flash floods and mudslides that injured 
four people, undermined a water supply line and closed a major 
trail. 
</P>
<P>
	A helicopter plucked a Phoenix man stranded in his car, and an  
officer in Tucson narrowly managed to grab an 8-year-old child 
being swept away. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms on Wednesday dumped 1.24 inches of rain on Phoenix,  
eclipsing the record of .47 inches for the date set in 1942. Tucson 
got 1.48 inches, the most recorded there since Oct. 26, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the summer monsoons, we've had only 61 days with an  
inch or more in the past 103 years. This is a real rarity,'' said 
National Weather Service meterologist Craig Ellis. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 3 inches drenched the Grand Canyon, leading officials  
to close the main trail from the South Rim to the canyon's floor. 
</P>
<P>
	The trans-canyon pipeline that brings water up to the southern  
rim's visitor center remained intact but was exposed and undercut 
for about 2,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the four injured in the canyon had broken legs, and parts  
of the 9-mile Bright Angel Trail were washed out or covered by 
mudslides, rock falls and debris, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other trails were open but the park set a moratorium on  
backcountry hiking and camping permits until the trail is repaired 
-- which might take three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tucson, three police officers sprinted after a van with three  
people aboard as it was swept down a suddenly raging wash. One 
officer tossed a garden hose to a woman who climbed out of the van 
and was pulled to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other officers smashed a window and pulled a teen-ager out,  
but an 8-year-old girl was swept downstream as the van went under. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the officers, Mike Carroll, raced to the far side of a  
nearby bridge, jumped into the torrent, grabbed a tree limb and 
snatched her out by her clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those people are extremely lucky to be alive,'' said fire  
Capt. Brian Delfs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
