<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Terrorist Threats Detailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned about a series of doomsday scenarios  
ranging from an anthrax release in Boston to an Iraqi nerve gas 
attack on U.S. troops, a government commission proposes a 
far-reaching reform of agencies now handling such threats. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said the recommendations ``deserve serious  
consideration.'' He directed his national security adviser, Sandy 
Berger, to coordinate an interagency assessment and to report back 
within 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's report released Wednesday details a plan to  
give the vice president the lead role in preventing and dealing 
with the threat of weapons of mass destruction and calls for 
appointment of a high-profile national director for 
nonproliferation 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, a congressional study estimated it would  
cost a city of 500,000 about $1.3 million to acquire basic 
equipment to prepare for a hazardous material incident and $12 
million to be ``highly prepared'' for a chemical, biological, 
radiological or nuclear event. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's main proposals and conclusions were disclosed  
last week in interviews, but former CIA Director John Deutch, who 
headed the panel, released details of its work Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the country needs to be better protected,'' Deutch  
said, introducing his congressionally-established 12-member panel 
at the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., the commission's vice chairman,  
announced plans to introduce legislation today that would tighten 
export controls on items that might be used to manufacture heavily 
destructive weapons, including requiring electronic registration of 
all sales of such products-- a practice he said should be adopted 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are woefully unprepared, and we would like to see something  
done before some incident occurs,'' Specter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission concludes that the top levels of government are  
``not effectively organized to combat proliferation'' and 
recommends more presidential and vice presidential involvement in 
the issue, as well as a reorganization of the nearly 100 agencies 
now dealing with the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	One commission member, former Democratic Sen. James Exon of  
Nebraska, dissenting from the report's main recommendation, urged 
greater Cabinet-level involvement and a nonproliferation director 
who would report directly to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``What has been crafted, in my opinion, is another lower-level  
'working group,''' Exon said. 
</P>
<P>
	To underscore the motivation for its proposals, the commission  
listed four scenarios it said could occur: 
</P>
<P>
	--Anthrax is released in a Boston subway station during rush  
hour, sending 6,000 people to hospital emergency rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	--Analysts estimate that North Korean scientists have assembled  
10 nuclear weapons, and intelligence reports say North Korea is 
planning to sell two. 
</P>
<P>
	--Iraqi President Saddam Hussein orders Scud missiles carrying  
nerve agents fired upon U.S. troops in Turkey and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	--A disgruntled Russian scientist at Ozersk acquires 44 pounds of  
highly enriched uranium and sells it to Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	``These events have not taken place,'' it said. ``But they  
could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the separate General Accounting Office report, investigators  
compiled estimates of the resources it would take to meet a 
catastrophic attack on a U.S. city of 500,000. The report cautions 
that the estimates and accompanying list of needed supplies are 
meant only to be illustrative of possible needs. 
</P>
<P>
	For a typical hazardous materials incident, it estimated $1.3  
million to procure materials ranging from duct tape to mobil comand 
posts and another $3.3 million to sustain the preparedness over 10 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	For a high level of preparation, the estimates were $12.2  
million for initial procurement and $42.9 million over a decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 03:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nurse Probed in Patients Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Virginia health officials have suspended the  
license of a nurse who allegedly admitted giving morphine overdoses 
to two terminally ill patients to hasten their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhea E. Henson, who had been licensed in the state since 1987,  
helped care for the men at Inova Fair Oaks Hospital, where she 
worked in the critical care unit, according to Fairfax County 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	Both patients died in June. Police and hospital officials  
declined to identify them. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Henson declined Wednesday to comment on the investigation.  
No criminal charges have been filed. Her attorney, Dale Race, said 
his client contends that she is innocent of any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the state Board of Nursing issued an emergency order  
Wednesday declaring Ms. Henson a danger to the public and suspended 
her license immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	In its order, the nursing board said Ms. Henson admitted that  
she ``administered an inappropriate dose of morphine to Patient A 
in order to hasten his death.'' The board said she also admitted 
giving another patient a morphine overdose. 
</P>
<P>
	Morphine, a powerful and addictive narcotic, typically is used  
to relieve the pain of cancer patients whose disease has spread 
throughout their bodies. An overdose can stop the respiratory 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Tests at a state forensics laboratory indicated one of the  
patients had excessive morphine levels in his body at the time of 
death, The Washington Post reported today, citing unidentified 
sources. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 08:06:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Upholds Bill on Mining Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats and moderate Republicans are  
winning some battles as Congress moves toward shaping Interior 
Department programs for the coming year. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 377-47 shortly after midnight this morning to  
approve a $14 billion measure financing federal land and cultural 
programs for the coming fiscal year. The bill fell about $1.2 
billion short of the amount President Clinton requested, cutting 
his requests for land purchases and energy conservation, but 
Democrats and their moderate GOP allies managed a few wins. 
</P>
<P>
	In a victory for environmentalists over Western mining  
interests, the House voted 273-151 to require hard-rock mining 
companies using public lands to obey a 1997 Interior Department 
ruling limiting the size of their waste dumps to five acres per 
20-acre claim. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is no limitation,'' said Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., of  
pro-mining lawmakers' claims that companies could legally operate 
additional dumps. ``That would be a bad joke on America 
taxpayers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the amendment said it was based on a  
misinterpretation of law by overzealous bureaucrats that would hurt 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need these jobs,'' said Rep. Rick Hill, R-Mont. ``Our  
communities need these jobs, our families need these jobs, our 
schools need these jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy-eight Republicans joined 194 Democrats and one  
independent in upholding the limits on waste sites. Voting no were 
eight Democrats and 143 Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	A version of the legislation approved by the Senate  
Appropriations Committee would let companies ignore the Interior 
Department ruling, an interpretation of the 1872 law that governs 
mining for gold and other hard-rock minerals on federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry supporters say the five-acre limitation on waste sites  
is too small for modern techniques, which use chemicals like 
cyanide on vast piles of rock from open-pit mines. Opponents say 
the provision is the only pro-environmental one in the entire 
127-year-old law, which lets companies purchase federal lands for 
$2.50 an acre or lease them for $100 annually per 20-acre claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The House also voted 259-166 to ban the use of steel-jaw traps  
or neck snares for commercial or recreational purposes at the 520 
national wildlife refuges. The Senate bill has no similar language. 
</P>
<P>
	It voted 243-180 to add $13 million to a program that helps  
low-income people insulate and otherwise winterize their homes, 
bringing it to $133 million, the same as this year. It also voted 
225-198 against eliminating a new requirement that states provide 
$1 for every $3 they receive from the program. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the House trimmed $140 million from the  
legislation, part of a continuing effort by Republican leaders to 
satisfy conservatives demanding spending cuts. The reductions would 
come from clean coal and land acquisition programs plus a 0.48 
percent cut in the entire measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts are what ``we have to do to get where we have to be,''  
said House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chided Republicans for yielding to  
conservatives ``who detest government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other votes Wednesday, the House:  
</P>
<P>
	--By 217-207, rejected an attempt by Democrats and moderate  
Republicans to add $10 million each for the National Endowment for 
the Arts and the National Endowment for the Humanities. The House 
also defeated a conservative effort to cut the arts endowment by $2 
million by 300-124. The bill would provide NEA with $98 million 
next year, the same as this year and $52 million less than Clinton 
wanted. The NEH would get $111 million, the same as this year and 
$39 million below Clinton's request. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to block new federal regulations that would help Indian  
tribes open gambling casinos over objections by their states. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ordered the National Park Service to redraw its plans for a new  
visitors center at the Gettysburg battlefield in Pennsylvania. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
