<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Exec: Malone, Johnson Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While frustrated with the Los Angeles Dodgers'  
awful first half, the Fox executive in charge of the team doesn't 
blame general manager Kevin Malone or manager Davey Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel good about the people running the team. The one thing  
I feel quite comfortable about is it's not a a lack of trying and 
effort,'' said Chase Carey, co-chief operating officer of News 
Corp., the Dodgers' corporate owner. ``We don't like the results, 
but we do like the decisions being made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the second half of the season Thursday night, the  
Dodgers were last in the NL West at 39-47, 10 games behind 
division-leading San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	While Carey frequently praised Malone and Johnson during an  
interview at News Corp.'s New York offices, he did not mention 
Dodgers president Bob Graziano, a holdover from the days of Peter 
O'Malley's ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, News Corp. decided to have Graziano report to  
former NBA executive Rick Welts, the new president of the Fox 
Sports Entertainment Group, rather than directly to Carey. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles signed pitcher Kevin Brown to a $105 million,  
seven-year contract before the season and opened with a $79.2 
million payroll, second in the major leagues behind the New York 
Yankees ($85.1 million). The big spending caused the Dodgers to be 
criticized by division rivals San Francisco and San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the cheap shots in terms of us, that's sports,'' Carey  
said. ``I'm a big boy, I can take it,'' he said, adding that others 
owners were using the Dodgers as ``a scapegoat'' for baseball's 
economic disparity. 
</P>
<P>
	``When other owners take those kinds of shots, I don't think  
that's productive,'' he said. ``Baseball's problems from an 
economic perspective are industry problems and have been since long 
before we bought the Dodgers.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
