<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Backs Scientists' Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers should be permitted to keep  
federally supported work confidential to protect patient privacy 
and corporate secrets, several House members said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``One individual's right to government information may infringe  
upon another's right to privacy,'' said Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., 
chairman of the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee's 
panel on government management, information and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	His subcommittee is considering a measure sponsored by Rep.  
George Brown Jr., D-Calif., that would repeal a law providing more 
access to federally funded research information under the Freedom 
of Information Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The FOIA, passed in 1966, put the burden on the government to  
justify barring someone from having access to government 
information. Under the law, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., won 
approval last year to attach a provision to the Emergency 
Supplemental Appropriations Act of 1999 requiring most 
taxpayer-funded research to be made public upon request. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government funds 60 percent of the scientific  
research at universities. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxpayers, Shelby said, ``are entitled to this information, and  
will thus play a positive role in ensuring that the conclusions 
drawn from government-funded data and studies are more solid by 
allowing a more open process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the FOIA contains exemptions that protect the  
privacy of patients and trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the Office of Management and Budget crafts a rule that  
would allow anyone to see the scientific calculations that give 
rise to thousands of federal rules and policies, scientific, 
university and medical communities want to limit broad access to 
this data. 
</P>
<P>
	They say the rule would allow anyone to look at the data in  
studies that underpin highly controversial rules. Rape victims who 
participate in studies, for example, might hesitate to volunteer if 
they believe that their names and stories might be made public. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are pitfalls in unrestrained openness, including ... the  
chilling effect that inappropriate public scrutiny could have on 
the free exchange of ideas and the willingness to take risks to 
find answers,'' Harold Varmus, director of the National Institutes 
of Health Department of Health and Human Resources, told Horn's 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
	``FOIA was not designed to accommodate the confidentiality  
requirements of the most sensitive scientific data,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But business leaders believe they have the right to know the  
scientific basis for government regulations they must comply with. 
</P>
<P>
	``This situation will be harmful to taxpayers and the regulated  
community because they will be limited in their ability to 
understand the operations of government,'' said William Kovacs, 
vice president for environment and regulatory affairs for the U.S. 
Chamber of Commerce. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
