<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Cuba Differ on Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- U.S. Chamber of Commerce officials refused to sign  
a memorandum of understanding with their Cuban counterparts 
Thursday because it left out members of the country's nascent 
independent business community. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamber president Thomas Donohue said the chamber was dedicated  
to including the communist country's small self-employed sector. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate reaction from Cuban officials, who had  
hoped to sign the agreement on Thursday. A noontime signing 
ceremony had been included on a schedule of the American chamber's 
activities provided to foreign media. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been easy to sign a document,'' Donohue said.  
But he said the American chamber would instead look for ways to 
make contact with Cuba's small independent sector, which has no 
formal representation. The Cuban chamber represents just Cuban 
government-run firms and foreign firms with Cuban government 
partnerships. 
</P>
<P>
	Donohue said he did not expect the self-employed sector to form  
any kind of representative group soon, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect that it will be more of a marathon than a sprint,''  
he said. But they must somehow be included before the American 
chamber will sign the memorandum of understanding, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The self-employed sector did not exist until 1994, when Cuba's  
communist government approved the creation of certain small 
enterprises, such as family restaurants, and the licensing of 
tradesmen, such as mechanics, plumbers and beauticians. 
</P>
<P>
	Donohue held a six-hour meeting with President Fidel Castro  
Thursday, suggesting Cuba had assigned high importance to the 
visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Donohue said the chamber was opposed U.S. trade sanctions  
imposed at the height of the Cold War in 1962 -- a statement widely 
reported in Cuba's state-controlled press. 
</P>
<P>
	But Donohue also disagreed with many aspects of Cuba's  
political, economic and human rights policies, which the Cuban 
press did not report. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a tragedy that during one of the most exciting and  
dynamic periods of economic expansion and technological innovation, 
the Cuban people have been left out,'' Donohue said in a Wednesday 
speech at the University of Havana. ``It is the lack of private 
enterprise more than any other factor that has played the greatest 
role in holding Cuba back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
