<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed: ATM Fees Rise Substantially </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- ATM fees charged by banks and savings and  
loans increased significantly from 1997 to 1998 as did the number 
of institutions offering free checking, the Federal Reserve said in 
a report to Congress released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank, which compiles a similar report on fees  
imposed by banks and savings and loans every year, found 
substantial increases by banks in: overdraft charges for checks (an 
average increase of 90 cents, to $16.65); fees that banks charge 
their customers for using another bank's automated teller machine 
(an increase of 4 cents-7 cents, to $1.10); and ATM surcharges, 
which banks charge people to use their ATMs if they are not 
customers of that bank (an increase of 6 cents, to $1.20). 
</P>
<P>
	Fees that savings and loans charge their customers for using  
another institution's ATM increased by 7 cents-8 cents to 
$1.05-$1.07, while ATM surcharges rose an average of 11 cents to 
$1.15. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey found no significant increases by banks or thrifts  
for other kinds of fees, however, such as those on checking and 
savings accounts and for stop-payment orders on checks. 
</P>
<P>
	The percentage of banks and savings and loans offering free  
checking accounts, which don't pay interest but impose no fees, 
increased sharply over the year, the Fed found. Banks with free 
checking jumped from 3 percent in 1997 to 17 percent last year; 
thrifts increased from 7 percent to 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Banks continue to be a great value for consumers looking for  
the best combination of price, service and convenience,'' said 
Patricia Boerger, a spokeswoman for the American Bankers 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed found that in 1998, as in previous years, most of the  
fees charged by big banks operating in several states -- including 
those created by mergers -- were significantly higher than those 
levied by smaller banks. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, big banks charged an average $5.21 more for  
stop-payment orders on checks than smaller banks and about $4.50 
more for insufficient funds for checks and overdrafts, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey comes amid a wave of bank mergers, with New England  
powerhouses Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. the 
latest big institutions to announce a marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer advocates have criticized as excessive the fees that  
banks charge consumers for accounts, ATM machines and credit cards, 
and Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan has expressed concern over rising 
bank fees in congressional testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank fees are still increasing and big banks are charging  
bigger fees. It's a serious problem for consumers,'' Edmund 
Mierzwinski, consumer program director for U.S. Public Interest 
Research Group, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank report also found:  
</P>
<P>
	-- As in the previous year, the proportion of banks and savings  
and loans with ATMs that impose ATM surcharges rose substantially. 
It increased an average 17 to 18 percentage points, to 78 percent 
of banks and 57 percent of thrifts. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Five percent of banks and 4 percent of savings and loans  
charge a fee to issue ATM cards to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The minimum balance required to open a passbook savings  
account at savings and loans, for which customers are charged no 
fee if they keep a minimum balance and one monthly fee otherwise, 
increased by an average of $33, to $114. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was based on data from about 700 banks and 350  
savings and loans. The margin of error was plus or minus 5 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Some figures, such as the increases in some fees charged by  
banks and savings and loans, are reported in a range because they 
represent banks in different categories such as small, medium and 
large. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
