<HEADLINE> Brothers Reportedly Linked to Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Handwritten notations referring to  
rewards offered following a series of synagogue fires are among 
evidence linking two brothers to the arson attacks, The Sacramento 
Bee reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The notes mention the name of a Sacramento businessman, Michael  
Zwebner, who offered $10,000 following the June 18 fires. Next to 
the man's name were the notations ``Yid bizman'' and ``$10,000 on 
us,'' the Bee reported, citing unidentified sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, as a result of posting the reward, that has helped, then I  
am pleased and proud of it,'' the Israeli-born Zwebner said. ``I 
think any act of violence against any ethnic community is abhorrent 
to a civilized society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There also was a reference to Sacramento bounty hunter Leonard  
Padilla, who offered a $25,000 reward in the arson case: ``Leonard 
Padilla, bounty hunter, $25,000 on us,'' the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Padilla said he's received ``heavy'' police protection from  
local law enforcement since his name turned up in the suspects' 
notebook during last week's searches. 
</P>
<P>
	The notebook was found July 8 during a search of a storage  
locker rented to Benjamin Matthew Williams, 31, the newspaper 
quoted unidentified sources as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his brother, James Tyler Williams, 29, are being held in  
the Shasta County Jail on charges of receiving stolen property that 
investigators have linked to the murders of a gay couple. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple, Gary Matson and Winfield Mowder, were found slain  
July 1 in their home outside Redding in northern California. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers have not been charged with murder, although  
authorities said charges could be filed by the end of the week. 
They have pleaded innocent to the stolen property charges. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI officials have refused to confirm that the Williams brothers  
are suspects in the arsons, but Shasta County officials have said 
the brothers are linked to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI spokesman Nick Rossi refused to comment on the evidence  
reported by the newspaper, criticizing the paper for potentially 
jeopardizing the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In a jailhouse interview with the Redding Record Searchlight  
earlier this week, Tyler Williams insisted he never met Mowder and 
Matson and doesn't know anything about the fires. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
