<HEADLINE> Smoltz Tests Arm in Minors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Pitcher John Smoltz got the results he  
was looking for in his first appearance for the Greenville Braves, 
Atlanta's Double-A Southern League affiliate. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, rehabilitating from an elbow injury, struck out four in  
two shutout innings in Greenville's 6-1 loss to the Jacksonville 
Suns in the first game of a doubleheader Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, I'm trying to get my elbow in a position to be a  
little less stressful and still try to throw the same pitches,'' 
Smoltz said. ``I can't do some of the things I've been able to do, 
simply being I can't go eight, nine innings anymore. Not on a 
consistent basis anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, 8-3 with a 3.49 ERA and 86 strikeouts before going on  
the disabled list, is expected to throw one or two more innings in 
Jacksonville before rejoining Atlanta at Miami on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be able to throw the same way,'' Smoltz said. ``If I  
get the results, pain-wise, that's all I'm looking for. I'm not 
looking for six up, six down, or three up, three down. I'm looking 
for results on how my arm is.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
