<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Vowing To 'Earn Votes' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT DODGE, Iowa (AP) -- Spending more time shaking hands than  
talking, Texas Gov. George W. Bush vowed today to ``earn every 
single vote'' as he traveled across Iowa in a parade of brightly 
decorated campaign buses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's a big step going from governor to president, but  
I've had some pretty good training,'' said Bush. ``I've learned how 
to lead. I'm running for one single thing and that is to win back 
the White House in the year 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential front-runner took President Clinton  
to task for not moving faster to deal with a sagging farm economy, 
and professed himself taken aback by Clinton's criticism of what 
Bush likes to call his ``compassionate conservatism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said it's rare for a sitting president to single out  
candidates even before nominees are picked. ``I'm amazed that the 
president of the United States is spending time talking about me,'' 
he said. ``It says I must be a threat to his so-called legacy. I 
take it as a huge compliment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Wednesday that a ``compassionate conservative'' is  
basically a Republican who would like to do things but can't and 
feels terrible about it. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the president backed off those remarks.  
``Everything I said yesterday was in complete good spirits,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a veiled reference to Clinton's impeachment, Bush told  
supporters, ``Together we can show that after a time of tarnished 
ideals, politics can be higher and better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush opened his day with a rally on the banks of the Cedar  
River, and aides sketched out two days of grass-roots meetings with 
relatively small groups. ``Shaking as many hands as I can, I'd call 
that retail,'' said Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush stopped off for lunch in Webster City where he wolfed down  
a cheeseburger and fries. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best looking one we've worked for yet,'' Virginia  
Hughes squealed to a friend after giving Bush a hug. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor announced Thursday that, with $30 million in  
the bank, he wouldn't take federal matching funds for his campaign. 
``I want to have as much flexibility as possible to get out my 
message,'' he said. ``I want to win the general election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is well ahead in most polls for the Republican presidential  
nomination, and financially much better off than any rival except 
publisher Steve Forbes, who to a large extent is financing his own 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Bush's critics argue that he has campaigned scantily in  
important early states like Iowa and New Hampshire, and aides said 
the two-day grass-roots swing was aimed at showing that Bush can 
work a diner as well as anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intend to earn every single vote,'' said Bush. ``I intend to  
win the Iowa caucuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was drawing moderate-sized crowds, including many who said  
they were merely curious. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to find out what all the fuss was about,'' said Dean  
Close, of Independence, an independent. ``I was wondering why 
Republicans were excited about George Bush when they weren't 
excited about him in 1992.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has come under fire from rivals who say he's vague on the  
issues, and he took care to address a sagging farm economy that's 
troubled Midwestern states like Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must recognize in the halls of Congress that we're in a  
disaster,'' said Bush. ``This Congress must provide disaster 
relief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also chided Clinton for not moving fast enough, pointing to  
a tour Clinton just completed of poverty stricken areas of the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president recently has been on a poverty tour,'' said  
Bush. ``Perhaps he ought to come to farm country. If he wants to 
find some people who are hurting he ought to look right here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He called on Clinton to both boost crop insurance and offer  
direct aid to farmers, and to reject the use of food as a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton planned to be in Iowa on Friday. He was scheduled to  
participate in an education event and to attend a fund-raiser for 
Sen. Tom Harkin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
