<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticized for Teachers Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Schools need to look for alternative ways to  
get teachers into the classroom instead of discouraging them, say 
researchers critical of calls to end so-called emergency 
certification. 
</P>
<P>
	Any kind of certification (standard, emergency or alternative)  
is better than no certification at all, the Thomas Fordham 
Foundation, a privately run school-reform research organization, 
concluded in a collection of reports Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education is the last remaining field in America where people  
think you can boost quality by tightening the rules and multiplying 
the regulations,'' said Chester E. Finn Jr., foundation president 
and a former Reagan administration Education Department official. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-four states require teachers to pass a test to earn a  
license. But the tests, which vary, grant teachers credentials 
based on a range of measures from basic skills to knowledge of a 
specific subject to teaching performance. States often fill 
classroom shortages by allowing teachers to use emergency 
certificates or alternatives. The Education Department is spending 
$1 million to study how states license teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the studies show that students whose teachers possess a  
bachelor's or master's degree in math outperform other students in 
math, regardless of the teacher's certification. Finn said that and 
other findings contradict the President Clinton's proposal, 
outlined in his State of the Union Address this year, to make 
states and school districts phase out emergency-certified teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports say teachers have weak verbal and math skills and  
not nearly enough have a college major or minor in the subjects 
they teach. But even some standard state credentials fall short of 
putting better teachers in the classroom, they say. In California, 
Ohio, New York and Minnesota, approved preparation programs tend to 
have very low entry requirements, no exit requirements and low 
subject content, the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Licensure isn't a regulatory intrusion; it's a standard to  
protect children,'' said Bob Chase, president of the National 
Education Association, the nation's largest teachers union. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is critical for teachers to know the subject matter and  
content of what they are teaching -- and it is equally critical for 
them to understand how the brain works, how to instruct children 
with different skill levels, and how to keep a classroom full of 
kids in their seats so they can share their content knowledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the reports say, states such as Pennsylvania can  
maintain strong alternative certification programs while raising 
academic standards for teachers. Teachers there must take more 
academic courses and fewer education courses and pass licensing 
exams with higher scores, but college graduates who pass the exams 
may teach under the mentorship of a principal or master teacher 
without attending a school of education. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pennsylvania program is being challenged by a state  
teachers' union and a state teacher college association. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education interest groups have pushed misguided regulatory  
schemes that will make it even harder for our public schools to 
attract strong teachers into their ranks,'' said Finn. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers and education leaders who agree with their  
conclusions suggested alternatives that include giving would-be 
teachers more access and fewer hurdles, allowing key personnel 
decisions to be made by schools and judging teachers primarily by 
gains in student learning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
