<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Profits Jump 172 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co., its production problems apparently  
behind it, today reported second-quarter profits up 172 percent 
over last year and well above analysts' estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	For the quarter ended June 30, the aerospace company had net  
earnings of $701 million or 75 cents a share, compared with profits 
of $258 million or 26 cents a share a year earlier. Revenues rose 
13 percent, from $13.39 billion to $15.13 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The results far outpaced the 48 cents per share predicted in a  
survey of analysts by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-quarter figures include a one-time gain of $181  
million or 19 cents a share from a federal income tax audit 
settlement covering 1988-1991. Second-quarter earnings in 1998 were 
reduced by a non-recurring charge of $78 million or 8 cents a share 
to reflect the planned termination of the MD-11 jetliner program 
and late delivery costs associated with new-generation 737 
aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding those one-time items, second-quarter earnings were up  
55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second-quarter results demonstrate growing momentum and  
confidence,'' said Phil Condit, Boeing chairman and chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our commercial airplanes group is on plan -- delivering  
airplanes and improving margins every day. Boeing delivered 165 
commercial airplanes this quarter -- on time, and with 17 percent 
fewer employees and a 10 percentage point improvement in overtime 
from the highest levels in 1998.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing struggled with production line snarls, delayed deliveries  
and the Asian financial crisis during the past two years. It lost 
$178 million in 1997 and had depressed earnings of $1.1 billion in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's Commercial Airplanes division had second-quarter  
operating earnings of $435 million, compared with a loss of $178 
million a year ago, when it delivered 137 planes in the quarter. 
Condit said the improvement was principally due to better cost 
control on the new 737 and 777 jetliner programs, more deliveries, 
and lower research and development spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's military aircraft and missiles segment had a 16 percent  
improvement in operating revenues, while the space and 
communications segment was down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, Boeing had profits of $1.17  
billion or $1.24 a share, compared with net earnings of $308 
million or 31 cents a share in 1998. Revenues rose 12 percent, from 
$26.33 billion to $29.52 billion. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
