<HEADLINE> Orioles' Miller Says It's Not Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Ray Miller gathered the Baltimore Orioles  
together before batting practice Thursday and told them the 
playoffs are not out of reach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them we're down 12 games in the loss column, which  
means we only have to make up one game a week,'' the Orioles 
manager said. ``I haven't given up yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller delivered essentially the same speech last year after the  
Orioles reached the All-Star break with a 38-50 record. Baltimore 
proceeded to win 14 of 15 to get back in contention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles were 36-51 before Thursday's game against Montreal,  
while second-place Boston is 49-39. Baltimore won two straight over 
Philadelphia before the break, giving Miller cause for optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look at the standings, the last series and the club coming  
back fresh,'' Miller noted. ``We have about a month-and-a-half to 
change things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said there won't be large changes before the July 31  
trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``The media creates much of that talk. The only time we will  
consider a trade is if it helps us win now and in the future,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it appears certain that catcher Lenny Webster will soon  
be traded, and starting pitcher Juan Guzman is likely to follow. 
Guzman is eligible to become a free agent after this season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
