<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Rangers Sign Tim Taylor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Rangers continued their free-agent  
signing blitz Thursday, agreeing to terms with center Tim Taylor on 
a four-year $5.8 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't lie to you, it's about money,'' said Taylor, who had  
four goals and seven assists in 49 games with Boston last season. 
``I understand I can't play forever. I came where the money was 
being offered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers, who missed the NHL playoffs the last two seasons,  
have signed five free agents in the last month at a cost of $59.9 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Theo Fleury agreed to a three-year, $24 million deal  
last week and on Tuesday New York signed backup goalie Kirk McLean 
for two years and $1.75 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier the Rangers agreed on four-year deals with 33-year-old  
left wing Valeri Kamensky for $17 million and 30-year-old 
defenseman Stephane Quintal for $11.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 30, has 39 goals and 40 assists in 267 games with  
Detroit and Boston and was a member of the Red Wings 1997 Stanley 
Cup champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I owed it to myself and my family to take the best offer,'' he  
said. ``The decision was made for me. There wasn't much to make a 
decision over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Thursday, the Rangers announced the retirement of  
defenseman Jeff Beukeboom, who was unable to resume playing because 
of a series of concussions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profits Predicted for Nissan by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARMINGTON HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- After two weeks on the job, the  
former Renault executive charged with overhauling Nissan Motor Co. 
says the Japanese automaker needs to start turning a profit again 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nissan will have to come back to profit very quickly,'' Carlos  
Ghosn said. ``When I say quickly, I'm saying specifically the year 
2000. I think the year 1999 is already, unfortunately, in the 
red.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn is the Renault SA vice president who became Nissan's chief  
operating officer July 1. He's on a two-week tour of Nissan's U.S. 
operations as part of his effort to develop a turnaround plan by 
late September. He spoke Thursday to auto writers at Nissan's 
research and development center outside Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian-born Ghosn, dubbed ``Le Cost Killer'' for his  
successful efficiency drive at French automaker Renault SA, was 
dispatched to Tokyo after Renault agreed in March to invest $5.4 
billion to gain a 36.8 percent stake in the debt-ridden Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan has lost money in seven of the last eight years. Ghosn  
noted that from 1991 to 1998, Nissan lost 1.7 percentage points of 
worldwide market share to 6.6 percent. That's the equivalent of 
800,000 vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	He hinted that Nissan may have to close or sell plants outside  
the United States to deal with its global overcapacity if sales do 
not increase quickly. Nissan's only wholly owned U.S. plant is in 
Smyrna, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have overinvested for what we sell,'' he said. ``This is a  
cost that we cannot bear, especially if this overcapacity leads to 
long-term overcapacity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn (pronounced GOHN) said he was convinced after talking to  
managers and employees that the company was eager to change. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Japan, people have been very open,'' he said. ``Very open,  
very candid, with a lot of sense of responsibility and a lot of 
sense that we will not have a lot of chances. We don't have a lot 
of time to fix Nissan's problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn said, ``All the people I've met, all the discussions I've  
had lead me to conclude that people have had enough of losing 
market share, people have had enough of being in the red.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan's U.S. sales have been improving lately; they were up 8  
percent in the first half of the year. The automaker has an 
aggressive plan to introduce a series of new models over the next 
few years, with an emphasis on light trucks -- the market's most 
profitable segment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn said Nissan may even decide to enter the full-size pickup  
segment, which has been the highly profitable domain of Detroit's 
automakers. It would join Toyota Motor Corp., which recently 
introduced a large pickup built in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our success in the U.S. is not important for Nissan, it's  
vital for Nissan,'' he said. ``Nissan has much more potential in 
the U.S. than what's it's delivering today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn said there is virtually no chance Renault will sell its  
cars in the United States under the Nissan badge within the next 
three years. It would take that long to design vehicles with the 
U.S. market in mind, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to announce his turnaround plan in October before the  
Tokyo auto show. He said it will be based in large part on what 
Nissan employees have identified as problems and solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	A priority will be improving relations with Nissan's parts  
suppliers to cut costs and encourage more innovation and 
cooperation in developing new vehicles, Ghosn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan also needs to be more innovative and create a more  
consistent design and styling theme with its new vehicles, he said. 
Once considered a trendsetter with such cars as the Datsun 240Z, 
Nissan in the last decade has been known more for blandness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made some great cars. We have made cars which are not  
so great,'' he said. ``We will have to bring back the attractive 
cars that our customers are asking us to show. And I think we have 
the potential.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astros' Dierker Returns to Baseball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Larry Dierker's goals will be simple at first.  
</P>
<P>
	On the day he returns as manager of the Houston Astros, all he  
wants is to drive himself to the Astrodome and to be on time. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker will return as manager of the Astros tonight for the  
first time since June 13, when he suffered a grand mal seizure that 
required brain surgery to remove a cluster of blood vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros play host to Detroit tonight through Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Looking fit and relaxed, Dierker showed up at the Astrodome on  
Wednesday for an optional team workout. His hair is beginning to 
grow back, and he feels normal except for occasional forgetfulness 
about time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strangest thing is that time seems to have no meaning. I  
find myself out of touch with time,'' Dierker said. ``It's been a 
month since this happened and it seems like two weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bothering Dierker more is the fact that he's prohibited from  
driving for another five months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not being able to drive is driving me up the wall,'' Dierker  
said. ``Every day I have the urge to get in the truck and drive 
somewhere. My wife has a busy life and she's going to get tired 
having to drive me everywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fans have been asked to wear brightly colored Hawaiian shirts --  
Dierker's favorite attire -- to welcome him back. Dierker met the 
media Wednesday wearing a lei. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be delighted tomorrow, but I haven't been antsy to get  
back,'' Dierker said. ``I don't feel anything but normal. I'd say 
at no point did I worry about my recovery. I had confidence that I 
would recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros begin the second half of the season with a long  
injury list that includes two stars, third baseman Ken Caminiti and 
left fielder Moises Alou. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather have Alou back than myself and I'd rather have Camy  
back than myself,'' Dierker said. ``But what we've gotten from the 
outfielders and third basemen we have wasn't so bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker's No. 49 jersey came down from the dugout, where it has  
hung in his honor since his collapse in the eighth inning of a game 
against the San Diego on June 13. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans no changes in his managing style.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing has affected my intellect,'' Dierker said. ``I feel  
the same and my philosophy is the same. I know what I want to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker checked out of Methodist Hospital on June 23 and has  
been recuperating at home. He has managed a few visits to the 
Astrodome and a few rounds of golf while convalescing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have the energy for a stressful workout and I don't  
have permission to do it, so that doesn't matter,'' Dierker said. 
``I was able to play golf a few times and I was able to do that in 
the heat of the day so I feel pretty good about my condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros went 13-14 under interim manager Matt Galante.  
</P>
<P>
	Dierker's collapse visibly shook his players and hushed the home  
crowd, which was never officially told what happened. He was 
treated on the field and ushered out of the stadium in an 
ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros, behind starting pitcher Shane Reynolds, were leading  
4-1 in the game, which was suspended and will resume when the 
Padres return to Houston on July 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker's condition was diagnosed as arteriovenous malformation.  
Dr. Rob Parrish, who performed the surgery, said the mass was about 
the size of a ``really big jalapeno.'' Parrish forecast a full 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Dierker, first base coach Jose Cruz left the team  
May 10 with an irregular heart beat and hitting coach Tom McCraw 
left May 16 to begin treatment for prostate cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz has rejoined the team. McCraw is still undergoing treatment  
in California. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
