<HEADLINE> Schumacher Will Probably Miss Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Two-time world champion Michael Schumacher is  
probably finished for the Formula One season after breaking his leg 
in a crash at the British Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher's manager said Thursday the Ferrari driver will need  
three months to recover from the crash last week. The season ends 
Oct. 31 in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is that he gets completely healthy  
and his leg injuries heal right. After that we will think about a 
comeback,'' manager Willi Weber said after visiting Schumacher at a 
Swiss clinic. ``A pause of three months is realistic. It will take 
that long for a full recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher, whose accident is believed to have been caused by a  
loose bolt on the rear brakes, plowed into a tire wall on the 
race's first lap. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old German might heal in time to race in the  
season's final Grand Prix in Suzuka, Japan. However, he probably 
wouldn't want to take a risk after saying he was ``lucky to be 
alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surgeons inserted a foot-long pin into his leg to fix two  
breaks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
