<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Flat for 2 Months in a Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer inflation, helped out by falling  
prices for gasoline and airline tickets, remained flat for the 
second month in a row -- the best showing in 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported Thursday that its Consumer Price  
Index -- the most closely watched gauge of inflation -- stood still 
in June, as it did in May. Economists had expected a slight rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time prices showed no increase for two straight months  
was in 1986, when for three consecutive months the CPI actually 
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those two big goose eggs will make it politically tough for  
the Fed'' to raise interest rates at its next meeting, on Aug. 24, 
said First Union economist Mark Vitner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly takes the pressure off for another increase,''  
agreed economist Sandra Shaber of the WEFA Group. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, the annual rate of inflation is 2.2 percent,  
compared with a 1.6 percent rise for all of 1998, the smallest 
increase in a dozen years. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets greeted the inflation report with enthusiasm.  
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 38.31 points to 
11,186.41. Broader stock indicators posted bigger gains, with the 
Nasdaq composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index reaching 
new closing highs. 
</P>
<P>
	Worried that inflationary pressures could be building, the Fed  
at its last meeting, on June 30, bumped up interest rates for the 
first time in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed's pre-emptive strike to keep inflation under control  
came after prices at the retail and wholesale level spiked in 
April, generating inflation fears. That increase was caused by a 
sharp run-up in prices for gasoline and other energy products. 
</P>
<P>
	But just as in May, the good showing on prices in June reflected  
a big drop in energy costs. Gasoline prices fell a sharp 3.2 
percent last month, the most in more than two years. Gasoline 
prices were down 2.7 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in gasoline prices contributed to an overall decline of  
1.2 percent in energy costs, which followed a 1.3 percent drop in 
May and helped reverse a part of April's huge 6.1 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	However, economists said gasoline prices in July are rising and  
if that continues overall consumers prices will probably edge up in 
the next report. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline fares also were down 4.8 percent in June, the largest  
drop in more than three years. Economists said that airlines have 
too many unfilled seats and are slashing fares to keep planes full, 
something they expect to continue in the months ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	New car prices, meanwhile, edged down 0.3 percent, reflecting  
foreign competition and efforts by dealers to make room in 
showrooms for new models. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparel prices fell 0.4 percent last month, the fifth decline  
this year. Economists said that with so many stores for shoppers to 
choose among, retailers are cutting prices to lure them in. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices were unchanged in June, after a sharp 0.4 percent  
rise the month before. Big declines in prices of pork and fresh 
vegetables held back food prices despite a sharp rise in beef 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the volatile food and energy sectors, price pressures  
remained tame. This ``core rate'' of inflation was up just 0.1 
percent in June, the same as May. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
