<DOCNO> APW19990715.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Plays Uruguay in Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A two-point victory won't do when  
the United States plays Uruguay in the Americans' first game of the 
Olympic qualifying tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole objective is to win, and to win by a large margin,''  
said Kevin Garnett, who is well aware that this American team will 
not only be judged by its success, but by its margin of success. 
</P>
<P>
	American teams have seen their average margin of victory shrink  
from 43.8 points per game in the 1992 Olympics -- the first team to 
use NBA players -- to 37.7 points in the 1994 World Championships 
and 32.3 points in the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the level of competition in this tournament a notch  
below what the United States will see in the 2000 Olympics, that 
trend could see a reversal. 
</P>
<P>
	The American players also are mindful of the reputations of the  
NBA teams that preceded them, including the 1992 team that won the 
gold medal in Barcelona, the 1996 team that won in Atlanta, and the 
1994 team that won the world championships in Toronto, but was more 
remembered for its in-your-face style of play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys tend to get on the U.S. about playing flamboyant, but  
you've got to understand the other teams are doing the same thing. 
You just don't understand what they're saying,'' Garnett said. 
``Rude in their country might be to give you an elbow. Rude in our 
country is to stick your finger up. 
</P>
<P>
	``The basketball part of it is about trying to win. That's the  
way you've got to look at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States opens play tonight against Uruguay, one of the  
lesser-known and lowest-regarded teams in the 10-nation field. 
</P>
<P>
	In first round games Wednesday, Uruguay defeated Cuba 87-84 in  
overtime, Canada beat Argentina 77-70, Puerto Rico routed Venezuela 
81-56 and Brazil defeated the Dominican Republic 70-64. 
</P>
<P>
	The international style of play, with its premium on outside  
shooting and aversion to physical play, does not exactly inject 
fear into the hearts of the fourth U.S. national team made up of 
professional players. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the U.S. players insist they are not overlooking the  
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't put anything past anybody in the game of basketball,''  
Vin Baker of the Seattle SuperSonics said. ``As confident as we are 
and as good as we are, anything can happen. It can snow in San 
Juan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is only the second time the United States has had to  
qualify for the Olympics in men's basketball. The other time was 
1992, when the original Dream Team won the Tournament of the 
Americas in Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying became necessary last summer when the U.S. team  
failed to win the world championships in Athens, Greece, after a 
league lockout forced NBA players from the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Grouped with the United States in the opening round are Cuba,  
Argentina, Canada and Uruguay. Group `B' consists of Puerto Rico, 
Venezuela, the Dominican Republic, Panama and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team is relatively young, with only three players --  
Steve Smith of Atlanta, Tim Hardaway of Miami and Gary Payton of 
Seattle -- older than 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine NBA veterans -- Allan Houston, Baker, Smith, Hardaway,  
Payton, Jason Kidd, Tim Duncan, Garnett and Tom Gugliotta -- will 
also have spots on the Olympic roster next summer. The other three 
roster spots on the qualifying team are held by three rookies -- 
Wally Szczerbiak of Minnesota, Richard Hamilton of Washington and 
Elton Brand of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Gugliotta broke his nose and Hamilton sprained his ankle  
Wednesday as the U.S. team held its final practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Gugliotta was elbowed in the nose by Kidd, while Hamilton  
sprained his right ankle while stepping off the practice court. 
Both are expected to be available against Uruguay. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to see zone defenses, and they are going to make  
us work for 30 seconds when we're on defense,'' Kidd said. 
``They'll use a lot of the shot clock, and while we're used to 
keeping it inside, they'll throw it inside to set something up 
outside for one of their shooters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of NBA players are scattered across the rosters  
of the competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Nash of Dallas and Todd MacCulloch of Washington are  
playing for Canada, and Felipe Lopez of Vancouver is playing for 
the Dominican Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Jackson of Indiana plans to join the Dominican team for the  
second round, which begins Monday. Four of the five teams in each 
group advance to the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	After playing Uruguay, the Americans play Canada on Friday,  
Argentina on Saturday and Cuba on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The most important games will be the semifinals a week from  
Saturday. The winners of those two games earn berths at the Sydney 
Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
