<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 38.31  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today, lifting some market indexes  
to new highs, as another report showed that the economy's 
surprising strength still hasn't sparked inflation. The Dow Jones 
industrial average advanced 38.31 to 11,186.41, finishing the day 
less than 15 points from Monday's record close of 11,200.98. 
Broader stock indicators posted bigger gains than the Dow, with the 
Nasdaq composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index reaching 
new closing highs. The Nasdaq was up 21.18 at 2,839.31. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        11,186.41  + 38.31
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1835  Declines 1059  Unchgd  634
NYSE Volume:         770,272,910
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online121       - 2
S&AMP;P 500:         1409.62 + 11.45
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          821.73  +  8.73
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,839.31  + 21.18
Gold(final) -    $254.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Unchanged in June  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices were unchanged in June for the  
second straight month, the best showing on inflation in 13 years, 
the Labor Department said today. Energy costs dropped sharply and 
food prices held steady. The last time the Consumer Price Index was 
flat for two straight months was in 1986, when for three 
consecutive months the CPI actually fell. In other economic news, 
the Commerce Department said business inventories rose 0.3 percent 
in May. The Labor Department said new claims for jobless benefits 
rose sharply last week to 310,000, the highest level in a month. 
That was up 11,000 from the previous week. 

</P>
<P>
	EPA Retracts Hewlett-Packard Deal  
</P>
<P>
	CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency has  
withdrawn a settlement with Hewlett-Packard Co. over inkjet printer 
chemicals. The Corvallis Gazette-Times reported that the deal was 
nixed partly because the world's second-largest computer maker 
refused to permit an audit of its records. Sylvia Lowrance, an EPA 
enforcement adminstrator, said the order had to be revised because 
of issues raised by an agency board reviewing the settlement and 
new concerns that have come to the agency's attention. A 
Hewlett-Packard spokeswoman said the deal was withdrawn because the 
two sides simply failed to agree on details for a government audit 
of the company's chemical records at its U.S. manufacturing plants. 
Hewlett-Packard shares were at 113, down 4 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco Announces Discovery, Sale  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC announced a major oil discovery in  
the Gulf of Mexico today and also said it plans to shed $10 billion 
in underperforming assets over the next three years. And while the 
company aims to boost capital spending by $26 billion by 2001, it 
also said it would slash expenses by 20 percent over the same 
period. BP Amoco also plans to eliminate an additional 3,000 jobs 
and to shift its emphasis increasingly toward exploration and 
production and away from less profitable refinery and 
petrochemicals operations. The company's new offshore discoveries 
include the Crazy Horse prospect located in 6,000 feet of water 125 
miles southeast of New Orleans. It has estimated recoverable 
reserves of 1 billion barrels. BP Amoco has a 75 percent stake in 
the site, with Mobil holding the remaining 25 percent. BP Amoco 
shares were at 121 1/2, up 3. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Earnings Drop 21 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. reported its second-quarter  
earnings fell 21 percent as lingering economic problems and the 
discovery of contaminated Coke products in Europe depressed the 
soft drink maker's sales. The earnings report, which met Wall 
Street's expectations, closed out a difficult quarter for Coke. But 
analysts noted that the company nonetheless made nearly $1 billion 
in the three months ending June 30 and said the Coke brand is still 
a world power. Net income for the three months ended June 30 was 
$942 million or 38 cents per diluted share, down from $1.19 billion 
or 48 cents per share a year earlier. Net revenues for the quarter 
were up 4 percent, from $5.15 billion a year ago to $5.38 billion 
this year. Coca-Cola shares were at 64, up 2 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Profits Jump 172 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co., its production problems apparently  
behind it, today reported second-quarter profits up 172 percent 
over last year and well above analysts' estimates. For the quarter 
ended June 30, the aerospace company had net earnings of $701 
million or 75 cents a share, compared with profits of $258 million 
or 26 cents a share a year earlier. Revenues rose 13 percent, from 
$13.39 billion to $15.13 billion. Boeing shares were at 46 3/4, down 
7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	New York Times Earnings Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times Co. reported an 11 percent  
rise in second-quarter income on higher advertising revenue and 
lower newsprint prices. The company said today that it earned $83.5 
million, or 47 cents per share, in its second quarter. The results 
did not include a $4 million pre-tax charge for expenses related to 
staff reductions at The Boston Globe. Revenues for the quarter rose 
4 percent to $779.4 million. 

</P>
<P>
	McGraw-Hill Earnings Rise 16 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The McGraw-Hill Cos. reported a 16 percent  
increase in second-quarter earnings today due to gains at Business 
Week, as well as growth in its financial services and education 
businesses. McGraw-Hill earned $90 million, or 45 cents per share. 
Revenues rose 5 percent to $922.7 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Suit Dismissed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge has thrown out Abercrombie &AMP;  
Fitch's lawsuit against retailing rival American Eagle Outfitters, 
which alleged American Eagle copied Abercrombie's image and 
business practices to boost sales. Judge John D. Holschuh of the 
U.S. District Court in Columbus, Ohio, ruled late yesterday that 
forbidding ``other clothing retailers from adopting similar methods 
of advertising would be unduly anticompetitive.'' Abercrombie 
chairman and chief executive Michael Jeffries said the company will 
appeal. 

</P>
<P>
	AP, RealNetworks Team on Web News  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Associated Press is teaming up with  
RealNetworks Inc. to launch a new service offering audio and video 
news to AP's member newspapers and broadcasters for use on their 
Web sites, the news cooperative announced today. The AP already 
offers audio and video news as part of its Internet news service, 
The Wire, and separately to selected newspapers. The new service 
makes more of this material available to the cooperative's members 
as a separate product. Members will be able to purchase some or all 
of the three parts of the new service: regular audio updates on top 
stories; audio and video clips to accompany major stories, nd live 
audio and video coverage of at least one event per day. 

</P>
<P>
	Functions of PC Put on Single Chip  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- National Semiconductor Corp. today  
unveiled a new computer chip that puts most of the functions of a 
PC on a single chip, a move that will bring more power and 
functionality to small information devices. The new Geode SC1400 
chip will do the work of what would normally require six different 
chips, company spokeswoman Linda Ashmore said. National 
Semiconductor is targeting the chip for use in ``information 
appliances'' such as television set-top boxes, hand-held 
information devices such as the Palm Pilot, and, eventually, car 
navigation systems. 

</P>
<P>
	NextCard Sues Providian Over Web Ad  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Web-based credit company NextCard sued  
credit giant Providian for copyright infringement in a case that 
could set a precedent for how the law applies to Internet 
advertising. In the suit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in 
San Francisco, NextCard accused Providian of copying a Web banner 
ad that features a descending thermometer to represent falling 
interest rates. NextCard said the ad is its most effective, with 
about 680,000 Web users clicking on it. ``There are no proprietary 
rights in banner ads,'' said Providian spokesman Marc Loewenthal. 
``They are attention-getting devices that do not reflect any 
original work of authorship.'' 

</P>
