<HEADLINE> Edwards Wins Salamanca Triple Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALAMANCA, Spain (AP) -- Four years after setting a world  
triple-jump record, Britain's Jonathan Edwards returned to Spain to 
score another impressive triumph in the Salamanca Grand Prix track 
meet. 
</P>
<P>
	With a jump of 58 feet, 1 1/4 inches, Edwards beat Cuba's Yoelbi  
Quesada by a whopping 17 1/4 inches on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago in this meet, Edwards set a world record of 59  
feet and pushed it to 60- 1/4 later the same year at Goteborg, 
Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he didn't threaten his own mark, he dominated the field  
Thursday night, leaving Quesada in arrears at 56-8. 
</P>
<P>
	With the unexplained absence of Olympic silver medalist James  
Beckford of Jamaica, Spain's Yago Lamela won the long jump at 27-2. 
Portugal's Carlos Calado was second at 26-2 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamela said competing without Beckford made him feel ``alone and  
without rivals,'' and put a break on the ``competitiveness needed 
for great jumps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's Tatiana Grigorieva won the women's pole vault at  
14-9, then failed on two attempts to set a world-record 15-1 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain's Pedro Pablo Nolet won the men's 100 meters in a photo  
finish over countryman Venancio Jose Murcia, both in 10.26 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Doug Turner took the men's 200 meters in 20.56  
seconds, .39 seconds faster than Spaniard Jordi Mayoral. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosa Akhigb of Nigeria won the women's 100 in 11.21 seconds, .16  
seconds faster than Australia's Knee Bone. The Australian won the 
200 in 22.90. 
</P>
</TEXT>
