<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report Criticizes Justice Department </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department investigation of  
campaign finance abuses was delayed but ultimately not impaired by 
mishandling of FBI intelligence on possible Chinese efforts to 
influence U.S. politics, Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	At her weekly news conference, Reno praised a report by  
Justice's inspector general, Michael Bromwich, that criticized 
department officials for showing Congress raw, uncorroborated 
intelligence but also took FBI counterspies to task for earlier 
keeping the same data from campaign finance investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was reading the 569-page top secret report ``in  
detail now, and I might quibble about some things, but I think it 
was a good, constructive report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Releasing a brief summary Wednesday, Bromwich found that at  
first raw data on possible Chinese attempts to influence U.S. 
politics was held too closely by the FBI for fear of revealing how 
it was obtained but later the same data was circulated too widely 
to avoid congressional criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	By rushing to meet demands from the Republican-controlled  
Congress for information about campaign finance abuses, Justice 
officials abandoned long-held standards and provided raw 
intelligence ``information of dubious quality,'' Bromwich 
concluded. He said this could endanger the investigation and the 
rights of those under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	He found ``no improper intent to conceal information'' from the  
department, Congress or the National Security Council. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime something is delayed, you can call that bungling. But  
... the (campaign finance) investigation itself was not impaired in 
the end,'' Reno said. ``It is important for all of us, not just the 
FBI, to make sure ... the information ... is furnished in a manner 
that will be helpful in a criminal investigation while at the same 
time protecting sources and methods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The department obtained a guilty plea from businessman Johnny  
Chung, who claims he was given $300,000 by China's military 
intelligence chief for President Clinton's 1996 re-election. 
Investigators say Chung gave only $20,000 of this to the Democratic 
Party and spent the rest on himself. They haven't corroborated who 
gave the money to Chung; China has denied it. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI welcomed many of Bromwich's suggestions and said it has  
begun more regular meetings with other agencies and stepped up 
production of ``finished'' analyses of raw intelligence data. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno ordered Bromwich's investigation after an embarrassing  
incident on Sept. 11, 1997, before the Senate Governmental Affairs 
Committee. The CIA told the committee about two pieces of Chinese 
intelligence from the FBI, which FBI Director Louis Freeh said he 
had not heard until the CIA testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said that data related to whether California  
businessman Ted Sioeng acted on behalf of China in donating 
$250,000 to the Democratic National Committee and $50,000 to a 
Republican think tank. Sioeng's attorney denied the Chinese 
directed or funded the contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	These two items and other FBI China intelligence actually had  
reached Freeh and Reno, but was haphazardly buried in various 
reports so ``senior officials were unaware that they had ever 
received it,'' Bromwich wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	By late 1997, all of it was given to four congressional  
committees, campaign finance investigators and the National 
Security Council. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither the department nor the Congress is well-served by  
replacing the careful screening of information with a headlong dash 
to supply information that results in the collapse of standards of 
quality and the provision of evidence of dubious quality,'' 
Bromwich wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, until Reno stepped in, FBI counterspies insisted on  
giving campaign finance investigators paraphrases of their data 
rather than direct access to the intelligence. Bromwich said the 
FBI counterspies ``did not strike an appropriate balance between 
(their) needs and those of the (campaign finance) task force and 
main Justice.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
