<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Flyers Announcer Hart Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Gene Hart, who broadcast Philadelphia hockey  
games over radio and television for 28 years under the nickname 
``Voice of the Flyers,'' died at age 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart died late Wednesday afternoon at Our Lady of Lourdes  
Hospital in Camden, said Michelle Chierici, hospital director of 
public relations. He was admitted to the hospital's critical-care 
unit after he became severely dehydrated and developed an infection 
following chemotherapy to treat a tumor. 
</P>
<P>
	Always ending his broadcast with ``Good night and good hockey,''  
Hart was the play-by-play man for the Flyers from their inaugural 
season in 1967-68 until 1994-95, calling the team's most thrilling 
moments and helping spawn legions of devoted Flyers fans with his 
frenetic style. 
</P>
<P>
	He was best known for his call of the Flyers' Stanley  
Cup-winning 1-0 victory over the Boston Bruins on May 19, 1974, at 
the Spectrum. ``The Flyers win the Stanley Cup! The Flyers win the 
Stanley Cup!'' he exclaimed, over and over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still get goose bumps when I think of that call,'' Flyers  
chairman Ed Snider once said. ``It will go down in sports history 
as one of the greatest broadcast moments of all time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart, a public school teacher in New Jersey for 15 years,  
received a part-time salary from the Flyers at the beginning of his 
broadcasting career while he kept his job as an announcer for the 
now-defunct Aquarama. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I could say they had 288 tapes and mine was the best,''  
he said. ``But it was really a matter of expediency. I was the 
right guy at the right time in the right place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart's broadcasting highlights include six Stanley Cup finals,  
five NHL All-Star games and two NHL-Soviet all-star series. Hart 
was inducted into the Flyers' Hall of Fame in 1992 and the Hockey 
Hall of Fame in 1997, one of 20 broadcasters so honored. 
</P>
<P>
	In later years, the job became increasingly tough for Hart. He  
occasionally had trouble keeping up with the game's fast pace and 
he sometimes misidentified players. At the end of the 1995 season, 
the Flyers relieved Hart of his broadcasting duties and assigned 
him to a community relations post. 
</P>
<P>
	Although disappointed, he took the news gracefully.  
</P>
<P>
	``You can't be unhappy with 28 years. I've had a dream career,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the last two seasons, he called games for the Philadelphia  
Phantoms, the Flyers' American Hockey League affiliate, on cable. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart underwent heart bypass surgery in 1985 and has been on  
kidney dialysis for almost a year due to complications from 
diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral arrangements were private. A memorial was scheduled for  
1 p.m Sunday at Philadelphia's First Union Center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC: Cease Use of Diarrhea Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The government is recommending that doctors  
temporarily stop giving children a diarrhea vaccine because at 
least 20 infants have developed a bowel obstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday  
that RotaShield, the vaccine against rotavirus, has not been 
conclusively linked to bowel obstruction, but early studies show it 
may increase the risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The obstruction occurs when one part of the bowel becomes  
enfolded within another. Symptoms include vomiting, bloody stools 
and abdominal pain. Surgery is often needed to clear the blockage 
if it isn't caught early. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC recommended suspending use of the vaccine in all  
children -- including those who have begun the three-dose series -- 
until November so health officials can conclude additional studies. 
Following the CDC's move, the American Academy of Pediatrics issued 
the same recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's enough to make us worry,'' said Dr. Melinda Wharton, head  
of the CDC's child vaccine preventable diseases branch. ``We're 
fortunate that rotavirus is a seasonal disease so we can postpone 
vaccination for a few months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rotavirus, an intestinal infection, is the leading cause of  
severe diarrhea in children under 5 in the United States. Each 
year, an estimated 3 million American children are sickened, 50,000 
are hospitalized, and 20 die. The disease primarily occurs in the 
winter and spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine's manufacturer, Philadelphia-based Wyeth-Ayerst  
Laboratories, said 1 million infants have been vaccinated with 
RotaShield since it received government approval in August. The 
three-dose series is given at ages 2 months, 4 months and 6 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Before its approval by the Food and Drug Administration, five  
cases of the bowel obstruction were reported for every 10,000 
vaccine recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the bowel obstruction was listed as a potential  
adverse reaction on the package insert. The CDC said it is still 
investigating, but based on the early findings so far, it appears 
that the bowel obstruction rate may be higher than expected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
