<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Second-Quarter Profits Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing's second-quarter operating earnings surged  
55 percent as the aerospace company seems to have overcome the 
production problems that hurt it over the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	For the three months ended June 30, Boeing recorded operating  
income of $793 million, up from $416 million in the year-ago 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings of 56 cents per share easily surpassed forecasts by  
First Call analysts of 48 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are very pleasing results,'' said analyst Peter Jacobs  
with Ragen MacKenzie in Seattle. ``The company is showing continued 
improvements in their commercial operations, solid performance in 
the defense and space areas, and one can definitely say the worst 
of the problems are behind the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing had net earnings of $701 million or 75 cents a share,  
compared with profits of $258 million or 26 cents a share a year 
earlier. Revenues rose 13 percent, from $13.39 billion to $15.13 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	These figures include a one-time gain of $181 million from a  
federal income tax audit settlement covering 1988-1991 and charges 
of $78 million in the year-ago period to reflect the planned 
termination of the MD-11 jetliner program and late delivery costs 
associated with new-generation 737 aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second-quarter results demonstrate growing momentum and  
confidence,'' said Phil Condit, Boeing chairman and chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our commercial airplanes group is on plan -- delivering  
airplanes and improving margins every day. Boeing delivered 165 
commercial airplanes this quarter -- on time, and with 17 percent 
fewer employees and a 10 percentage point improvement in overtime 
from the highest levels in 1998.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing struggled with production line snarls, delayed deliveries  
and the Asian financial crisis during the past two years. It lost 
$178 million in 1997 and had depressed earnings of $1.1 billion in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's Commercial Airplanes division had second-quarter  
operating income of $435 million, compared with a loss of $178 
million a year ago, when it delivered only 137 planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit said the improvement was principally due to better cost  
control on the new 737 and 777 jetliner programs, more deliveries, 
and lower research and development spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially key was not having to pay for huge amounts of  
overtime and extra people to get airplanes out the factory door, 
Condit told reporters in a telephone conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pure and simple,'' he said, ``it's the number of hours it  
takes to build an airplane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is projecting revenues of $58 billion this year and $48  
billion in 2000. Next year's drop is primarily due to fewer orders 
being placed because of Asia's economic slump, Condit said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, Boeing had profits of $1.17  
billion or $1.24 a share, compared with net earnings of $308 
million or 31 cents a share in 1998. Revenues rose 12 percent, from 
$26.33 billion to $29.52 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Boeing fell 87 1/2 cents to $46.75 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange on the news. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs noted, however, that the stock price had risen by about  
$4 a share in the past week in anticipation of the earnings report, 
and is up about 44 percent for the year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
