<HEADLINE> TV Appearance Leads to Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A mayoral candidate was arrested on an  
outstanding warrant Thursday night when an officer watching TV 
recognized her from a live interview on the evening news, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorothy Joyner, 57, was arrested on a warrant charging her with  
one count of misdemeanor burglary. Details of the warrant were 
unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Joyner, a Republican, is one of the candidates in a field of  
25 running for mayor in this overwhelmingly Democratic city. Her 
name appears as Dorothy Jennings in filing papers. On television 
she identified herself as Dorothy Joyner-Jennings. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer who issued the warrant last year happened to be  
watching the 6:30 p.m. news, said police spokeswoman Angelique 
Cook-Hayes. 
</P>
<P>
	He alerted his supervisors and officers were waiting for Ms.  
Joyner when she left the studios of WBFF-TV in Baltimore. Cameras 
captured her leaving the station in handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	During her appearance on the ``Newsmaker'' segment, Ms. Joyner  
described herself as a churchgoer with 30 years experience in 
education. She also spoke at length about crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that we need to retrain our police officers. Our  
officers need to steer clear of the abrasiveness they project. 
Instead of abrasiveness, what about courtesy? What about manners?'' 
she asked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
