<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Wraps Up N.Y. Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y. (AP) -- Gun control? Yes. Patients'  
rights? Yes. Commuter tax? Um. Well. 
</P>
<P>
	Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has established an exploratory  
committee for a likely U.S. Senate campaign, wrapped up the 
suburban phase of her ``listening tour'' on Wednesday by holding 
forums on two of her favorite subjects, gun violence and health 
care reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	She reiterated her support for strict gun control and for  
changing the way health care is administered, but she did not 
always provide direct answers. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether she supports repeal of a commuter tax on people  
who work in New York City but don't live there, she said: ``The 
real issue here is the high level of taxation. ... It's a fact. 
They did it. The courts have made their ruling on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commuter tax was repealed by the state Legislature.  
</P>
<P>
	Republican New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is also  
exploring a potential Senate run, opposed the tax repeal, saying 
New York City would lose too much money. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani said Mrs. Clinton's lack of a position on the issue  
``tells me she's not a candidate yet. When she becomes a candidate, 
she'll have to answer the question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a forum in Great Neck at the headquarters of the North  
Shore-Long Island Jewish Health System, Mrs. Clinton was asked how 
she would help working Americans who can't afford health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will address that issue,'' Mrs. Clinton responded. ``I will  
keep addressing it. I don't know quite what we're going to do about 
it but I think it's unacceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The questioner, Kathy McIntyre, a self-employed certified public  
accountant, has four children and is a widow. She cannot afford 
health insurance and relies on emergency rooms for medical care. 
</P>
<P>
	But She was not put off by Mrs. Clinton's lack of an easy  
answer. ``I think Mrs. Clinton should be our senator,'' Mrs. 
McIntyre said afterwards. ``I think as the first lady she has been 
thwarted in achieving her health care goals. Too bad she can't run 
for president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton started her day with a discussion on gun violence  
and strongly attacked the gun lobby for blocking an effort to make 
it more difficult for people to buy weapons at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Clinton also made an embarrassing gaffe during the  
forum when addressing a woman whose son was injured in a 1994 
shooting, telling the woman: ``You've really spent a lot of time in 
the years since your son's murder--'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mother, Alice McEnaney, interrupted her and said, ``He  
wasn't murdered. My son's alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank God,'' said Mrs. Clinton. Mrs. McEnaney then indicated  
that her son, Jason, was sitting in the front row. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton had met Mrs. McEnaney, but not Jason, prior to the  
forum. Before the first lady's blunder, Mrs. McEnaney told the 
audience, ``On Dec. 14, 1994, we got a phone call that's every 
parent's nightmare. My son was involved in a hostage-taking at 
SUNY-Albany. He disarmed a gunman, he had been shot in the 
process.'' She did not specifically say he had survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how the error occurred and whether Mrs. Clinton had been  
told beforehand that the young man survived, her committee 
spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said, ``Mrs. Clinton was sharing her 
concern for the mother of a gunshot victim and misspoke. That's 
it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
