<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NEH Grants $2.2M to Save Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Librarians try to save miles of bookshelf  
space by digitally recording the information they contain, but some 
of that information could be lost, the government said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Endowment for the Humanities warned of the possible  
data loss in announcing a $2.2 million grant to Cornell University 
for ``Project Prism,'' to promote ``information integrity in 
digital libraries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are especially concerned that history is literally  
disappearing before our eyes,'' NEH Chairman William R. Ferris said 
in a statement. ``Many historical documents, including founding 
fathers' papers, newspapers, photographs and other documents are 
disintegrating. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of these documents were transferred to digital formats in  
the belief that would preserve them forever. But now we're learning 
that digital formats are very fragile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said there are no common preservation processes for digital  
records, but Project Prism will help develop a strategy that can be 
applied throughout the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Naomi Duchay, a researcher at Cornell, said digital records  
become hard to retrieve if they are preserved on software that has 
become obsolete in the rapidly changing digital world. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system you're using to write your story could be  
superseded in time and it might not be possible to recover the 
text,'' she told a reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	The formats containing the old data might no longer be readable  
by people using today's software and hardware. It's already hard to 
find equipment to read some material digitized in the 1980s, she 
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	As described by NEH, Project Prism would try to ensure that  
information is available when and where people want it, protect 
privacy and property rights and ensure the content of digital 
collections for future generations. 
</P>
<P>
	Project Prism is one of six NEH efforts, in cooperation with  
universities and the National Science Foundation, to computerize 
records and make them readily available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
