<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP, RealNetworks Team on Web News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Associated Press is teaming up with  
RealNetworks Inc. to launch a new service offering audio and video 
news to AP's member newspapers and broadcasters for use on their 
Web sites, the news cooperative announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP already offers audio and video news as part of its  
Internet news service, The Wire, and separately to selected 
newspapers. The new service makes more of this material available 
to the cooperative's members as a separate product. 
</P>
<P>
	Members will be able to purchase some or all of the three parts  
of the new service: regular audio updates on top stories; audio and 
video clips to accompany major stories and live audio and video 
coverage of at least one event per day. 
</P>
<P>
	The audio and video clips will be produced by The AP from its  
radio and television news reports. The service will be distributed 
over the online network of Seattle-based RealNetworks, which is the 
leading provider of streaming audio and video over the Internet. 
Some 60 million people use its RealPlayer software to play audio 
and video content over the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	AP, the world's oldest and largest newsgathering organization,  
is a cooperative of its member newspapers and broadcasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Several AP members will begin using the service this summer,  
including latimes.com, the Web site of the Los Angeles Times, The 
New York Times On the Web, USAToday.com, washingtonpost.com, 
Arizona Central, the Web site of The Arizona Republic, and Tribune 
Interactive, which includes Web sites for the Chicago Tribune, The 
Orlando Sentinel, the Sun-Sentinel of South Florida, the Newport 
News Daily Press and 18 Tribune television stations. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
