<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on dry Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices rose Thursday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for hot, dry weather in 
key growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts for weekend temperatures to rise into the 90s,  
accompanied by little moisture, boosted fears about heat stress to 
young crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of Illinois, Indiana and Ohio already are reporting low  
soil moisture, and prolonged dry weather through next week could 
begin to lead to yield reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybean futures also were boosted by larger than  
expected export demand in the past week, which came as prices fell 
sharply amid concern about bumper production. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 cent to $2.61 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn rose 4 1/4 cents to $2.05 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 
2 cents to $1.11 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 6 1/4 cents to 
$4.27 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .23 cent to 63.42 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .60 cent to 76.65 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .95 cent to 46.90 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
.75 cent to 33.70 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
