<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGraw-Hill Earnings Rise 16 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The McGraw-Hill Cos. reported a 16 percent  
increase in second-quarter earnings Thursday due to gains at 
Business Week, as well as growth in its financial services and 
education businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw-Hill earned $90 million, or 45 cents per share, compared  
to $77.8 million or 39 cents a share in the same period a year ago. 
Revenues rose 5 percent to $922.7 million versus $881.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings were slightly higher than the 44 cents per share  
expected by analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from financial services rose 12 percent thanks to gains  
at the company's Standard &AMP; Poor's division, which publishes 
company information and issues credit ratings. S&AMP;P posted gains 
despite a dropoff in new U.S. bond issues as the company continued 
to expand its business in overseas markets, especially Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ad pages at Business Week increased 8.4 percent in the second  
quarter, reflecting strong advertising demand from the computer and 
communications industries. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw-Hill's educational and professional publishing division  
posted a 5 percent gain in revenues as strong orders from 
elementary and high schools bolstered results. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, McGraw-Hill's profits rose  
17 percent to $114.5 million or 57 cents a share from $98 million, 
or 49 cents a share. Revenues rose 3.4 percent to $1.64 billion 
from $1.58 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McGraw Hill rose 62 1/2 cents to $50.43 3/4 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
