<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doc, Pharmacy Owners Plead Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDDING, Calif. (AP) -- A doctor and two pharmacy owners have  
been charged with murder, accused of dispensing a powerful 
painkiller that resulted in five overdose deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Frank Fisher and pharmacy owners Stephen and Madeline Miller  
entered innocent pleas involving two of the deaths in Shasta County 
Superior Court on Wednesday. They had earlier pleaded innocent to 
the other three deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge has yet to determine if a trial will be held.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the deaths were caused by the wrongful  
prescription of oxycodone, a morphine-like painkiller. The dead 
ranged in age from 19 to 38. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have alleged the Harvard-educated Fisher ran a  
``patient mill,'' prescribing oxycodone and other drugs after only 
cursory examinations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Millers are accused of filling most of Fisher's  
prescriptions at their Shasta Pharmacy in Redding in exchange for 
kickbacks from him. 
</P>
<P>
	The three also face fraud charges in connection with more than  
$2 million in medical billings. They have remained jailed on 
multimillion-dollar bails since their Feb. 18 arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those raising money for Fisher's legal defense is Robert  
Stevens. His wife, Tamara Stevens, is among the five who died. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher has said he treated many poor patients with chronic pain  
who were snubbed by other doctors, and has said he wrote large 
prescriptions to ensure they could ease their suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	Treating patients in extreme pain involves risk, Fisher told The  
Sacramento Bee earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the attorney general's office understands the  
issue of chronic pain or how you treat it,'' he said. ``I feel like 
I'm being punished for behaving with good conscience and doing the 
right thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 23:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners' New Ballpark Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Safe opened for business Thursday, with the  
Seattle Mariners uncertain whether they can keep Ken Griffey Jr. 
and Alex Rodriguez locked up. 
</P>
<P>
	After 22 1/2 seasons in the climate-controlled Kingdome, the  
Mariners moved into Safeco Field, which has a retractable roof but 
no heating or air conditioning. At $517 million, it is the most 
expensive baseball stadium ever. 
</P>
<P>
	While the team wants the Public Facilities District that built  
the ballpark to pay for $100 million in overruns, some fans didn't 
concern themselves with the cost. The government agreed to pay $372 
million of the original $417 million estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorin Sandretzky, a 33-year-old bodyguard from suburban Burien,  
made his feelings clear as he sat in the main concourse, holding 
high a sign that read: ``Whoever Paid for It, Thanks!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's beautiful, it's 100 percent state of the art,'' he said.  
``For anybody that's complaining, I say come down here and look at 
what their money did. This is what baseball should be. I've never 
seen so many smiles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The frustrating 3-2 loss to the San Diego Padres -- caused mainly  
by Jose Mesa's four walks in the ninth inning -- was almost an 
afterthought as the Mariners celebrated the move to Safeco Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Mariners Alvin Davis, Harold Reynolds and Ruppert Jones  
participated in a pregame ceremony honoring the team's past. 
Mariners announcer Dave Niehaus, who has been with the team since 
its 1977 inception, threw out the ceremonial first pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	And fans explored the ballpark, many in awe of its technological  
marvels -- particularly the retractable roof that covers the stadium 
like an umbrella. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a curtain rising on a new act, the 22-million-pound roof  
opened an hour before Seattle played the Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time a baseball game in Seattle was played outside a  
dome was in 1969, when the Pilots played at Sick's Stadium. After 
one season, the expansion team moved to Milwaukee and became the 
Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners say the 47,000-seat stadium, erected next to its  
utilitarian predecessor, will ensure the future of baseball in the 
Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they may not be able to afford both the stadium and the  
high cost of keeping Griffey and Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are eligible for free agency after the 2000 season, and it  
may cost $400 million or more to keep them. Rodriguez's agent, 
Scott Boras, is expected to seek a 10-year deal averaging $20 
million per season or more. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans, who angst daily about the future of their superstars, set  
aside their worries for the night. They cheered as the roof opened 
to the score from the movie ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' performed by 
The Seattle Symphony Orchestra on the other side of the 
center-field wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is awesome. It's far beyond what I thought it would be,''  
John Bender, who drove by the stadium several days a week in the 
past month to monitor its progress. ``Who cares about the cost 
overruns?'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Alex Deccio could hardly contain his glee as he took  
his seat in the field-level section behind home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican was among the two-dozen Eastern Washington  
legislators who counter-balanced the opposition of many 
Seattle-area lawmakers and helped win approval of Safeco Field's 
financing package during the Mariners' 1995 playoff run. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it wasn't for Eastern Washington folks, this place wouldn't  
be here!'' he exclaimed. 
</P>
<P>
	Deccio shrugged off the Mariners' request for more money after  
pledging to cover all overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the engineering marvel that this is, I'm surprised they  
didn't go over more,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 19:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
