<DOCNO> APW19990715.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 10:08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Part of Energy Dept. Budget Blocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In another fallout over allegations of Chinese  
espionage, a House subcommittee today directed that $1 billion of 
the Energy Department's budget be withheld until Congress 
reorganizes the department's nuclear weapons programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ron Packard, R-Calif., chairman of the House Appropriations  
subcommittee on energy and water, said reforms to improve nuclear 
weapons security were essential before the $1 billion in DOE 
operating funds will be reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee action was taken as the panel approved the  
fiscal 2000 energy and water appropriations bill. The legislation 
will be considered by the full House in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has a budget of about $18 billion, but  
most of that goes to contractors. The $1 billion withheld for DOE 
operations represents a large part of the department's direct, 
noncontractor spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is to be withheld until Congress restructures the  
department's national security programs or establishes an 
independent agency to oversee and manage their operations, Packard 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been growing sentiment among lawmakers to create a  
largely autonomous agency within the Energy Department responsible 
for nuclear weapons programs, including operation of the three 
nuclear weapons labs and security. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has said he is willing to  
accept in theory creation of a semiautonomous agency as long as 
it's clear the energy secretary has authority over the agency. He 
also wants security and counterintelligence functions to be 
departmentwide and not confined to the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	A largely Republican proposal gaining momentum in the Senate  
would create a semiautonomous agency, but insulate it more from the 
rest of the department than what Richardson has been willing to 
accept. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, some Republican members of the House, including  
Packard, would prefer to have the nuclear programs taken away from 
the Energy Department altogether, and create a totally independent 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	But House members are divided on the issue.  
</P>
<P>
	Seven House committee and subcommittee chairmen wrote a letter  
to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., this week urging him to 
oppose any effort to restructure the Energy Department without 
further hearings and review. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Tom Bliley, R-Va., the Commerce Committee chairman, and F.  
James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., the Science Committee chairman, 
warned against trying to make ``quick fixes'' at the Energy 
Department that could harm science research programs and hinder 
safety and environmental protection at the weapons facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Launches Digital Fingerprinting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Local police can now take a single fingerprint  
from a suspect at a roadside arrest and find out in minutes from a 
new FBI computerized national crime data system whether that person 
is wanted, rather than waiting the hours, days or longer that the 
old FBI system took. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, the FBI launched its new National Crime Information  
Center 2000 (NCIC 2000), replacing the old NCIC computer network 
that linked the bureau to state and local police. 
</P>
<P>
	Among a series of improvements, the new system has the ability  
to automatically process fingerprints and mugshots. It also 
contains the old NCIC system's lists of wanted people, criminal 
histories, missing and deported people, stolen guns, vehicles, 
license plates, stocks, boats and other articles. 
</P>
<P>
	But the old NCIC didn't even handle fingerprints or mugshots.  
Local police had to mail or fax 10-finger print sets to the FBI, 
which checked them by hand against its 39 million sets of 
fingerprints and answered by mail, fax or, in urgent cases, by 
telephone whether there was a match. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, a police officer in a station or even in a squad car in the  
field can put a suspect's index finger into a small reader that 
transmits the print by radio to FBI NCIC 2000 computers in 
Clarksburg, W. Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, the NCIC 2000 computer -- automatically without  
any action by FBI employees -- checks the single print against 
250,000 fingerprints in the FBI's file of fugitives and wanted 
persons. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer pops out in minutes. If the print identifies the  
suspect as someone who is wanted, the NCIC 2000 computer not only 
relays the result to local police but also sends a mugshot of the 
wanted person to a computer screen or printer in the local police 
station or even in the squad car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that NCIC 2000 will foster a revolution in law  
enforcement,'' FBI Director Louis J. Freeh said Thursday. 
Previously, ``a wanted person had sometimes already been released 
from custody before the more time-consuming record systems produced 
the needed information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few state or local police agencies already have the equipment  
needed to take full advantage of the new system, including the New 
Jersey and Michigan state police, FBI spokesman Steve Fischer said. 
``We are looking to have most of the law enforcement agencies in 
the country on board within three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI will provide the software free, but the local agencies  
have to buy their own laptop computers, fingerprint scanners and 
printers. 
</P>
<P>
	NCIC 2000 cost $183.2 million and arrived on duty four years  
later than originally planned. 
</P>
<P>
	And, last Sunday's startup halted the FBI's computerized  
background checks of gun buyers for more than 24 hours. Since then, 
FBI personnel have been working to clear the backlog of checks on 
prospective gun owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other new capabilities, NCIC 2000 can search its files  
for: 
</P>
<P>
	--All variations of a name, such Jeff, Geoff or Jeffrey.  
</P>
<P>
	--Identifying marks like scars, tattoos and photos of  
automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	--Lists of sexual offenders, people on probation or parole, or  
federal prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	It can also link files: A query on a stolen vehicle will also  
return information on any stolen guns found in that vehicle. And it 
stores five days worth of queries and can report whether police in 
other jurisdictions are looking for the same people or property. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 28, Fischer said, the FBI's Clarksburg records center  
will take another step into the future. The old hand searches of 
10-fingerprint sets for matches in the 39 million-print files will 
become computerized with the launch of the Integrated Automated 
Fingerprint Identification System. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Wants Boycott of S. Carolina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The NAACP is supporting a tourism boycott  
of South Carolina because the state flies the Confederate flag at 
the Statehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP voted Thursday at its national convention in New York  
to boycott the state at the urging of the South Carolina chapter. 
The resolution still must be ratified by the national board in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourism is a top industry in South Carolina and visitors spent  
$6.8 billion in the state last year, according to state figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're asking African-Americans and others who believe in  
fairness to consider relocating their family reunions, conventions, 
church groups and other meetings outside of the state as long as 
the Confederate flag is flown over the state Capitol,'' said James 
Gallman, president of the South Carolina chapter of the National 
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina is the only state that flies the flag over its  
Statehouse. Mississippi and Georgia incorporate the rebel flag in 
their state flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges supports a compromise to take down  
the flag and place it near a Confederate memorial on the Capitol 
grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, the political will to enact such a compromise does  
not exist today in the South Carolina Legislature,'' the 
vacationing Hodges said in a statement released by his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers in 1995 passed a law giving the Legislature sole power  
to remove the flag. 
</P>
<P>
	The flag was raised over the Statehouse in 1962 to commemorate  
the Civil War's centennial. Opponents say it is an offensive 
reminder of slavery. Supporters say it celebrates the state's 
heritage and the sacrifice of South Carolinians during the war. 
</P>
<P>
	A boycott likely wouldn't have an immediate effect on the state,  
said tourism department spokesman Lou Fontana. Less than 5 percent 
of blacks who vacationed in South Carolina attended conventions, 
which usually are planned several years in advance, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Religion Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today moved to restore legal  
assurances that people can practice their religious beliefs without 
undue government interference. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Religious Liberty Protection Act,'' which passed 306-118,  
is aimed at better protecting religious practices in such instances 
as schools telling Jewish boys they can't wear yarmulkes while 
playing basketball or Muslim firefighters being told they can't 
grow beards. 
</P>
<P>
	Police now can arrest a Catholic priest for serving communion to  
minors and violate Orthodox Jewish laws by carrying out autopsies, 
said Rep. Sue Myrick, R-N.C. ``This is wrong and it has to be 
changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The measure declares that state and local governments can only  
take actions that impose a ``substantial burden'' on a person's or 
group's religious practices if they can prove a ``compelling 
governmental interest.'' The full Senate has yet to consider it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day Americans are wrongfully denied an opportunity to  
practice their religion according to the dictates of conscience,'' 
said Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., a chief sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is supported by a broad range of religious and civil  
rights groups ranging from the Christian Coalition to the Peyote 
Way Church of God. The Clinton administration, in a statement, said 
it strongly supports the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	But the measure is opposed by civil rights groups worried that  
landlords could use the religious defense to discriminate against 
potential tenants and conservatives who see it as federal 
encroachment on state and local rights. The NAACP Legal Defense and 
Education Fund said Wednesday it was concerned the act would be 
used against minorities seeking protection from discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters cited such cases as a woman denied employment because  
her faith prevented her from taking a loyalty oath, a Colorado 
county that tried to limit the operating hours of a church in the 
same way it did commercial facilities and coroners trying to carry 
out autopsies over the religious objections of family members. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is a result of a decade of conflict between Congress  
and the courts. In 1990 the Supreme Court ruled that even 
relatively minor laws and regulations could be used to deny some 
religious practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress responded in 1993 by passing a measure that applied the  
compelling governmental interest principle in religious practice 
cases, but in 1997 the Supreme Court struck down that law, saying 
Congress had exceeded its constitutional authority. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bill tries to conform to the Constitution by saying its  
provisions apply only to federally funded state and local programs 
or issues involving interstate commerce. It also applies to land 
use regulations that discriminate against houses of worship. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Farris, president of the Home School Legal Defense  
Association and head of the group that wrote the 1993 bill, said he 
is against the current measure. He said it would help only big and 
powerful religious groups and that the courts would again declare 
it unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	Farris said use of the interstate commerce provision would only  
extend federal controls over religious issues. ``We think that the 
rope being used to pull religious freedom out of the ditch today is 
the rope that will hang us in the future,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Anders, legislative counsel of the American Civil  
Liberties Union, which also supported the 1993 bill, said it 
opposes the new measure because of several recent court cases in 
which landlords have used religious arguments to discriminate 
against would-be tenants. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal shield, he said, was being ``used as a sword to  
violate people's civil rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., offered an amendment that would bar  
large property owners and businesses from discriminating against 
gays, the disabled or minorities on religious grounds. It was 
defeated 234-190. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1691.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
