<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS All-Stars Helped by Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Soccer's next big thing, the MLS All-Star game,  
will kick off in the afterglow of the U.S. women's dramatic World 
Cup victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The men don't have much choice but to ride along on the women's  
shirttails. Jealous? No. Grateful? Yes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I say that definitely people might be more aware of the game  
because of the women, and we're all pretty thankful for that,'' 
said Matt Jordan of the Dallas Burn, the backup goalie for the 
Eastern Conference in Saturday's game. ``We're all sort of jumping 
on their boat, their bandwagon, so to speak. So it's a very 
positive situation for all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roll a soccer ball on a field these days and it's impossible not  
to talk about the women, who won the final over China on Brandi 
Chastain's penalty kick last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Especially in the current climate, with the wonderful  
performance by the women, soccer's on everyone's mind,'' Alexi 
Lalas, the goateed star of the Kansas City Wizards, said before a 
MLS-sponsored celebrity game Wednesday night. ``I think that it's a 
wonderful time to celebrate not just the MLS, but soccer in 
general.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lalas attended two women's games and watched the final on TV.  
He's fielded as many questions about the women as the MLS, but 
hasn't tired of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all soccer and it's all good. They deserve everything  
they're getting. Now let's see what they do with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's the catch. After the All-Star game, the men return to  
their league. There's no such thing for women. 
</P>
<P>
	Elena George, one of dozens of screaming teenagers who were at  
the celebrity game, offered a suggestion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the women are just as good. I think they should  
definitely have a men and women matchup thing, the best women 
versus the best men. And they should have a women's professional 
league. That would really influence girls. 
</P>
<P>
	``The women got everybody pumped up to go watch soccer because  
they, like, won,'' said George, who's 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The women have a supporter in none other than pro wrestler Ken  
Shamrock, the self-professed ``World's Most Dangerous Man'' who was 
a huge hit in the celebrity game and looked downright civilized in 
a soccer uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the women winning the soccer tournament, it just goes to  
show you how women's sports have moved up and are getting exposure 
like they should,'' Shamrock said. ``You saw it was a sellout there 
(at the Rose Bowl). Most men's soccer games don't get that unless 
it's Brazil or Argentina or something like that. So the women have 
absolutely opened some eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Newman has a unique perspective. Not only is she a soccer  
mom, but her husband, Guy, is an assistant coach with the Wizards 
who watched as much of the women's tournament as possible. Her 
father-in-law, Ron Newman, coached the now-defunct San Diego 
Sockers to 10 indoor titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that women's soccer is any type of threat to the  
men's league at this point, but I think it gives women and girls 
something to strive for and I think it brings an awareness,'' 
Newman said. ``It's not just a kid's sport anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newman's daughters, Gabby, 6, and Brittany, 9, wore Mia Hamm  
jerseys. 
</P>
<P>
	``That got voted over the Kansas City Wizards jersey,'' Newman  
said. ``She's worn that shirt for about a week straight. I can't 
get it off her,'' Newman said, pointing to Gabby. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's New England Revolution goalie Walter Zenga, who  
can't figure out all the talk about the women's team. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Europe, they don't care about the women's soccer,'' said  
Zenga, an Italian. ``Everywhere it is a different mentality, no? I 
think it is just a little strange for one team to be on top of the 
world and they don't have a league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It remains to be seen if the women's success will help boost  
ticket sales for Saturday's game, which for the second straight 
year is being played in a non-MLS city. League officials would be 
happy to sell 30,000 tickets at 70,000-seat Qualcomm Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	A game between Chivas of Mexico and Chile's Universidad Catolica  
will follow, and officials hope for strong same-day ticket sales to 
fans from Tijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully this sport has made friends over the course of the  
last three weeks,'' MLS commissioner Doug Logan said. ``If so, that 
would be a good thing for Major League Soccer.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
