<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Body Probes Interbrew Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Commission investigators have  
raided the offices of the brewer Interbrew in an effort to 
determine if it is using anti-competitive tactics to muscle out 
rivals in the Belgian market. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission spokesman Stephen Rating said Thursday the agency is  
investigating whether Interbrew is offering pubs rewards for 
stocking its beers and excluding others, requiring wholesalers to 
carry all its beers and exclude other brewers, and cutting prices 
to drive out competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspectors representing acting E.U. Commissioner for Competition  
Karel van Miert visited several Interbrew offices Tuesday and 
Wednesday and took documents with them, the company confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The inquiry is limited to the Belgian market, said Rating.  
</P>
<P>
	The Leuven-based company has a 60 percent market share in  
Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Under European Union competition rules, companies could be fined  
up to 10 percent of their annual sales if found to be using 
anti-competitive practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission runs the day-to-day affairs of the 15-nation  
union, proposes EU law and enforces its implementation across 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, it imposed $6.8 million in fines against British  
Airways on Wednesday for allegedly paying British travel agents to 
direct travelers onto its flights. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling was the result of a two-year inquiry triggered by  
two formal complaints from British Airways' archrival, Virgin 
Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Virgin accused British Airways of offering travel agents extra  
commissions if they could demonstrate that its ticket sales were 
going up compared to rival carriers, particularly when selling to 
corporate clients. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
