<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Chief Reaffirms Euro Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- The chief banker of the 11-nation euro zone  
reaffirmed his faith in the sinking European currency and hinted at 
higher interest rates Thursday, sparking a small rally just as 
crisp, new euro banknotes start rolling off printing presses around 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Wim Duisenberg, president of the European Central Bank,  
emphasized that improvement in the European economy, along with the 
bank's anti-inflation stance, should help the euro regain some of 
the 12 percent in value it has lost against the dollar since its 
Jan. 1 introduction. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's clear potential for a stronger (euro)'', Duisenberg  
said after the regular monthly meeting of the bank, which sets 
monetary policy for the nations that adopted the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	``Modest'' signs of recovery ``appear to confirm the outlook for  
a continued improvement in the course of this year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of Duisenberg's comments, the euro gained about half  
a cent, finishing in London at $1.0244. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts attributed the euro's rise to a hint from Duisenberg  
that the bank's next move for interest rates -- when it comes -- will 
be to raise them. Higher rates increase demand for a currency as 
investors seek better returns compared with other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank council left its key interest rates unchanged Thursday,  
as widely expected, and no further changes are expected this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But asked whether the bank was moving toward a bias in favor of  
tightening monetary policy -- meaning raising rates -- Duisenberg 
said ``you could see a tightening bias slightly creeping in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much the euro's weakness has been attributed to the booming  
economy in the United States and the resulting higher interest 
rates, which make investments in dollars more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve in Washington this month raised its key rate  
to 5 percent to keep inflation under control. The European Central 
Bank's last action was to cut rates to 2.5 percent in April to help 
spur Europe's sluggish economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	While governments and corporations use the euro for financial  
transactions, bills and coins won't enter circulation until the 
euro becomes legal tender on Jan. 1, 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	To prepare for that, mints in Belgium, Germany, Italy,  
Netherlands and Spain this month began or will soon begin printing 
euro banknotes, the bank announced. Plants in other countries will 
start production in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen billion euro notes will be printed in denominations of  
5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200 and 500 euros. The designs -- bridges, 
gateways and windows in styles ranging from classical to modern -- 
are common across the EU. 
</P>
<P>
	Minting of the eight different euro coins -- 1, 2, 5, 10, 20 and  
50 cents and 1- and 2-euros -- began in May 1998 and is proceeding 
on schedule, the bank said. Some 448 million, 8 percent of the 
total to be put into circulation, have already been minted. 
</P>
<P>
	The design on one side is standard, while the reverse has the  
profile of a monarch or national symbol. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
