<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb Taking Tax Deduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. says a $17 million  
pretax loss on the sale of its Miracle Ear hearing aid business 
will be offset by a tax deduction. 
</P>
<P>
	The eye-care company erroneously reported Monday that the loss  
would be covered by gains from the recent sale of its sunglass 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the company said the loss from the sale will be offset  
by a benefit from a tax deduction recorded in the fourth quarter of 
1998 when Bausch &AMP; Lomb reduced the value of the hearing aid 
business on its books. The tax deduction could not be taken until 
the business was sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The after-tax gain on the Miracle Ear sale will be $12 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Miracle Ear, headquartered in Golden Valley, Minn., makes and  
sells hearing aids and related products. It is being sold to 
Amplifon SpA of Italy, a leading distributor and retailer of 
hearing aids in Europe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
