<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras To Sit Out Davis Cup Singles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Pete Sampras, the No. 3 singles player  
in the world, will play only doubles for the United States in its 
Davis Cup quarterfinal against Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's draw for the matches Friday through Sunday set the  
lineup, which cannot be changed except in case of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. captain Tom Gullikson had said all along that he would not  
use Sampras for singles, even though the team would be stronger 
that way. Sampras had joined the team late and expressed concern 
about upsetting the chemistry. 
</P>
<P>
	But few expected that Gullikson's comments were anything more  
than gamesmanship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't expect him to come all this way to sit on the  
sidelines and watch,'' Australian foe Patrick Rafter said this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sampras won't watch. He'll play doubles with Alex O'Brien on  
Saturday against Sandon Stolle and Mark Woodforde. The singles 
matches Friday will be Todd Martin against Lleyton Hewitt and Jim 
Courier against Patrick Rafter. 
</P>
<P>
	The singles matchups will be reversed on Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	The quarterfinal tie is being played at the Longwood Cricket  
club to commemorate the Davis Cup centennial. The first matches 
were played here in 1900 after founder Dwight Davis purchased the 
trophy and issued a challenge to the international tennis 
community. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
