<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- The United Church of Christ has  
restructured its ministries, but new officers say the changes won't 
affect the liberal church's mission to embrace diversity and preach 
tolerance of differences among its 1.4 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1957, about 600 people have had seats on 10 administrative  
boards. Now there will be about 200 people on four boards called 
ministries, according to Andy Lang, a church spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most significant change ... is the very existence of a  
collegium of offices who together will look at the whole ministry 
of the church,'' said Dale L. Bishop, executive minister of Wider 
Church Ministries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. John H. Thomas was elected general minister and  
president. Edith A. Guffey was elected associate general minister. 
Executive ministers in addition to Bishop are the Rev. Jose A. 
``Joe'' Malayang, Local Church Ministries, and Bernice Powell 
Jackson, Justice and Witness Ministries. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *United Methodists slow losses    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Membership in the United Methodist  
Church dropped by 38,477 last year, the smallest decline since a 
gradual erosion began three decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Membership now stands at 8.4 million, United Methodist News  
Service reported, down from 11 million when the denomination was 
formed in a two-way merger in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Methodist Church is America's third-biggest  
denomination, behind the Roman Catholic Church and Southern Baptist 
Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Methodists' annual membership losses varied from 42,761 to  
76,568 in the period from 1989 to 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
