<P>
 *Some priests fly on pastoral duty    	
</P>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Some 50 Roman Catholics, members of the  
National Association of Priest Pilots, flew into Dayton for their 
annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them was the Rev. Jim Kelley, who ministers to 20 Alaskan  
villages and part of the Aleutian Islands. He drops in on each 
village twice a month, landing in fields cleared by locals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether there's one Catholic there or 20 or 50 or 100, I  
stop,'' the 70-year-old pilot-priest said. 
</P>
<P>
	The association was founded in 1964 by two Kentucky priests to  
promote the use of the airplane in evangelical and missionary work. 
Most of its 140 members fly single-engine Pipers or Cessnas. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, the pilots make a financial contribution to someone  
who uses a plane in missionary work, according to the Rev. Mel 
Hemann of Cedar Falls, Iowa. This year, it goes to a priest in the 
Congo, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley, a former Navy chaplain, began flying just after he was  
ordained. He usually flies solo, but he doesn't feel alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``God's there,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
