<DOCNO> APW19990715.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Live-Fire Drills To Go On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The death of a civilian at a Navy missile  
range in Puerto Rico is ``extremely regrettable,'' but live-fire 
training exercises there must continue, Navy Secretary Richard 
Danzig said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The target range on the island of Vieques is uniquely situated  
for the full gamut of Navy and Marine training operations -- far 
superior to 18 alternative sites studied by the Navy since the 
accident, Danzig said at a briefing for reporters at the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a national security standpoint, this is an important and  
not replaceable site,'' Danzig said as he presented a Navy study 
that backs continued use of the range. 
</P>
<P>
	David Sanes Rodriguez, a security guard who worked for the Navy,  
was killed April 19, when two 500-pound bombs dropped by a Navy 
FA-18 fighter-bomber missed their target by 1 1/2 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his death, a small band of protesters has occupied a  
scrubby, pockmarked outcrop of the Vieques range, which is littered 
with dozens of unexploded bombs, artillery shells and grenades. The 
Navy has let the protesters stay, hoping to avoid arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico wants the Navy to stop shelling the 51-square-mile  
island, where 9,000 people live. The Navy controls about two-thirds 
of the island, which lies eight miles east of the main island of 
Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello was the first witness last week  
before a special four-member Pentagon commission examining the 
Navy's use of the island. Rossello's spokesman, Pedro Rosario 
Urdaz, said Thursday that Puerto Rico will continue its efforts to 
get the Navy out of Vieques. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ( the Navy report's conclusion) was predictable, and it's  
clear that our government is not in agreement with that position,'' 
he said. ``The governor has complete faith that the public policy 
of the government of Puerto Rico will prevail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Navy officials are to present the sea service's position to the  
special commission on July 23. The commission's recommendations to 
Defense Secretary William Cohen are due in six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Danzig and the senior Navy and Marine officers who prepared the  
study stressed no civilian has been killed around the range in 
about 50 years of training operations at Vieques. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we had an extremely regrettable (accident) on the  
range, it was on the range and it was a Navy employee,'' Danzig 
said. ``That is, in my standpoint, an important reassurance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the island ``will not put up with one more bullet,'' said  
Alba Encarnacion, director of Vieques Protests, an anti-Navy group 
in Vieques. ``These poor people are not going to continue carrying 
the entire weight of the national defense. We have given 60 years 
and we will give no more. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the people of the Navy were objective people and conscious  
of the damage that they have done to the island of Vieques they 
would leave. ... There have to be hundreds and hundreds of 
uninhabited islands in the world, but this has turned into a matter 
of pride for them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990715.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gillette Earnings Drop 19 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Shaving giant Gillette Co. blamed overseas  
troubles for a 19 percent drop in second-quarter earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also makes Duracell batteries, saw net income  
drop to $300 million, or 26 cents a share from $372 million, or 33 
cents a share in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the three-month period ending June 30 were $2.41  
billion, a 4 percent increase from the $2.33 billion in sales from 
the second quarter of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said sales would have climbed 9 percent had it not  
been for adverse exchange rates and the divestiture of a cosmetics 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Everett Howe, Gillette's vice president for investor relations,  
called the international markets where Gillette does about 
two-thirds of its business a ``problem area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But we're starting to see what I would call a progressive  
improvement around the world,'' he said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Howe also said increased marketing and advertising costs for new  
shaving products and batteries contributed to the earnings drop. 
</P>
<P>
	The report matched the expectations of analysts surveyed by  
First Call Corp., but last month Gillette warned of a sharp 
earnings drop. At the time, Wall Street had been predicting 
earnings of 29 cents-per-share. 
</P>
<P>
	Long known as a steady moneymaker for blue-chip investors,  
Gillette announced in September it would lay off 4,700 employees 
worldwide, or 11 percent of its work force. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings announcement was made after the close of the market  
Thursday. Gillette's stock closed at $44.75 on the New York Stock 
Exchange, up $1.25. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
