<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Appoints Assistant to President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- David H. Tomlin has been appointed assistant to  
the president of The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Louis D. Boccardi, president and chief executive officer of the  
news cooperative, announced Thursday that Tomlin would succeed 
Kelly Tunney, who was named assistant to the president and director 
of corporate communications earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomlin, currently a general executive in the AP's Newspaper  
Membership department, joined the AP as a newsman in Columbus, 
Ohio, in 1970. He later worked in the Raleigh, N.C., and Pittsburgh 
bureaus before being named chief of bureau for South Carolina in 
1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years later he moved to Des Moines, Iowa, as chief of  
bureau for Iowa and Nebraska. In 1988 he transferred to AP 
headquarters in New York, where he has held a variety of executive 
assignments. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomlin, 53, has also been a reporter and editor at the Newport  
News, Va., Daily Press, and the San Antonio Express-News. A native 
of Providence, R.I., he holds bachelor's and master's degrees in 
international relations from Johns Hopkins University and its 
School for Advanced International Studies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
