<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers Postpone Game After Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE, Wis. (AP) -- The Milwaukee Brewers postponed their  
game tonight in a gesture of respect to three workers who died when 
a huge crane collapsed while handling a portion of the roof for the 
team's new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Five others were injured Wednesday afternoon when the crane  
broke in half as it lifted the 400-ton load. It crumbled into the 
partially completed stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The 567-foot crane, nicknamed ``Big Blue,'' was lowering a piece  
of Miller Park's $400 million retractable roof into place. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like two bombs going off,'' said Gary Craig, who lives  
nearby. ``When I went outside I looked around and saw the 
helicopters hovering over the stadium, and I could see that the 
crane was gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The names of thee victims were not released. Only one of the  
injured -- the 64-year-old crane operator who fell up to 30 feet -- 
remained hospitalized today. He was listed in stable condition with 
a broken hip and broken shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers used used dogs and searchlights to search the rubble  
for any other victims until late Wednesday, but none were found, 
Deputy Fire Chief Gerald Frank said. No one known to be at the site 
was unaccounted for, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the cause of the accident has not been determined, winds  
were gusting to 26 mph at the time the crane fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers, who play in adjacent Milwaukee County Stadium and  
will move to Miller Park, postponed their scheduled game against 
the Kansas City Royals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a game, baseball,'' Mayor John Norquist said. ``What  
happened today was death, and that's horrible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Fleming, a mayoral spokesman, said the accident caused  
significant damage to the 43,000-seat stadium, scheduled to open 
next season. He said he did not know how long it would set the 
project back. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane, built by Neil F. Lampson Inc. of Kennewick, Wash., is  
the largest in North America and one of four of its size in the 
world, a designer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, several Miller Park workers were injured when a  
steel girder being lowered into position collided with an aerial 
basket. On May 10, a worker was hospitalized for a week after 
falling 60 feet from the roof. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
