<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Earnings Drop 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. reported Thursday its  
second-quarter earnings fell 21 percent as lingering economic 
problems and the discovery of contaminated Coke products in Europe 
depressed the soft drink maker's sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings report, which met Wall Street's expectations,  
closed out a difficult quarter for Coke. But analysts noted that 
the company nonetheless made nearly $1 billion in the three months 
ending June 30 and said the Coke brand is still a world power. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should all be so lucky to have Coke's problems,'' said John  
Sicher, editor-publisher of Beverage Digest in Greenwich, Conn. 
``And as economic conditions in many of these markets improve, 
there is no doubt in my mind that Coke will return to healthy 
growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the three months came to $942 million, or 38  
cents per share, down from $1.19 billion, or 48 cents per share, in 
the same quarter a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors responded positively, boosting Coke's stock price  
$2.12 1/2 to $64 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's really going on is that people are beginning to look  
ahead,'' said Skip Carpenter, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; 
Jenrette in New York. ``Clearly, the business was hit hard ... but 
the stock market tends to look a year off, and the markets are 
starting to stabilize and the company is poised to be in a stronger 
position than ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola's quarterly revenue rose to $5.38 billion, up 4  
percent from $5.15 billion a year earlier, even though worldwide 
unit case volume -- a standard industry measure representing 24 
eight-ounce servings -- dropped 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The revenue figures are actually higher than expected, and  
that is pleasing,'' said Bank of America Securities analyst David 
Goldman. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke had earlier warned that sales would be off during the  
quarter because of continuing economic problems overseas. 
Thursday's report said that while second-quarter unit case volume 
declined 2 percent in the Middle and Far East, economic conditions 
appear to have leveled off or shown improvement in many parts of 
the region. 
</P>
<P>
	In Latin America, case volume was even with year-earlier  
numbers. Case volume fell 1 percent in both North America and 
Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke also attributed the drop in earnings to the withdrawal of  
its products from markets in Belgium and France after hundreds of 
people complained of illness from drinking its beverages. Coke 
recalled its products in those countries and faced restrictions on 
sales elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also recalled nearly 8 million bottles of its  
beverages after a consumer in Poland discovered mold in a bottle of 
Bonaqa mineral water. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been criticized for a slow response to the  
contamination in Europe. Coke took out newspaper ads to apologize 
and chairman and chief executive officer M. Douglas Ivester went to 
Europe to reassure customers. On Friday, the company planned to 
give away free products in Belgian supermarkets. 
</P>
<P>
	The apologies continued in Thursday's earnings announcement,  
with Ivester saying, ``the Coca-Cola system is diligently working 
to rebuild the trust of our customers and consumers, and we remain 
very optimistic about the future of our business in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ivester and several Coke executives plan a trip to New York next  
week to meet with investors and stock analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company is still very profitable, very strong and a very  
sound organization,'' Carpenter said. ``And it has never been in a 
stronger strategic and competitive standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, Coca-Cola's net income was  
$1.69 billion, or 68 cents per share, down 18 percent from $2.05 
billion, or 82 cents per share, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month revenues were up 2 percent from $9.6 billion last year  
to $9.8 billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
